<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugAgentSlain     08-10 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Places Defendant at Scene of Drug Agent Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness testifying Wednesday at the trial
of men charged in the torture-murder of drug enforcement agent
Enrique Camarena testified that he saw one of the defendants at the
scene of the killing.
   George Gomez Espana Gonzalez, who cut a plea bargain with the
government, testified that he picked up Rene Verdugo Urquidez at
the villa of a Mexican drug kingpin in Guadalajara, Mexico, during
the time Camarena was held there.
   Gonzalez, a real estate salesman, said he drove his boss to the
home of Rafael Caro Quintero on either Feb. 7 or Feb. 8, 1985.
   Camarena was abducted Feb. 7, 1985, from outside the U.S.
consulate in Guadalajara. The government says he ws taken to Caro's
house where he was tortured and killed during a 24-hour period.
   Gonzalez said he waited in the kitchen of the villa where he saw
several semi-automatic weapons and heard Caro talking with a group
of men in the back yard.
   When he departed , he said, Verdugo hitched a ride, bringing
with him a man he referred to as ``Commandante.''
   He said Verdugo appeared tired. He added that he needed some
sleep and spoke of having solved a problem with the help of the
commandante.
   In a tape recording of Camarena's torture and inquisition, one
of his interrogators is referred to as ``Commandante.''
   Gonzalez said he met Verdugo once before in 1984 in connection
with a financial transaction in which a suitcase full of about $1
million in cash from Caro, was transported to San Diego for deposit
in a bank.
   Verdugo's role in the money laundering transaction was unclear
other than that he was present.
   Gonzalez' testimony was interrupted frequently by defense
objections that it constituted hearsay. His comment that the $1
million came from Caro ultimately was stricken from the court
record.
   Gonzalez told jurors he struck a plea bargain with the
government to testify in the trial to avoid going to prison for
making false statements about the importation of money, the $1
million, and offering a bribe to a federal officer.
   Verdugo, 36, and Raul Lopez Alvarez,28, are charged with the
torture murder of Camarena, whose body was found buried at a remote
Mexican ranch along with that of his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar.
Both had been severely beaten and Camarena's skull was crushed.
   The government alleges that Caro,33, head of a powerful drug
cartel, orchestrated the killings. He was charged in Mexico and is
being tried there along with other defendants.
   A third defendant in the Los Angeles federal court trial, Jesus
Felix Gutierrez, 38, is charged with helping Caro flee Mexico after
Camarena's killing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
