<DOCNO> AP880810-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-APArts:CzechoslovakianArt     08-10 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Czechoslovakian Art,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Freewheeling Exhibit First in Prague Since 1969</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IVA DRAPALOVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Glasnost'' has come _ or
returned _ to Czechoslovakian art with the first freewheeling
exhibit by hundreds of artists held in Prague since 1969.
   Twenty-five thousand people filed past more than 2,700 works by
882 artists in the first two weeks of the ``Prague salon'' staged
at a city stadium and in the Park of Culture and Recreation.
   Following demands for such a show at a meeting last year of the
state-run Union of Artists, the salon is free of the rigid
restrictions imposed on most art exhibits since the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms of 1968 were crushed.
   Picking up on a tradition started with a salon in 1968 but
abandoned after 1969, works are shown in alphabetical order. Each
artist gets the same space, regardless of rank, and is free to fill
it with any work completed in the last five years.
   The result is a chaotic mix of abstract, expressionist and
surrealist styles competing side-by-side for the visitors'
attention.
   Despite the freedom, however, there is no explosion of
previously unknown talent.
   Nonetheless, some artists make bold steps into the political
sphere. Premysl Vanicek, for example, hung a kitsch portrait of
Mikhail and Raisa Gorbachev close to a portrait in identical style
of Franz Kafka, the author whose full works are still unpublished
in his native Prague.
   Another picture, by Vaclav Sramek, consists entirely of the
letters P and A and is entitled ``Perestroika, A Variation on
Somebody Else's Theme'' _ a possible allusion to the similarity
between Gorbachev's reforms and those introduced in Czechoslovakia
in 1968 by Alexander Dubcek.
   Elsewhere in the exhibit, Olga Berekova displays a portrait of
Pope John Paul II, while rock star Mick Jagger graces the sculpture
section.
   The exhibit is limited to members and candidates of the Artists'
Union. In the past, the union was often accused of giving
preferential treatment to some members and failing to promote young
artists who have a chance to show at the salon.
   One idea behind the present exhibit seems to have been an
official desire to show that the alleged restrictions were not
preventing great young talents from coming forward.
   ``Gone is the era when so-called forbidden fruit tasted good
just because it had the odor of something forbidden, unwelcome and
outlawed,'' the political and arts weekly Tvorba said.
   ``The possibility of such a broad exhibition ... prevents the
birth of wronged artists and even martyrs because of an insensitive
and entirely unnecessary administrative intervention. All were
given the same chance and only the future will show who will win.''
   Official support for the salon went all the way up to Communist
Party leader Milos Jakes, who praised it as a chance for artists to
compare works.
   But not everybody was so enthusiastic. Czechoslovakia's graphic
artists, highly ranked internationally, did not take part, and not
one professor from the Academy of Arts chose to display works.
   The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo chafed at the low standard
of many works shown and took issue with at least one sculpture,
criticizing a torn chaise longue with a figure made out of tree
fungi as a work that had nothing to do with contemporary art.
   The exhibit was preceded by a handful of much smaller shows that
were tolerated but not officially sponsored in Prague last year.
   The Soviet drive for glasnost, or openness, in the arts and
state-run media has produced nothing like the outstandingly frank
films, plays and articles now seen in Moscow. But a few previously
banned films have been shown and the media has printed articles on
previously taboo topics such as drug addiction and prostitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     08-10 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Expected To Have Little Effect on This Year's Commodity
Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the drought is reducing crop
production sharply, Agriculture Department analysts do not expect
it to have much effect on U.S. commodity exports this year.
   On May 26, before the drought's impact was apparent, the USDA
forecast agricultural exports at a value of $33.5 billion in the
fiscal year that began last Oct. 1, up from $27.9 billion in
1986-97. The volume of shipments was forecast at 145.5 million
metric tons, up from 129.2 million.
   ``Exports in 1988 are primarily crops harvested during the
1987-88 crop year,'' says the department's Economic Research
Service. ``The drought will affect next year's exports more than
this year's.''
   The agency report, which was by economist Stephen A. MacDonald,
was in the August issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine. It did
not include projections for 1988-89 exports, however. Those are
scheduled to be released by USDA on Aug. 25.
   ``The drought's impact on exports during fiscal 1989 will depend
both on how much U.S. production drops and on how overseas
competitors and consumers react to higher prices,'' the report
said. ``Previous droughts in 1980 and 1983 provide useful
indicators.''
   For example, in the 1980-81 crop year, U.S. corn and soybean
supplies declined 10 percent and 12 percent, respectively, from the
previous year. At the same time, export prices averaged 18 percent
higher for corn and 16 percent higher for soybeans.
   And in 1983-84, corn and soybeans supplies dropped 29 percent
and 19 percent, while export prices rose an average of 23 percent
and 24 percent.
   Meanwhile, the actual volume of corn exports fell by less than 4
percent following the 1980 and 1983 droughts, while soybean exports
dropped 17 percent following the 1980 drought and 19 percent after
1983.
   ``But with higher prices, the value of agricultural exports rose
after each drought year,'' the report said.
   In 1980-81, the value of U.S. farm exports rose to a record of
$43.8 billion before declining. The export value, after sliding to
$34.8 billion in 1982-83, jumped to $38 billion in 1983-84,
reflecting the higher prices and shorter supplies.
   ``Although drought-reduced supplies and higher prices will help
cut the U.S. share of world agricultural trade in 1988-89, there is
no reason to believe that the drought will permanently constrain
the U.S. share of the world market,'' the report said.
   Exports dropped sharply in the early 1980s and still have not
recovered their former glory. But the report said ``conditions were
substantially different'' then.
   For one thing, the early 1980s were marked by global recession
and severe contraction in the ability of developing countries to
pay for imports. The global economy was recovering by 1984, but the
dollar and U.S. price supports had risen for several years,
prompting foreign producers to increase output and take advantage
of higher prices.
   Today, world economic growth is expected to remain near 3
percent in 1989, and U.S. price supports _ which tend to dominate
international commodity prices _ are lower as a result of the 1985
farm law. Also, the report said, the dollar has been declining for
three years and is unlikely to rebound.
   ``These conditions suggest a better post-drought outlook for
U.S. agricultural exports after fiscal 1989 than existed after
fiscal 1981 and 1984,'' the report said.
   Further, the continued strength of ``high-value'' exports such
as meat and horticultural products, is a major factor in the
overall outlook. Those items declined less than grain, oilseed and
cotton during the mid-1980s and recovered sooner, beginning in 1986.
   This year, the report said, horticultural products are expected
to rise $550 million to a record $3.7 billion, while exports of
animal products are projected to rise $600 million to a record $5.6
billion. Overall, exports of high-value products are expected to
reach $15.3 billion in 1987-88, matching the 1980-81 record.
   High-value exports go mainly to developed countries, where
financial constraints are ``almost unheard of'' and where local
currencies have risen against the U.S. dollar in recent years, the
report said. In all, sales to those countries are expected to climb
$1.7 billion this year to $16.7 billion, the biggest surge in four
years.
   Agricultural exports to the European Economic Community rose
$594 million during the first eight months of 1987-88 and are
expected to total $7.2 billion for the entire year, a 6 percent
increase.
   The report said the rise in EEC purchases stems from ``moderate
income and employment growth'' in the 12-nation bloc, and the
``inexpensive'' dollar, which allows Europeans to get more for
their currencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
