<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugTesting     08-10 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee OKs Drug, Alcohol Tests on Railroad Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would subject most of the
nation's 300,000 railroad workers to mandatory, random drug and
alcohol testing is moving through the House after many months of
delay.
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee sent the bill to the
full House on Tuesday by a voice vote. The House should ave a
chance to vote on the measure shortly after lawmakers return to
Washington in September after a recess that begins this week.
   The bill's future is in doubt, however, because the Senate
favors a more extensive measure that also would cover airline and
trucking industry employees.
   ``The public safety demands action in this Congress on random
testing of not only railroad employees, but of ... employees in the
motor carrier and aviation industries as well,'' said Sen. John
Danforth, R-Mo., the leading sponsor of the Senate's drug and
alcohol testing legislation.
   Congress started working on drug testing legislation in January
1987, shortly after 16 people died and 175 were injured when an
Amtrak passenger train collided with a Conrail locomotive in Chase,
Md. Two Conrail crewmen later admitted to having smoked marijuana
shortly before the accident.
   Railroad unions had opposed the legislation, arguing that it was
an invasion of privacy and could result in workers losing their
jobs because of inaccurate test results. They dropped their
opposition this spring, after the Department of Transportation
proposed testing regulations the unions considered less fair.
   The legislation would apply to most of the nation's 300,000
railroad workers, including management, but it would not cover
clerical workers.
   It would require that the workers undergo not only random
testing _ considered a deterrence _ but also examinations after
accidents, before hiring, for reasonable cause and as a part of
annual physical examinations.
   Workers found to be using illegal drugs or abusing alcohol would
be suspended without pay and required to undergo a rehabilitation
program. They would be given their old jobs back if they
successfully complete the program.
   Among the amendments the committee approved was one allowing
workers to continue being paid if they volunteer to take the
rehabilitation programs.
   The bill contains provisions designed to protect workers against
harassment, and to certify the laboratories that would conduct the
testing.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the energy and commerce
panel, complained that laboratories often conduct ``enormously
slovenly work,'' and said he would introduce legislation that would
set standards for lab work.
   ``Those people with false positives are going to lose jobs,
opportunity, they're going to lose their good name,'' Dingell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
