<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LonelyRepublicans Bjt   08-10 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lonely Republicans, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Republicans Are Few But Feisty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Are you Catholic? Do you know what penance
means? That's what it's like to be a Republican in Massachusetts.''
   The words come from an aide to a top Republican state
legislator, but they sum up the sentiments of most Massachusetts
Republicans, long the political minority in the state.
   The ascendancy of the state's top politician, Democratic
presidential nominee Michael S. Dukakis, isn't making life any
easier for the state's Republicans _ who are outnumbered by
Democrats 4 to 1.
   Republicans have not won a statewide election since 1972. Of the
state's 11 congressmen, one is Republican. Only 33 of 160 members
of the state House of Representatives are Republican and unless
Republicans win two state Senate seats this fall, they won't have
enough votes to demand a roll call.
   Recent figures show that only 12.8 percent of the state's voters
are Republican, compared with 46.7 percent who are Democrats.
   ``We'll say, let's have a caucus, is there a phone booth
available?'' said former state Rep. and current White House aide
Andrew Card.
   Still, Republicans like Joe Malone act optimistically. Malone
has to, because he may be the GOP's ultimate long-odds guy as the
challenger of Edward M. Kennedy this November for the U.S. Senate
seat Kennedy has held since 1962.
   ``When you're bucking a well-entrenched establishment, you have
to be tenacious, persistent and look for areas of growth,'' said
Malone, 33.
   All state Republicans hope that 1988 will begin to erase the
embarrassment of two years ago, when a pair of Republican primary
candidates for governor were forced from the ticket in disgrace.
One had falsified his resume, and it was reported that the
secretary of the other candidate walked into his office one morning
and found him nude. A third had to be called in at the last minute
to run against the heavily favored Dukakis.
   ``I compare us to the Red Sox: we have all this potential,''
said Polly Logan, the Republican national committeewoman and
legendary fund-raiser, who comes from a family of powerful
Massacusetts Democrats.
   State Republicans first lost their footing at the turn of the
century when Irish immigrants realized their political potential
and began their domination of state politics.
   Many of the traditional Boston Brahmin Republicans like former
Ambassador to the United Nations Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., former Sen.
Leverett Saltonstall and former Sen. Sinclair Weeks Sr. are dead.
Others, like former Gov. Francis Sargent, former U.S. Attorney
General Elliot Richardson, former state Sen. William Saltonstall
and former State Committee Chairman John Sears are no longer very
active in the party.
   Malone is an example of the new Massacusetts Republican. One of
seven children born to Italian immigrant parents, he was raised in
working-class Waltham, west of Boston and a world apart from the
tiny suburbs of the North Shore that spawned many old-line
Republican stalwarts.
   His father owned a trucking company and traveled to the Boston
docks every day for shipments. The elder Malone changed his name
from Mulone on the advice of a friend who suggested he would get
better treatment from predominantly Irish longshoremen and police.
   Though Harvard educated, Malone sticks close to his roots and
still lives in Waltham.
   White ethnics like Malone are not unknown in the Republican
Party in Massachusetts. In 1966, John Volpe, an Italian-American
Republican, was elected governor. Party chairman Ray Shamie, a
conservative millionaire who entered state politics fairly
recently, is of Syrian and French descent.
   But for the most part, Malone said, ``the Republican Party was
viewed as representing the haves and the Democrats the have-nots.''
He said some traditional Yankee Republicans have distanced
themselves from his candidacy and prefer to concentrate on George
Bush's presidential campaign.
   Saltonstall, the former state senator and son of Leverett
Saltonstall, said that's untrue. ``We think he's great,'' he said.
``We're glad to work with him.''
</TEXT>
