<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0811 08-10 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0811,0987</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Creates Cease-fire Observer Corps; Lacks Money to Finance It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th pvs, `U.S. Ambassador Vernon...' to
UPDATE with report of U.S. asking Arab gulf countries to pay more
for peacekeeping force. PICKS up 6th graf `At the White..' DELETES
2 bottom grafs to TRIM.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financially strapped United Nations
created a $74 million observer corps Tuesday to monitor a truce
between Iran and Iraq, but the secretary-general said, ``I simply
do not have the money'' to pay for it.
   Marrack Goulding, undersecretary-general in charge of
peacekeeping operations, said the General Assembly probably would
be summoned to special session this week to assess funds from the
membership.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar told an American
reporter: ``You should advise your government to participate fully
in these efforts for peace.''
   The United States, which supports U.N. peacemaking in the
Persian Gulf and Afghanistan, has fallen $467 million behind in its
U.N. payments over several years. It is assessed more than $200
million annually, one-quarter of the regular budget.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters said: ``I think the United
States will meet its obligations and make its payments.''
   The New York Times reported in Wednesday editions that the
United States is asking Arab countries of the Persian Gulf to pay a
higher share of the cost of the peacekeeping force, and that such a
sum could amount to $20 million.
   It quoted Assistant Secretary of State Richard S. Williamson as
saying the U.S. asked the Arab countries for a ``special voluntary
contribution toward the cost of the monitoring force, since they
are the chief beneficiaries.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration welcomed the cease-fire announcement and would bear
``its fair share of the cost'' of the observer force, including
transportation and equipment.
   ``It is our understanding that there will be neither U.S. nor
Soviet troops in the observer force,'' he added. ``It has been a
major aim of the United States to bring this war to an end.''
   Perez de Cuellar announced Monday that a cease-fire will begin
Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old war, which has killed or wounded more
than 1 million people and cost hundreds of billions of dollars. The
Security Council created the observer group, which is part of the
truce agreement.
   Twenty-five countries will provide the 350 unarmed observers,
paying the members they assign. The $74 million, including $47
million in start-up costs, will cover the initial six-month
authorization.
   Goulding told The Associated Press some observers already were
on their way to the Persian Gulf. He would not say how many or what
countries they represented.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark announced Tuesday in Ottawa
that Canada will contribute 385 military personnel to the
peacekeeping force, mostly communications specialists. They are
expected to start arriving in the region Wednesday.
   A U.N. naval force, the first in its history, also may be
created to patrol the disputed Shatt al-Arab waterway that forms
the southern border between Iran and Iraq.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said the United States will
withdraw most of its naval forces from the gulf only when it is
convinced the cease-fire has taken effect.
   This will be the seventh U.N. peacekeeping or observer group
created by the 159-member organization. The others operate in
Afghanistan, Cyprus, Lebanon, India, Pakistan, Syria and Jerusalem,
the last two resulting from Arab-Israeli wars in 1973 and 1948,
respectively.
   In Iraq, state television announced the cease-fire declaration
after midnight, declaring victory in the war and three days of
celebration. Fireworks exploded over the Tigris River and tens of
thousands of rounds of ammunition were fired into the air.
   Tehran radio reported the truce at 7 a.m. Tuesday, and Iranians
generally greeted it with relief tempered by skepticism about
prospects for a lasting peace. The military commander and
parlimament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, said Iran will not attack
but its soldiers will be prepared to repel the enemy.
   Perez de Cuellar is expected to ask the General Assembly for a
special assessment on members in proportion to their regular
contributions. That means Washington would be expected to pay the
largest share.
   ``I proceed on the assumption that the United States will come
up with its full assessment of 25 percent or more,`` Goulding told
a news conference.
   Walters said in his remarks to reporters after the Security
Council meeting: ``This proves definitively that the United Nations
has a purpose, that it is useful to all peace-loving countries,
including the United States of America. It has stopped the biggest
war since World War II.''
   Goulding would not identify the 25 countries that will
contribute soldiers and other personnel to the U.N. Iran-Iraq
Military Observer Group. He said the list might be announced
Wednesday, after approval and diplomatic formalities.
   The five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Britain, China, France and Soviet Union _ won't provide personnel
because the United Nations wants to avoid involvement by the major
powers.
   Contributing nations will be chosen by geographical
distribution, Goulding said. Japan, which never sends troops, is
expected to provide medical, communications and other personnel in
addition to $10 million.
   Among nations expected to send soldiers are Algeria, Austria,
Denmark, Fiji, Ghana, India, Kenya, Nigeria, Norway, Sweden, Turkey
and Yugoslavia.
   ``We expect to have an impressive body of observers deployed in
Iran and Iraq in time to observe a cease-fire,'' Goulding said.
``We certainly will try to have all 350 men there by D-Day,'' the
term Perez de Cuellar has used to describe Aug. 20.
   The United States has withheld funds from the United Nations
over several years for political reasons and as a means of
compelling it to introduce budgetary and other reforms.
</TEXT>
