<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ImpeachmentOath     08-10 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Impeachment Oath,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Take Oath For Hastings Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a ceremony as old as their legislative
body, senators have sworn to ``do impartial justice'' in the
impeachment trial of U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings, but the
trial won't happen until next year.
   It was like a page of history Tuesday as senators became judges
and jurors in an impeachment case for only the 13th time in their
history.
   But the proceeding did more for history buffs than for advancing
the impeachment case, as Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va. announced that time constraints in the 100th Congress will
make a trial impossible until next year.
   Hastings, who was not present at the Senate session, is the
first defendant to be impeached after winning acquittal on similar
charges at a criminal trial. He also is the first black impeachment
defendant.
   The House formally presented 17 articles of impeachment, along
with its recommendation that the Miami jurist be ousted for
committing ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
   Language in the oath used to swear in senators, and in a
proclamation ordering them to keep silent ``on the pain of
imprisonment,'' was adopted for the first impeachment case in
December 1798.
   The Senate at that time dismissed charges against Sen. William
Blount of Tennessee, saying a senator could not be impeached.
   The House voted 413-3 on Aug. 3 to impeach Hastings, accusing
him of: participating in a bribery conspiracy; lying about the
conspiracy at his criminal trial; leaking confidential wiretap
information, and discrediting the federal judiciary.
   Impeachment is the way Congress removes federal officials from
office, especially federal judges who are appointed for life. After
the House votes for impeachment, akin to an indictment, the Senate
conducts a trial in which conviction requires a two-thirds majority
of those present and voting.
   Senators approved a summons directing Hastings to answer the
impeachment articles by Sept. 8.
   The Rules Committee was asked to report by Sept. 23 on whether
the Senate should use a committee to hear the evidence before the
case is presented to the full chamber. That system was used for the
first time in the last impeachment trial, which resulted in the
conviction of Harry E. Claiborne and his removal as a U.S. district
judge in Las Vegas, Nev.
   The committee also is to report on the authority of the Senate
to receive impeachment articles in one Congress and conduct a trial
in another. House precedents show it has been done twice before.
   On Tuesday, House ``managers'' _ who function as prosecutors _
were led into the chamber by the House and Senate sergeants at
arms, with chief manager Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J., at the head
of the line.
   Rodino, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, was followed
by fellow committee members Hamilton Fish of New York, the ranking
Republican on the panel; John Conyers, D-Mich., chairman of the
subcommittee that investigated Hastings; George Gekas of
Pennsylvania, the ranking Republican on the subcommittee; and Rep.
John Bryant, D-Texas.
   While they sat at tables at the front of the chamber, Senate
Sergeant At Arms Henry Giugni intoned a traditional proclamation:
   ``Hear ye, hear ye, hear ye: All persons are commanded to keep
silent, on pain of imprisonment, while the House of Representatives
is exhibiting to the Senate of the United States articles of
impeachment against Alcee L. Hastings, judge of the United States
District Court for the Southern District of Florida.''
   Rodino then read every word of the 17 impeachment articles. And
when he finished, traditional words were heard again as senators
were sworn in:
   ``You do solemnly swear that in all things appertaining to the
trial of the impeachment of Judge Alcee L. Hastings, a judge of the
United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida,
now pending, you will do impartial justice according to the
Constitution and laws. So help you God.''
   The second most senior senator, Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., first
swore in the senior senator, John Stennis, D-Miss. Stennis then
swore in third-ranking Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis. Proxmire then
swore in the rest of the Senate.
   The House has impeached 15 federal officials in its history.
Twelve cases have gone to trial in the Senate. Two officials
resigned prior to Senate proceedings and five _ all federal judges
_ have been convicted by the Senate and removed from office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
