<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     08-10 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``60 Minutes'' Tops Ratings; NBC Wins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shows are reruns, and so are the A.C.
Nielsen Co. ratings. NBC won again last week. NBC won the whole
month of July, and CBS' ``60 Minutes'' was the top-ranked show,
with old news.
   ``60 Minutes,'' a consistent top 10 show, made it to the top on
Sunday with reports on Disney studio chief Michael Eisner, an
interview with Billionaire Boys Club founder and convicted murderer
Joe Hunt, and a report on Brazilian men getting away with murdering
their wives.
   The rest of last week's top 10 shows were ``Golden Girls,''
``Cheers'' and a fourth-place tie between ``Different World'' and
``His Mistress,'' all on NBC; ``A Case of Deadly Force'' on CBS; a
three-way tie among ``The Cosby Show'' and ``Night Court,'' both of
NBC, and CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote''; and ``ALF'' on NBC.
   NBC won the week with an average rating of 10.7 and an average
share of 21 percent of the viewing audience, followed by CBS with
10.2 and a 20 share and ABC with 8.6 and a 17 share.
   Each rating point represents 886,000 homes with television.
   For the July sweeps period, NBC averaged 11.2, followed by CBS
at 9.1 and ABC at 9.0. Ratings in sweeps months, which are often
sweetened by special programming, are used to determine advertising
rates.
   For the 46 weeks of this season, NBC's average rating is 14.8,
followed by CBS' 12.5 and ABC's 12.4.
   CBS won the evening news ratings with a 9.0 rating for the week,
while ABC and NBC tied at 8.6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
