<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-Gretzky     08-10 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Gretzky,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hockey's The Great Gretzky Traded To L.A</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He married a movie actress and now he's
Hollywood-bound, but it's clear the city that won Wayne Gretzky
renown as the greatest ice hockey player of his time has scored
more than a few points with him.
   Gretzky said at a news conference Tuesday that he wanted the
trade from the Edmonton Oilers to the Los Angeles Kings for
personal reasons, ``for the benefit of Wayne Gretzky, my new wife
and our expected child in the new year.''
   Then, the Great Gretzky was overcome with emotion.
   ``There comes a time when ...,'' he said before pausing. He
rubbed bleary eyes trying to regain his composure, then seemed to
give up. Without continuing, he stood up and walked away from the
microphones.
   Gretzky said his wife, Los Angeles-based actress Janet Jones,
did not ask him to seek a trade. ``It's my own gut feeling,'' he
said. The two were married July 16.
   Gretzky led the Oilers to four Stanley Cup championships in the
last five seasons. He holds or shares 49 National Hockey League
scoring records.
   The trade involved four other players, three first-round draft
choices and more than $10 million.
   Oilers' president Glen Sather, also with tears in his eyes, said
he hated to trade Gretzky but it was a good deal ``for Wayne, the
Oilers and the National Hockey League.''
   But Oiler fans reacted swiftly to news of the trade. Callers
jammed the 21 telephone lines at the team offices, some threatening
to cancel season tickets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
