<DOCNO> AP880810-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Governors'Politics     08-10 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Governors' Politics,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Record Causes Concern Behind The Scenes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Behind the facade of non-partisanship that
characterized the recent meeting of the nations's governors were
some highly partisan discussions of Michael Dukakis' role in his
state's economic revival.
   Among Republicans at the National Governors' Association that
ended Tuesday, there was clear concern that Dukakis has scored well
among voters with an appeal that emphasizes his tenure as steward
of the so-called ``Massachusetts Miracle.''
   As Republicans prepare to nominate George Bush for president,
they hope to use their national convention, opening Monday in New
Orleans, to raise questions about the Dukakis record. They hope to
portray a vote for the Democrat as risking a reversal of the
economic and foreign policy gains they claim as the legacy of
Ronald Reagan's presidency.
   Among the Democratic governors at the bipartisan National
Governors' Association meeting, there was a determination to keep
the message of ``competence'' before the voters in their states.
   ``We have one of our own running, one we have consistently
admired not just politically but intellectually,'' said Gov. Jim
Blanchard of Michigan, chairman of the Democratic Governors'
Association, after a strategy session Tuesday with Dukakis.
   Dukakis responded that his Democratic colleagues ``are going to
be an essential part of this campaign.''
   As expected, voters will get a sharply different picture of the
Dukakis record from his Republican colleagues.
   At a meeting the same day of the Republican Governors'
Association, statistics were distributed designed to show that the
Massachusetts economy is lagging behind other New England states,
all of which are enjoying a boom.
   The GOP numbers compared employment statistics in 1982 and 1987
and said that Massachusetts ranked last among the six New England
states in the percentage increase in new jobs.
   Using the same two years for comparison, the GOP figures ranked
Massachusetts fourth in the percentage increase in housing starts.
   The GOP governors also received Labor Department statistics
comparing the job growth between January 1983 and January 1988,
numbers that showed Massachusetts ranked 33rd in the nation.
   But the Republicans also were stuck with figures that showed
Dukakis' home state ranked first in New England in the increase in
per capita income and had the region's second lowest unemployment
rate.
   The effort to chip away at the Dukakis record was part of a GOP
strategy that became increasingly apparent at the governors'
meeting as well as in New Orleans.
   In an appearance before the Republican platform committee, Vice
President Bush described his opponent as the ``stealth candidate''
for keeping his position on issues invisible.
   And at the governors' meeting, Republican Gov. George Deukmejian
of California said, ``The only thing the Democrats have going for
them is their saying it's time for a change.''
   But while Republican governors were trying to portray Dukakis as
an unknown quantiy, they also were prodding Bush to make his vision
clearer to the voters.
   ``I don't think George Bush has been able to articulate his
vision to the satisfaction of voters in Wisconsin,'' said that
state's Republican governor, Tommy Thompson.
   ``People are confused about his views on the issues,'' said
another Bush supporter, Gov. Tom Kean of New Jersey.
   Meanwhile, Democratic governors clearly were pleased that
Dukakis has made a point of including them in his campaign.
   Blanchard recalled that four years ago, Democratic nominee
Walter Mondale didn't meet with his party's governors until October.
   ``The fact that we are having this meeting in early August bodes
well,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LiberaceTrial     08-10 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Trial,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendants Give Different Story on Entertainer's Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defendants in a lawsuit challenging the
will of the late Liberace testified Tuesday that in the weeks
before his death he was alert and active, rather than barely able
to walk or speak, as his housekeeper says.
   Dora Liberace, sister-in-law of the famed pianist and a
defendant in the lawsuit, said Liberace offered a toast at a
Christmas dinner, saying ``Next year we'll all be together again.''
He died six weeks later of complications from AIDS.
   A day earlier, Dorothy McMahon, Liberace's housekeeper for 16
years and a plaintiff in the suit, had testified that he could not
even bathe himself without assistance on the day he supposedly
reviewed his will.
   Liberace's sister and four others have charged that Liberace's
health was failing rapidly at Christmas time of 1986 and that he
was physically unable to comprehend a will and trust he signed four
weeks after the holiday celebration.
   Liberace died Feb. 4, 1987, two weeks after signing a will and
trust that left Beverly Hills, Calif., lawyer Joel Strote as
executor of the vast estate and head of the Liberace Foundation for
the Performing Arts.
   Those filing the suit contend that Strote has taken excessive
fees as head of the foundation.
   But testimony Tuesday indicated Strote's efforts had made money
for the foundation, and that the assets of the Liberace estate had
climbed from $14 million to $18 million under his guidance.
   Wayne Williams, an executive of First Interstate Bank, said a
check of records indicated Strote had saved the estate $1.1 million.
   Dora Liberace testified she sided with Strote in a bitter split
over control of the foundation, which provides scholarships to
nearly 30 colleges and universities.
   The wife of the late George Liberace testified of bitter
feelings between family members, and said she had been told she was
not welcome in the family. She currently runs the Liberace museum
in Las Vegas and is administrator of the foundation.
   George Liberace played straight man for his famous brother on
Liberace's popular television show in the 1950s. He moved to Las
Vegas in 1979 to start the museum.
   Dora Liberace testified Tuesday that Cary James, Liberace's
companion for six years before his death, had wanted to take
control of the foundation.
   Strote met with Liberace Jan. 15, 1987 and negotiated a new will
and trust, leaving him in charge of both. Liberace signed the
documents _ numbering more than 100 pages _ a week later at his
Palm Springs home. He slipped into a coma Feb. 1 and died Feb. 4.
   Dora Liberace and her daughter, Donna Mathews, testified Tuesday
that Liberace was alert and active when they went to his home for
the Christmas celebration in 1986.
   The sister-in-law said the subject of AIDS had surfaced in the
spring of 1986, shortly after Liberace had entered Valley Hospital
in Las Vegas for a series of tests.
   She recalled a time when Liberace came to pick her up for a
dinner engagement.
   ``He sat down on the divan and said `Dora, I do not have AIDS,'
'' she testified. ``Nothing else was said.''
   Plaintiffs in the suit are Liberace's sister, Angie;
housekeepers McMahon and Gladys Luckie; long-time manager Seymour
Heller and James.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     08-10 0897</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0938</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the more than 6,000 Californians whose
bank accounts have gone unclaimed for more than seven years were
particularly easy for the state to find: President Reagan and
Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   State Controller Gray Davis said Tuesday the state has returned
$3,492 to Reagan from a dormant campaign fund account stemming from
his eight years as governor of California.
   Meese, who served as Reagan's state legal affairs secretary in
1967, also recently received $9,095 from a personal account left by
his late father, Edwin Meese Jr.
   Under California law, accounts that have been inactive for seven
years or more are turned over for safekeeping to the controller's
office, which has amassed a trust of more than $375 million in 1.1
million individual accounts.
   So far, more than $3 million has been returned to 6,000 people
with such accounts, including $131,000 returned to charities and
civic organizations, such as the Boy Scouts of America.
   Davis, a Democrat, said he even found $94.96 that appears to
belong to Republican Gov. George Deukmejian.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Peter O'Toole wept with joy upon
hearing that a judge granted him custody of his 5-year-old son
during the school year, his attorney said.
   ``Peter O'Toole is a fabulous father,'' said attorney Jeffrey P.
Weinstein. ``He was not performing in court.''
   Superior Court Judge Alexander D. Lehrer ruled Tuesday that
Lorcan O'Toole will live with his mother, Karen Somerville O'Toole,
during school holidays in December and April and in the summer.
   ``I think she hoped to have been given the opportunity to
educate the boy ... but she will abide by the judge's decision,''
said her attorney, Gary Newman.
   In May, a judge in London ordered O'Toole to return his son to
Ms. Somerville O'Toole so the courts in New Jersey could decide
which parent should get permanent custody of the boy.
   The Irish-born O'Toole, 56, met Ms. Somerville O'Toole, 38, six
years ago when she lived in California. Ms. Somerville O'Toole, who
was never married to the actor but took his name, now lives in
Navesink, N.J., and New York City.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arsenio Hall, who co-stars in the hit movie
``Coming to America'' with fellow comedian Eddie Murphy, plans to
host a new TV talk show beginning next year.
   ``The Arsenio Hall Show,'' set to debut Jan. 2, marks Hall's
second attempt at a nightly interview program. Hall had served as
host of ``The Late Show'' on Fox Broadcasting until earlier this
year when the program was replaced.
   During a news conference Tuesday, Hall said his show ``will try
to do something different. ... Every night is going to be a party.
We're going to have a lot of fun.''
   The one-hour program will be distributed by Paramount Domestic
Television, and has been sold to eight of the nation's top 10
television markets.
   ``Coming to America'' has grossed $100 million at theaters since
it opened early last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics have liked Michael Keaton's dramatic
portrayal of a drug addict in ``Clean and Sober,'' but the actor
says the praise shouldn't extend to his character.
   ``I thought there was nothing redeemable about this guy. There
was nothing likeable about him,'' Keaton said of the movie that's
being released today.
   It was the second movie role Keaton accepted with reluctance,
the first being the box-office hit ``Beetlejuice.''
   It was also a dramatic departure for the star of ``Mr. Mom,''
``Johnny Dangerously'' and ``Nightshift.''
   ``Beetlejuice'' director Tim Burton, who will be directing
Keaton and Jack Nicholson in the forthcoming futuristic ``Batman,''
said Keaton is going through a sort of renaissance.
   ``He's one of the few comedic actors that can bridge that gap to
drama,'' said Burton.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Universal Studios is moving to a new home,
and who better to spread out the welcome mat than Norman Bates _
Anthony Perkins, actually _ in his latest ``Psycho'' movie?
   In addition to ``Psycho IV,'' new ``Lassie'' and ``Beaver''
television series will be shot when Universal begins production at
its new Orlando home, the company said Tuesday.
   Universal, competing with the new Disney-MGM Studios, said the
444-acre studio complex will begin filming 18 episodes of ``The New
Leave It To Beaver'' for cable Oct. 10. The new episodes filmed in
Florida will appear first on Atlanta SuperStation TBS and will then
be syndicated by Qintex Entertainment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CRIVITZ, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nina Siemaszko has a featured role in
Francis Ford Coppola's latest movie ``Tucker,'' but the 18-year-old
actress says she gladly gave up attending the premiere to be at a
youth camp.
   Even so, she says, missing the gala event was not easy with
people like Dustin Hoffman, Robert Duvall and Warren Beatty
attending the party.
   Since she was 3, Siemaszko has spent her summers at Camp Norwid,
a Polish Youth Association camp about 20 miles west of Crivitz in
northeastern Wisconsin. This year she's working as a volunteer
counselor at the camp.
   ``I know I always can come back here,'' Siemaszko said recently.
``I missed the premiere of `Tucker' because I was here. I love
doing this.''
   Siemaszko plays the daughter of Preston Tucker in the movie that
opens Friday about a man whose revolutionary car sparked a power
struggle in the automobile industry in 1946.
</TEXT>
