<DOCNO> AP880810-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Innis-SharptonShove     08-10 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Innis-Sharpton Shove,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Innis and Sharpton In Confrontation on TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Innis, the national chairman of the Congress
of Racial Equality, shoved the Rev. Al Sharpton to the ground
during the taping of a nationally syndicated television program
Tuesday.
   The two men managed to regain their composure and continue the
discussion of leadership in the black community, said Bill Boggs,
executive producer of the Morton Downey Jr. show.
   But Sharpton said they will have it out in a benefit boxing
match next month, Boggs said.
   The incident occurred during taping of the often heated talk
show at the Apollo Theatre in Harlem.
   During earlier taping Monday night, ``Al Sharpton started to
make some derogatory remarks about Roy Innis,'' Boggs said. Downey
then arranged for the two men to come face-to-face the next night.
   During taping Tuesday, ``Sharpton made a few statements early in
the show that basically questioned Innis' ability and his authority
as a black leader today and for whom he was speaking, and
criticized him for `kowtowing' to (state Attorney General) Robert
Abrams,'' Boggs said.
   Abrams is the special prosecutor in the case of Tawana Brawley,
a black Dutchess County teen-ager who claims she was abducted and
sexually assaulted by a group of white men. Under the guidance of
her advisers, who include Sharpton, Miss Brawley has refused to
cooperate with the investigation.
   Innis cited his own appearance on a Downey show in June.
According to Boggs, Innis told Sharpton that during that show, he
had come to Sharpton's defense, ``in spite of all those
shenanigans'' in the case.
   A screaming match ensued, with Sharpton yelling ``that's not
true.''
   ``Innis stood up and was basically telling Sharpton to let him
speak ... and towered over him,'' the producer said. As the rotund
Sharpton started to get up, Innis pushed him. Sharpton fell into
the chair and toppled over backwards onto the floor.
   Sharpton was not hurt, but he leapt up and a lot of people
rushed onto the stage, Boggs said.
   Downey brought things back under control within about 20 minutes
and there was no other physical confrontation, he said.
   Boggs said the show is scheduled to air Aug. 30.
</TEXT>
