<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes $59 Billion for Housing, Independent Agencies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has passed a compromise spending
bill providing $59 billion for the Department of Housing and Urban
Development and 16 independent agencies.
   The House vote Tuesday was 373-30, sending the bill to the
Senate.
   House Democratic leaders said the appropriations bill for HUD
and other agencies is consistent with the budget summit agreement
worked out last year by Congress and the White House.
   The bill would provide $10.7 billion for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, including $900 million for a
space station, and funds for the Environmental Protection Agency,
the Veterans Administration, the National Science Foundation and
the Consumer Product Safety Commission, among other agencies.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Said Largest Ever Involving Law Firm And S&L Insurance Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philadelphia law firm has paid $50 million
in the largest payment ever to settle a claim by the Federal
Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
   The FSLIC, the government insurance fund backing deposits in
savings institutions, announced Tuesday it had received the payment
from the firm of Blank, Rome, Comisky & McCauley to settle charges
stemming from the firm's representation of Sunrise Savings and Loan
Association of Boynton Beach, Fla.
   FSLIC, in a suit seeking $250 million, charged the law firm with
negligently advising Sunrise and aiding its officers in violating
federal banking laws.
   Proceeds of the settlement will be divided between FSLIC and
former shareholders of Sunrise, an insolvent institution placed
into receivership in July 1985, according to a statement from the
agency.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Twelve Receive National Medal of Arts From Reagans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and Mrs. Reagan presented the
National Medal of Arts to 12 luminaries of the arts. ``The right to
sing your own song is the promise and glory of America,'' Reagan
said.
   It was the fourth time the medals have been awarded since they
were created by Congress in 1984 on Reagan's recommendation.
   Awarded the medals on Tuesday were: Novelist Saul Bellow;
Actress Helen Hayes; filmmaker and composer Gordon Parks; Architect
I. M. Pei; choreographer Jerome Robbins; Pianist Rudolf Serkin;
Composer Virgil Thomson; Art historian Sydney J. Freedberg; Roger
L. Stevens, founding chairman of the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts; Art patron Brooke Astor; arts patron Francis
Goelet; and philosophy professor and philanthropist Obert C. Tanner.
</TEXT>
