<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PolishDefector     08-10 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polish Defector,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Folk Dancer Stays In Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish folk dancer who had performed in
Israel left a farewell letter for his troupe and defected a few
hours before he was to fly home, Israeli officials said.
   The dancer belonged to a 46-member troupe performing at the
Haifa Folklore Festival. Haifa municipal spokesman Josef Bar
identified him as Sigmund Arnas.
   ``Arnas left a letter in which he said he decided to stay in
Israel and sent warmest regards to the group,'' Bar said Tuesday.
``Since this morning, we have been unable to find him. He simply
disappeared.''
   The troupe flew back to Warsaw later Tuesday after a two-week
stay in Israel. It was one of three East European folklore troupes
performing at the festival.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Israel has no set policy on
whether to grant asylum to defectors. Each case was examined on its
own merits, he said.
   Israel and Poland restored low-level diplomatic ties in 1986
after a rupture of almost 20 years.
</TEXT>
