<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSDrug 1stLd-Writethru a0445 08-10 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Drug, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Trials of New AIDS Drug Start Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng About 50, to correct name of firm and
location; picks up 7th graf pvs, AIDS is.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new type of genetically engineered AIDS drug
is being tested starting today on human victims of the deadly
disease at the National Cancer Institute.
   The first round of tests is designed to assess the safety of the
drug, called CD4, rather than its effectiveness, but researchers
hope the drug will open new avenues to attack the virus that causes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   The drug mimics a protein normally found on the surface of
immune system cells that are susceptible to the AIDS virus.
   Researchers hope the experimental drug will, in effect, fool the
deadly virus into harmlessly attaching itself to the injected
substance rather than the similar receptors on immune system cells.
   Similar studies will begin in a few days at San Francisco
General Hospital and New England Deaconess Hospital in Boston.
   About 50 patients will be involved in the first round of tests
of the drug which is manufactured by Genentech Inc. of South San
Francisco, Calif.
   AIDS is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune
system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and
infections. The virus most often is spread through close contact
with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons. Its
chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug users.
   As of Monday, AIDS had been diagnosed in 70,208 Americans, of
whom more than half, 39,620, had died, according to the federal
Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to have recovered from
AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CIA-Soviets     08-10 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CIA-Soviets,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Director Accuses Soviets of Stepping Up Espionage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIA director William H. Webster says the Soviets
are trying harder than ever to tap into U.S. intelligence and that
security breaches in the last three years have cost the United
States billions of dollars.
   In a speech Tuesday to the American Bar Association, he said he
has set up a special counter-intelligence agency to protect the
CIA's foreign operations.
   ``This center was badly needed ... too many things were falling
between chairs,'' he told the association's annual meeting. About
12,000 lawyers are attending the weeklong convention, which ends
today.
   ``Over the past three years, we have discovered more
penetrations of the U.S. defense and intelligence communities than
at any time in our history,'' said Webster, who took over the
Central Intelligence Agency in May 1987 after 10 years as director
of the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
   ``The costs of these compromises are estimated in the billions
of dollars,'' he added.
   ``The Soviet intelligence services, the KGB and GRU, represent
by far the most significant intelligence threat ... Despite Soviet
glasnost and perestroika, we've actually seen an increase this year
in Soviet atempts to recruit U.S. sources,'' he said.
   Glasnost is the name of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
drive for greater discussion on selected subjects. Perestroika is
his program to make Soviet economy more efficient.
   Webster, a former U.S. Court of Appeals judge, said the Soviets
were ``more aggressive and more sophisticated'' than ever in their
search for information on U.S. nuclear strategic forces, foreign
policy, NATO, technology, American intelligence sources and
methods, and congressional intentions.
   He cited two cases this summer, both involving Canada: the
arrest of Canadian Stephen Ratkai on charges of trying to pass U.S.
military secrets to the Soviet Union in Newfoundland, and the
expulsion or barring from Canada of 17 Soviet officials for
allegedly attempting to steal U.S. military and commercial
technology in Montreal.
   Webster said the CIA and FBI were working closely together in
``offensive and defensive measures'' to counter foreign spies.
   He said the CIA collected information on 253 terrorist threats
around the world over the past 3{ years, and he cited one success
and one failure when warnings were relayed into the field.
   ``In one such case, the agency received a report that terrorists
planned to assassinate the senior American diplomat in a major
Eastern country when he arrived for a meeting ... He arranged for
the meeting to be held elsewhere and escaped the attempt on his
life.
   ``Sadly, just a few days ago, a similar warning was issued to
another figure in South America. The warning was not heeded and he
was assassinated.''
   CIA public affairs director William Baker said the director
intentionally did not name the two people involved and that the
agency would not comment further.
   Webster said terrorism was again on the increase, from 500
incidents in 1981 to almost 800 in 1985 and a projected 900 this
year.
   ``About half of these terrorist incidents worldwide are directed
against U.S. persons and property,'' he said.
   However, he credited FBI intelligence-gathering with checking
terrorist bombings and other attacks within the United States, down
from 100 a year to ``less than a dozen in the last two years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
