<DOCNO> AP880810-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FBI-StolenNotes     08-10 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Stolen Notes,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Clears FBI in Acquisition of His Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A journalist has cleared the FBI of wrongdoing in
acquiring some of his confidential notes, which he previously
believed had been stolen from his home in Costa Rica, a newspaper
reported today.
   Tony Avirgan told The Boston Globe he learned last weekend that
the FBI got the material indirectly through a CBS News colleague,
Carroll Dougherty.
   Avirgan said Dougherty told him he gave copies of the notes to
Jack Terrell, a former mercenary who was giving the FBI information
on alleged illegal activities connected with a private Nicaraguan
rebel aid network, and that Terrell gave the FBI access to some of
them.
   Avirgan said Dougherty's passing along of the material was
unauthorized and unethical.
   Doughtery said he thought he had Avirgan's permission to share
the notes with Terrell.
   ``Obviously, I had no idea the material would end up in the
hands of the FBI,'' Dougherty said.
   Two weeks ago, the Globe said 39 pages of Avirgan's material
found in the files of the FBI's field office in Washington
apparently were obtained through two break-ins at Avirgan's home in
Costa Rica. The FBI later confirmed the notes were in its files.
   Following the report, Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of
the FBI oversight committee in Congress, announced an investigation
into the matter.
   Avirgan said at the time that there was no other way the
material, including notes of interviews and private memos to his
editor, could have been acquired and given to the FBI.
   ``But after investigating this incident thoroughly, we now
realize that the FBI did not obtain the documents as a result of a
break-in or any other unethical or illegal action,'' Avirgan said.
   ``We did suffer two break-ins, in 1985 and 1986, in which files
were rifled and, perhaps, photocopied,'' he said. ``We're still
looking for an explanation of those break-ins.''
   Doughtery's role was discovered last week when his handwriting
was found on one page of the material released by the FBI, the
Globe said.
   Avirgan said Doughtery was sent to Costa Rica by CBS News in
1985 to help him and his journalist wife, Martha Honey, investigate
the attempted assassination of dissident Contra leader, Eden
Pastora.
   Avirgan and his wife have filed a $24 million damage suit in
Miami accusing U.S. and Nicaraguan Contra officials of
responsibility for the bombing. The lawsuit was dismissed in June
for insufficient evidence.
   Avirgan said Dougherty told him last weekend he provided copies
of Avirgan's notes to Terrell in exchange for Terrell's material on
the private network aiding the rebels fighting to overthrow
Nicaragua's leftist government.
   But, Terrell told the Globe the material was not used in a trade.
   The FBI got copies of Avirgan's material when agents interviewed
Terrell in 1986, the Globe said. Terrell told the newspaper he gave
the FBI fewer than 39 pages but said his memory might not be
accurate.
   John Mattes, a Florida lawyer, said when Terrell was approached
by the FBI, ``I advised Terrell to cooperate fully with the FBI and
to give them everything he had. That's how CBS material got into
their files.''
   Greg Jones, a spokesman for the FBI, said Tuesday that FBI
Director William Sessions ``has maintained throughout that the
materials came to us from an individual who voluntarily provided
them to us. The FBI did not solicit the information nor did we know
how it was obtained.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
