<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SexRing     08-10 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Ring,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Smash High-Tech Sex Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-tech prostitution ring used
computers to keep records on 40,000 customers, including
professional athletes and politicians, police said.
   The Berkeley-headquartered ring used beepers to dispatch escort
service ``dates,'' said Oakland police Sgt. Mike Martin.
   About 100 officers, coordinated by a task force from Oakland,
San Jose and the state Attorney General's office, served 18 search
warrants on Tuesday in San Francisco Bay area cities. They arrested
seven people.
   Martin would not disclose the customers' names, but said they
included politicians and pro athletes. He said the computer records
listed their sexual preferences along with home addresses, phone
numbers, and credit-card account numbers.
   Among those arrested was the alleged leader of the $3
million-a-year operation, Thomas Nathaniel Lusk, 48, who was
recently released from federal prison, where he served a term for
income-tax evasion.
   Lusk owned seven escort services that employed dozens of
prostitutes, who averaged $160 to $175 an hour for their services,
Martin said.
   The women communicated with the office through beepers and
telephones and couriers picked up the money or credit card vouchers.
   Lusk and four others were arrested on $500,000 warrants charging
them with multiple counts of felony pimping and pandering, police
said. The others were booked for investigation of pimping and
pandering and possession of cocaine.
</TEXT>
