<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrongAddresses     08-10 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wrong Addresses,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Phone Book Gets Thousands Of Addresses Wrong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bad connection somewhere in the
telephone company has apparently caused thousands of customers to
be listed with the wrong street number in the new phone book.
   South Kingstown streets were renumbered late last year as part
of the state's new 911 emergency telephone system. Officials
delivered a list of the new street numbers to New England Telephone
Co. in February, four months before the deadline for address
changes in the new book.
   But Arthur Jones, a spokesman for the telephone company, said no
one from the phone company's 911 division passed along the new
addresses to the division that publishes the telephone books.
   ``I believe that the left hand doesn't know what the right hand
is doing at the phone company,'' said Jack Carney, the engineer in
the town Department of Public Works who coordinated the street
number changes.
   Town Council President Harold Smith urged the phone company to
publish a supplement to make the corrections instead of waiting
until next year's book.
   ``It is a big mistake, a significant mistake. I don't think we
can go a year without it being rectified,'' Smith said. ``If there
is any place that needs to have the correct address, it is the
telephone directory.''
   Officials said the problem affected a significant number of the
town's 20,968 residents, although they did not have exact figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
