<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0478 08-10 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Plunge While Dollar Soars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT date and figure for largest previous one-day drop,
SUB 2nd graf. Picks up 3rd graf, `The dollar ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged across the board on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange on Wednesday, setting a record for daily trading
this year, while the U.S. dollar soared against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main barometer, dropped 615.49 points, or 2.18 percent, to close at
27,554.87. It was the index's largest one-day drop since Nov. 11,
when it fell 649.70 points.
   The dollar opened at 134.93 yen, 1.35 yen higher than Tuesday's
close of 133.58 yen in Tokyo, and continued to move up. After
reaching the 135.20 yen mark in mid-morning, the highest level
since July 18, it closed at 134.92 yen, up 1.34 yen from Tuesday's
close.
   Securities dealers attributed the sharp drop of the index to the
discount rate hike by the Federal Reserve of the United States and
a 28-point fall of the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials in New
York overnight.
   ``The stock market has been sluggish to begin with,'' said a
dealer at a Tokyo brokerage. ``Then came news of sudden discount
rate hike in the U.S. and an overnight drop of Dow Jones industrial
average in New York. The combination of them caused today's sharp
fall.''
   The Nikkei index was on a three day downward stretch since
Saturday before Wednesday's trading began. It lost 254 points in
the past three days, hitting the below 28,000 mark for the first
time since July 29.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, reacting to the dollar's
surge, said the current exchange rate fluctuation was not violent
and there was no need for central bank intervention to stem the
rise.
   Kyodo News Service quoted a Bank of Japan official as saying
``We will monitor the progress in the U.S. closely, but have no
intention of changing Japan's current domestic policy stance.''
   Exchange dealers also said that profit-taking was taming the
dollar's sharp upward surge.
   ``Players who bought the dollar yesterday (Tuesday), especially
the trading houses and insurance companies, are selling it off in
profit-taking,'' said a exchange dealer at a U.S. investment bank
in Tokyo.
   ``But active buying from other sources cut in immediately after
the dollar inches down, not allowing it to fall below the 135-yen
level,'' the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``I
expect more buying later in the day.''
   Securities dealers said the morning decline in stock prices was
in response to a 28-point loss in Wall Street's Dow Jones
industrial average, which fell after the Federal Reserve Board
announcement that it was increasing the U.S. discount rate to 6.5
percent from 6.0 percent.
   An increase of the discount rate, the fee the nation's central
bank charges for short-term loans to member banks, would affect
other interest rates, including those on prime rates and mortgage
rates, to be set by commercial banks. Higher U.S. interest rates
increase the attractiveness of dollar-denominated investments.
   ``They were more concerned about the interest rate hike in
Japan,'' said a dealer at a Tokyo brokerage. ``But the worry seems
to have cleared and I expect share prices will recover shortly.''
</TEXT>
