<HEAD>Bush Says He Likes Poll Results But Doesn't Believe in Polls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng ``He's trying, to correct quote by
deleting extraneous matter; picks up 17th graf pvs, Emphasizing
policy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is upbeat about a new poll showing
him narrowing the lead of Democratic presidential rival Michael
Dukakis, saying ``It's a nice change,'' and, ``I like it, I like
it.''
   After weeks of trailing Dukakis by as much as 17 points in some
surveys, the vice president and his staff took pains Tuesday to
bring attention to a Gallup poll that said he was only seven points
down, with Dukakis holding a 49 percent to 42 percent edge.
   The poll gives Bush a better footing for next week's Republican
National Convention, where he will be crowned the GOP presidential
nominee, by showing him in close contention with the Massachusetts
governor instead of dropping further behind.
   ``Things are moving. We're beginning to get them in focus. Watch
and you'll see these surveys turn around,'' Bush said.
   ``This is dramatic movement ... it's very encouraging. ... It's
a nice change, it's a nice turnaround,'' he told reporters in
Philadelphia at the end of a daylong trip through Pennsylvania.
   ``I told you to be patient,'' he said. ``I like it, I like it,''
he exulted.
   Tempering his optimism, Bush said, ``Polls don't matter.'' He
went on to say, ``I don't believe in polls, not even the good ones.
... I don't think polls mean anything.''
   The Gallup survey of 1,004 registered voters, conducted Friday
through Sunday, had a 3 percentage point margin of error.
   Bush's trip, with stops in Erie and Pittsburgh as well as
Philadelphia, was his last outing before he goes to the convention
in New Orleans.
   Today and Thursday, he is taping separate, hour-long interviews
in Washington with the four major television networks for broadcast
during the convention.
   Bush also continued work on his search for a running mate. Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said the vice president asked him and four
other guests on Air Force II about their recommendations but gave
no clue to his thinking.
   Specter said the consensus of the guests was that the No. 2 job
should go to Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who
unsuccessfully challenged Bush for the nomination.
   ``I know Dole could do it,'' Specter said. ``Dole ought to
appear in front of Boston Bay and say that Dukakis could walk on
water and the reason is it is full of sludge and solid waste
disposal.''
   Bush said at a news conference that his decision was not
imminent. ``I'm not close in the sense of, like tomorrow, making a
final decision,'' the vice president said. He has said he wants to
keep it a secret until the final day of the convention, which
begins Monday.
   Bush also stepped up his attack against Dukakis, saying his
opponent was trying to avoid being specific on issues.
   ``He is trying to run away from a record in Massachusetts on the
very, very far liberal fringe of the political spectrum and I have
to pin him down,'' Bush said. ``And he's unwilling to do that
because he thinks he can preempt the middle.'
   Emphasizing policy differences with Dukakis, Bush said, ``When
he says he's against the death penalty for everything, the country
has a right to know it. I happen to think some crimes are bad
enough. You should.
   ``When he says he wants to take guns away from people, why then,
the country ought to know that,'' the vice president added.
   Bush said he was urging speakers at the GOP convention to be
positive and to focus on the issues.
   ``But I can't guarantee that somebody's not going to take a
swipe at Michael Dukakis,'' Bush said. ``I have a lot of friends
out there and they didn't like the vicious, personal attacks
(against Bush at the Democratic convention) and I did not react to
them. But I can't control everybody, but I'm urging them to stay
positive, as I'm doing.''
   Bush added, ``There's a lot of people out there that want to go
after 'em. There's a lot of people that feel it was a very unfair,
totally negative tune there.''
</TEXT>
