<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Drop, Dollar Up Against Yen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The increase in the U.S. discount rate upset Tokyo
investors today, causing a major drop in stock prices and a sharp
increase in the dollar against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main barometer, fell 615.49 points, or 2.18 percent, to close at
27,554.87. It was the largest one-day drop of the index since Nov.
11, 1987, when it fell 649.70 points.
   The volume traded on the first section of the exchange was 700
million shares compared to 650 million Tuesday.
   Securities dealers attributed the drop to the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board's half-percentage point increase in its discount rate
to 6.5 percent on Tuesday and the subsequent 28-point fall in the
Down Jones average in New York.
   ``The stock market has been sluggish to begin with,'' said a
dealer at a Tokyo brokerage, speaking anonymously.
   He said news of the Federal Reserve's action and the New York
Stock Exchange tumble came as a surprise, and ``the combination of
them caused today's sharp fall.''
   An increase in the discount rate, which the central bank charges
for short-term loans to member banks, would in turn affect the
interest rates the commercial banks charge.
   However, another Tokyo dealer, also speaking anonymously, said
investors had been prepared for the interest rate increase for some
time and ``were more concerned about any interest rate increase in
Japan. But the worry seems to have cleared, and I expect share
prices will recover shortly.''
   The Nikkei index had previously fallen for three straight days,
shedding 254 points and dipping below the 28,000 mark for the first
time since July 29.
   On the foreign exchange market, the U.S. currency remained
strong throughout the day's trade.
   The dollar opened at 134.93 yen, 1.35 yen higher than Tuesday's
close, and continued to rise. After reaching the 135.20-yen mark in
mid-morning, the highest level since July 18, it closed at 134.92
yen, up 1.34 yen from the day before.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, reacting to the dollar's
surge, was quoted by Japanese newspapers as saying the current
exchange rate fluctuation was not violent and that there was no
need for central bank intervention to stem the rise.
   Kyodo News Service quoted an unidentified Bank of Japan official
as saying: ``We will monitor the progress in the U.S. closely, but
have no intention of changing Japan's current domestic policy
stance.''
   Exchange dealers added that profit-taking was taming the strong
rise of the dollar.
   ``Players who bought the dollar yesterday, especially the
trading houses and insurance companies, are selling it off in
profit-taking,'' said an exchange dealer at a U.S. investment bank
in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
