<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Koch-Beggars     08-10 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koch-Beggars,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYC Starting Ads Urging People To Ignore Beggars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has announced an
advertising campaign to encourage people to give money to charities
rather than to panhandlers because, he says, most beggars are
trying to rip people off.
   The advertisements on subways will urge people to donate money
to charities, so ``they will know the money will go not for booze,
not for drugs, but to provide maintenance for these people,'' the
mayor said Tuesday.
   ``I'm concerned that people are giving lots of money
collectively, and in most cases _ not all _ it's a scam,'' Koch
said. ``People who say they are starving _ it is simply not true.
In most cases, they are demented.''
   Koch added that panhandlers who don't take advantage of the
city's shelter and welfare system are either ``mentally disturbed,
or it's a scam.''
   There are no statistics on the number of panhandlers in New
York, but groups who work with the homeless say they number in the
thousands.
   The subway signs will describe the city's public assistance
programs so that people can make an educated decision about whether
to give money, Koch said. The signs also may include a phone number
to offer beggars that would direct them to places where they can be
assisted.
   ``I don't want New York City to become a city where people think
it's OK to assume the role of beggars as if it were a profession,''
the mayor said.
   Human Resources Administration Director William J. Grinker, who
is developing the advertising campaign, called the beggars ``an
increasingly intrusive part of urban life that has gotten to be
like graffiti.''
   But Christina Walker, director of the Food and Hunger Hotline,
an association of 600 soup kitchens and food pantries, said
suggestions that people are begging because they choose to, or are
mentally ill or addicted to drugs or alcohol is a ``useful myth.
... People are asking for money because they need money to
survive.''
   Almost all soup kitchens are closed on weekends and in the
evenings, Walker said, and the food pantries are aimed toward
people with homes. All food providers must limit the number they
can serve, she said, and thousands are turned away daily.
   In a survey last year by the Legal Action Center for the
Homeless of 500 men who attend soup kitchens in the city, 69
percent said they receive no public assistance. Of these, 42
percent said they were forced to panhandle to survive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
