<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParkRiot     08-10 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Park Riot,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Concerned About Police Force At Tompkins Square Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A review of videotapes of a park confrontation
between police and protesters in which 53 people were injured shows
officers may have used excessive force, the mayor and police
commissioner say.
   ``The films that I saw the other day are very disturbing,''
Mayor Edward I Koch said Tuesday, adding that the officers may have
legitimate explanations for their conduct last weekend.
   But Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said he would be surprised
if some of the officers could justify the actions that caused irate
residents to file 40 charges of brutality.
   ``There is some behavior that was captured on tape that I think
the individual officers that are involved are going to have great
difficulty explaining,'' Ward said.
   A riot involving 450 demonstrators and 400 officers broke out at
Tompkins Square Park in Manhattan's Lower East Side as police tried
to enforce a 1 a.m. curfew on Sunday. In the wake of the riot, Koch
suspended enforcement of the curfew to prevent further violence.
   Police had gone to Tompkins Square because of complaints from
residents of the gentrifying neighborhood that the park was a
nighttime hangout for drug dealers, rowdy drunks, homeless people
and so-called punk rockers, who dress in black leather and spike
their hair.
   Among the 53 injured were 14 police officers.
   During the confrontation, several officers in one of the tapes
apparently tried to hide their badge numbers with black bands, the
New York Post reported today. One officer apparently was not
wearing a badge, it said.
   Failure to display badge numbers and name plates is a violation
of departmental regulations.
   The Civilian Complaint Review Board, which is comprised of
civilians and police representatives, appealed to residents of the
East Village area to come forward with their complaints and to help
identify officers who used excessive force.
   ``This is a priority case; it will be given our full
attention,'' said Deputy Commissioner Sandra Marsh, who anticipated
a long investigation because of the number of complaints.
   After the panel looks at the evidence, it sends its
recommendation to the police commissioner, who can accept it or
reject it.
   The most severe recommendation is to charge the officer with a
breach of department discipline. The officer would face a
departmental trial, which could lead to dismissal.
</TEXT>
