<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beryl Heads Northwest After Dropping Heavy Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical depression Beryl was heading northwest over Louisiana
early today after dropping 1 to 2 inches of rain on southwest
Mississippi and southern Louisiana.
   The center of the depression, which was downgraded from a
tropical storm on Tuesday, was near Lafayette, La., and was
expected to continue toward the northwest.
   On Tuesday evening, strong thunderstorms produced wind damage in
west-central Texas. Winds gusted to 59 mph near Midland.
   Thunderstorms dumped heavy rain over central New Mexico on
Tuesday afternoon, causing local flooding. A 20-foot section of a
bridge was washed out at Sandia Knolls, and considerable flooding
of streets and dry gullies was reported at Albuquerque when over an
inch of rain fell within an hour.
   Other showers and thunderstorms fell over eastern Colorado,
where large hail accompanied heavy rain in Colorado Springs;
south-central Nebraska, Missouri, west-central Illinois, Florida
and the coast of the Carolinas. The weather was fair over the rest
of the nation.
   The high for the nation Tuesday was 110 degrees at Bullhead
City, Ariz.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included more than 2{ inches at the Marine Corps base at Cherry
Point, N.C., more than 1 1@3 inches at Lafayette, La., and
Albuquerque, and nearly an inch at Altus Air Force Base, Okla.
   For today, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for
portions of the Ohio Valley and the southern half of the middle
Mississippi Valley, and from eastern Texas and the lower
Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast and Florida.
Thunderstorms were predicted be most numerous over the central Gulf
Coast and Louisiana in association with Beryl. Additional showers
and thunderstorms were forecast for central Oklahoma, central New
Mexico, and northern New England. The rest of the nation was
expected to have mostly sunny skies.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 80s and 90s across much
of the nation; in the 70s in portions of the California coast and
northwest Washington state; 95-100 from central Texas into southern
Kansas; and 100-110 over the desert Southwest and the valleys of
California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 90 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 fair; Boston 74 foggy; Buffalo 80 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 76 fair; Cincinnati 74 hazy; Cleveland 77 cloudy;
Detroit 77 foggy; Miami 81 partly cloudy; New York 75 fair;
Philadelphia 76 fair; Pittsburgh 71 foggy; Portland, Maine 71 fair;
Washington 77 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 64 fair; Chicago 77 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
86 fair; Denver 66 windy; Des Moines 72 fair; Indianapolis 76
foggy; Kansas City 74 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 69 fair;
Nashville 80 fair; New Orleans 76 showers; St. Louis 79 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 cloudy; Anchorage 60 cloudy; Las Vegas 80
fair; Los Angeles 62 cloudy; Phoenix 90 fair; Salt Lake City 67
fair; San Diego 66 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 63 partly
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 77 cloudy; Toronto 75 hazy.
</TEXT>
