<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EscapeRuse     08-10 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Escape Ruse,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailers Give Convict Gun, Videotape Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENDLETON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate who used a what he thought was
a smuggled gun in an escape attempt found out two days later that
he was an unwitting participant in a training exercise and that the
weapon carried blanks.
   ``He was making statements that he'd almost made it,'' Umatilla
County Sheriff Jim Carey said Tuesday.
   Stanley Bernson, a 52-year-old murderer who had tried to escape
three times from the county jail since 1986, had asked a guard to
help him break out, Carey said.
   With the sheriff's permission, the jailer ``smuggled'' a gun and
bullets into Bernson's cell. However, the firing pin had been
removed and the gunpowder taken out of the bullets.
   ``Our goal was to find out what it would take if it was the real
thing, and how he would react,'' Carey said. ``The adrenaline was
flowing like it was really going down.''
   Bernson pulled the gun on two guards Saturday, the sheriff said.
``When he stepped out of his cell, he told them to empty their
wallets and put their watches on the floor, and he ordered them
into the cell,'' Carey said.
   ``Then we allowed him from there on into a corridor, which we
had already pre-planned. Then we played it out in a way that made
sense to him.''
   Bernson was trapped by locked doors at each end of the corridor
and was forced to negotiate with guards watching him through a
video camera. The escape attempt lasted 22 minutes and ended when
Bernson gave himself up.
   ``We just talked to him and observed him and saw how he reacted
to things we did,'' Carey said. ``He de-escalated pretty fast.''
   Bernson did not try to fire the gun during the escape attempt,
Carey said.
   Bernson is awaiting trial in the 1978 slaying of a 15-year-old
girl and is serving a life sentence for murdering a Richland,
Wash., woman in 1979. He was transferred to the jail from the
Washington State Penitentiary in Walla Walla.
   ``He's a big concern for us,'' the sheriff said. ``I used
unusual measures this time. I've really got a unique problem with a
unique individual.''
   Bernson's attorney, Dennis A. Hachler, declined to comment on
the incident because of a judge's gag order in the murder case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
