<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Seals     08-10 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Seals,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Meet In London To Discuss Seal Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from European countries bordering the
North and Baltic seas today began a two-day meeting to discuss the
deaths of thousands of seals along their coasts, the environmental
group Greenpeace said.
   Greenpeace, which is sponsoring the meeting with the University
of London, said the scientists will assess the extent of the
deaths, the cause and any possible action which may be taken.
   ``While governments argue over who is to blame for the current
crises in the North and Baltic seas, the common seal in this area
faces extinction,'' said Greenpeace spokesman Andrew Booth.
   The 12 scientists attending the meeting come from Britain,
Denmark, the Netherlands, Germany, Norway and Sweden, said
Greenpeace press spokeswomen Sue Adams.
   A virus is suspected as the cause of the seals' deaths. West
German environmentalists have blamed the virus on waste from
industry, but scientists say they do not really know its exact
cause. The deaths began early this year.
</TEXT>
