<1ST_LINE>u i PM-RefusenikFamily 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refusenik Family, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0506,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MOSCOW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prominent Refusenik Family Leaves for United States</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with arrival in Vienna. Pick up
7th pvs, `The family...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet Jewish refusenik family who
became the center of a superpower tug-of-war during the Moscow
summit emigrated to the West today, ending an 11-year struggle to
leave their homeland.
   Yuri and Tanya Zieman and their 12-year-old daughter Vera smiled
broadly as they stepped off an Aeroflot jet from Moscow to a warm
welcome from Western friends, U.S. Embassy officials and HIAS, an
organization that helps emigre Soviet Jews.
   Asked how she felt on arriving in the West at last, Mrs. Zieman
said simply, ``Stunned.'' Her daughter, clutching a welcome bouquet
from wellwishers, giggled, ``Excited.''
   The family will stay in Vienna until Friday, when they will fly
to Boston for a reunion with an older daughter who emigrated in
1987 with her husband.
   Several dozen friends and relatives gathered for a champagne
toast at Moscow's Sheremetyevo airport today to celebrate the
Ziemans' departure.
   ``I'm glad you're all here,'' Zieman told the group. ``I invite
you all to my new home.'' Zieman is a former computer specialist
who has held odd jobs since applying to emigrate, and was seriously
ill earlier in the year.
   In Vienna, he said he now feels ``much better. I'm so excited
that it sometimes seems to me that all my sicknesses are behind
me.''
   In Moscow, Mrs. Zieman called her departure ``one of the most
difficult moments of one's life.''
   ``It's like your own funeral in a way because most of the people
who are here today I won't see again _ my old teachers, relatives,
friends,'' she said.
   The family spent a sleepless night clearing customs at the
Moscow airport and saying goodbye to friends, she said.
   U.S. diplomats said President Reagan had planned to visit the
Zieman family at their south Moscow apartment during the summit
meeting May 29 to underscore the United States' concern for human
rights in the Soviet Union.
   But they said a high-ranking Soviet official told the Americans
that if Reagan visited the family they never would be allowed to
emigrate.
   Reagan did not visit the family, and two weeks after he left
they were told their application had been refused again and that
they should reapply in 1992. However, within weeks they received
official permission to leave.
   Soviet officials previously had rejected their applications for
emigration, saying the Ziemans had access to state secrets.
   The Zieman family was among the most prominent of those
remaining in the Soviet Union in the year since officials began
granting permission for the best-known refuseniks to emigrate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     08-10 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir: Israel Will Crush Any Attempt To Declare Palestinian State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said today that
Israel would maintain its control of the West Bank and crush any
Palestinian attempt to declare an independent state in the occupied
territories.
   Shamir's 20-minute speech came during a special session of
Israel's 120-seat parliament. It was convened to debate the
decision by King Hussein of Jordan to cut legal and administrative
ties with the West Bank, which Jordan annexed in 1950 and Israel
captured in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Left-wing politicians called for the debate to discuss Israel's
response to Hussein's announcement. They argued Israel should
explore peace prospects with the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   But Shamir, referring to a Palestinian initiative to declare a
Palestinian state in occupied lands, said:
   ``Israel will prevent in the most determined way any attempt to
carry out any idea _ to the extent that there are madmen who raise
it _ of establishing a Palestinian government. Such people will be
met with an iron fist that will leave no trace of their attempts.''
   The proposed declaration, which was made public last week, calls
for a Palestinian state in the West Bank, Gaza Strip, parts of the
Galilee and east Jerusalem. Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes
trading any Israeli-held territory for a peace pact.
   Shamir said Jordan's steps ``were aimed first and foremost
against the PLO'' and would ``harm the Arab residents and not the
state of Israel, which will continue to maintain legal and security
control as always.''
   In an interview published Tuesday with the Saudi Arabian
newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat, the chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, Yasser Arafat, was quoted as saying he
preferred not to say much about Jordan's disassociation from the
West Bank ``so as not to explode the situation with Jordan.''
   Shamir also appealed to Palestinians to end their uprising
against Israel. Since Dec. 8, 238 Palestinians and four Israelis
have died in the uprising.
   Yossi Sarid of the liberal Citizens Rights Movement criticized
both the Likud and the Labor Party led by Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres, saying they had failed to take advantage of Hussein's speech.
   Peres had relied on Hussein to negotiate on the behalf of
Palestinians and get around Israeli opposition to dealing with the
PLO, which Israel considers a terrorist organization.
   Gadi Yatziv from the Socialist Mapam Party criticized Shamir for
continuing ``to bomb, to explode, to deport, to arrest and to
harass the soul of the whole (Palestinian) people.''
   ``You must know there is nothing to be accomplished by
deportations when people are fighting for their freedom,'' Yatziv
said. ``Make peace now.''
   Since Dec. 8, Israel has deported 29 Palestinians.
   Also today, assailants hurled two firebombs at a military
vehicle in the West Bank town of Ramallah, wounding one soldier,
the army said.
   Troops closed and searched the area. Arab witnesses said
soldiers rounded up about 300 Palestinians and broke into shops
during the search.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
