<DOCNO> AP880810-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0848EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugAgentSlain     08-10 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Agent Slain,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killing Was A Mistake, Defendant Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. drug agent was killed following hours
of torture because Mexican drug kingpin Rafael Caro Quintero got
``carried away,'' a defendant in the murder case was seen saying on
videotape.
   Raul Lopez Alvarez, 28, made the comments in Spanish to an
undercover drug agent during a conversation at a Los Angeles hotel.
The 15-minute videotape, with English subtitles, was played for the
jury Tuesday.
   Drug agent Enrique Camarena was kidnapped in Guadalajara,
Mexico, in 1985. His body and that of his pilot were found buried
at a remote ranch in Mexico several weeks later. They had been
severely beaten and Camarena's skull was shattered.
   The videotape was of a conversation between Lopez and Abel
Reynoso, a Drug Enforcement Administration agent who posed as a
drug trafficker, the agent testified during the federal trial of
three Mexicans.
   ``A justifiable death never brings you problems,'' Lopez is
heard saying, adding that unjustifiable slayings do bring problems.
   ``Camarena was justifiable?'' Reynoso asked.
   ``That was a mistake,'' Lopez responded. ``The idea wasn't to
kill him.''
   A transcript showed Lopez suggesting the intitial plan was to
get Camarena to join forces with the drug traffickers _ ``to get
him on our side.''
   The killing took place because ``He's very hasty, because he's
young.''
   ``Who?'' Reynoso asked.
   ``Caro, because he's young,'' Lopez said. ``Because he's very
full of life. ... He got carried away.''
   Reynoso said Lopez admitted he was ``with the people watching
over Camarena.''
   The agent said Lopez told him that men using Mexican federal
police credentials lured Camarena into their car outside the U.S.
consulate in Guadalajara and that the agent was beaten with pipes
heated in fire.
   The government claims the crimes were orchestrated by Caro, 33,
who is imprisoned in Mexico where he and two others are being tried
for the offenses.
   During cross-examination, Lopez attorney Yolanda Barrera
suggested that Lopez made up everything he told the agent, basing
his story on what he read in newspapers and heard on the streets.
   Lopez and Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, are charged with murdering
Camarena and Camarena's pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar. Jesus Felix
Gutierrez, 38, is charged with helping Caro flee Mexico after
Camarena's slaying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
