<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Arafat-Jordan     08-10 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arafat-Jordan,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Says Jordan Cut Ties To West Bank Without Telling Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat has criticized
Jordan for failing to notify him before severing ties with the
Israeli-occupied lands, but he said the PLO is capable of taking
over Jordan's administrative role.
   Arafat also expressed anger at other Arab countries for failing
to tell him about Jordan's plans for the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
where an uprising against Israeli rule has been under way for eight
months.
   The remarks, Arafat's first since King Hussein of Jordan cut
ties with the occupied lands, were published Tuesday in the Saudi
Arabian newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat. Copies of the paper were
obtained in Manama today.
   In the interview, Arafat also said his Arab allies had failed to
adequately fund the uprising, and he ruled out sending a joint
Palestinian-Jordanian delegation to a proposed Middle East peace
conference.
   ``The PLO was not consulted beforehand and was not officially
notified until after the measures (by Jordan) were announced, when
it (the PLO) is the party that is directly concerned in all this,''
said Arafat.
   He insisted the Palestine Liberation Organization is capable of
assuming Jordan's administrative role in the occupied lands. He
assured the 1.5 million Palestinians living there that the PLO's
institutions ``are capable of absorbing everything.''
   Arafat declined to speak at length, he said, ``so as not to
explode the situation with Jordan.''
   King Hussein also recently scrapped a proposed West Bank
development project, dissolved the lower house of Parliament, where
30 out of 60 representatives were from the West Bank, and stopped
paying the salaries of about 21,000 teachers, health workers and
civil servants in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Hussein, whose nation lost the West Bank to Israel in 1967, said
he acted because the PLO was the sole legitimate representative of
Palestinians.
   Arafat noted Hussein said he had notified some Arab capitals
about Jordan's plans but that none had in turn told Arafat.
   The PLO leader also commented on an international peace
conference on the Middle East proposed by the United States.
Despite several visits to the region, Secretary of State George
Shultz has won little support for the plan.
   Arafat rejected sending a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation
to such a conference because ``that idea has been erased from our
dictionary even though Jordan has been repeating it.'' He said the
PLO prefers a pan-Arab delegation, adding: ``We accept the idea of
a joint delegation with Egypt.''
   The Arab world backed the PLO as the sole legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people at the Arab summit in
Algiers in June. Arab leaders also agreed to financially support
the Palestinian uprising with $128 million in aid, but Arafat said
they had not fulfilled their commitment.
   Since Dec. 8, more than 230 Palestinians and four Israelis have
been killed in the uprising in the occupied lands. The uprising is
led by underground leaders with ties to the PLO.
   Arafat was interviewed in Bulgaria before returning to the Iraqi
capital of Baghdad. The trip to Bulgaria followed a meeting of the
PLO Central Council to debate the implications of King Hussein's
announcement.
</TEXT>
