<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NavyDeath     08-10 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Of Four Instructors Rejected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy admiral has rejected the appeals
of four rescue instructors charged in the death of an airman who
was dragged into a swimming pool while classmates sang to drown out
his screams for help.
   The decision means the instructors have exhausted their appeals.
   The four had apealed the fines and reductions in rank they
received in June as non-judicial punishment in the death of Lee
Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   He died March 2 after being pulled from a training pool at the
Pensacola Naval Air Station's Rescue Swimmer School.
   Vice Adm. Ron Thunman, chief of naval education and training,
found the punishments appropriate, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   The instructors are Petty Officers David J. Smith, Richard
Blevins, Frankie Deaton and John Zelenock. They were charged with
conspiracy to commit battery. Two other Navy personnel are awaiting
courts-martial.
   A court-martial for Lt. Thomas Torchia, the school's former
officer-in-charge, was postponed three days until Aug. 25, said Lt.
Cmdr. Dennis Hessler.
   A fifth instructor, Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael Combe, faces
court-martial Aug. 29 on charges of involuntary manslaughter,
conspiracy to commit battery and battery.
   Combe could receive more than three years in a military jail and
a bad conduct or dishonorable discharge. If convicted, Torchia
faces three months' confinement, loss of pay and a reprimand.
   The Navy has accused Combe of holding Mirecki's head under water
after other instructors had physically forced the recruit back into
the pool.
   Mirecki had been pushed back into the pool after he panicked,
climbed out and shouted that he was quitting the course. The
instructors ordered other recruits to turn their backs to the pool
and sing the national anthem.
   At an investigative hearing, a pathologist testified Mirecki
suffered heart failure followed by drowning.
</TEXT>
