<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Ballet     08-10 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Ballet,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American To Choreograph Avant-Garde Work For Chinese Dancers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American who made her choreographic debut
with the Broadway show ``Oh! Calcutta!'' plans to add abstract
dancing to the repertoire of China's national ballet company.
   ``Their repertoire at the moment is tried and true classics like
Swan Lake and Giselle,'' Margo Sappington told reporters today. ``I
can push them beyond what they're used to.''
   Miss Sappington, who has choreographed ballets for the Joffrey
Ballet, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater and the Houston Ballet, is to
create a contemporary work for 15 to 20 members of the Central
Ballet of China, the nation's most prestigious dance group.
   She said her new 25-minute work for the Beijing troupe, to be
called ``Heliotrope,'' will be set to a violin concerto by Du
Mingxin, head of the composition department at the Beijing's
Central Conservatory of Music. It will premiere at the Tianqiao
Theater on Sept. 18.
   Li Chengxiang, director of the Central Ballet, said the work
will be performed three or four times in Beijing and then will
become part of the troupe's repertoire.
   Miss Sappington said she hopes ``this kind of abstract ballet
will bring in some new people, some young people.''
   The standards of the Chinese dancers are very high, she said,
and classical ballet will provide the base ``on which I hope to
embellish.''
   The Central Ballet was founded in 1959, but during the Cultural
Revolution of 1966-76, it was allowed to perform only revolutionary
works such as ``Red Detachment of Women.''
   Since then, the troupe has expanded its repertoire and won
international honors for its mastery of Western classical works. In
recent years, the company toured the United States, Britain and the
Soviet Union with a repertoire that includes Chinese and Western
classics as well as works from the Cultural Revolution.
   The dancers, like Chinese athletes, are recruited in elementary
school and trained in special schools.
   Other Western ballet figures such as Rudolf Nureyev, Beryl Grey
and Maria Fay have coached Chinese dancers, but Miss Sappington
says she will be the first to choreograph a ballet ``from scratch.''
   She said the Chinese are excited about the chance to improvise.
   ``I hope this creative experience will make a lasting
relationship for cultural exchange not only for me but also for
other Western choreographers and the Central Ballet,'' she said.
   Miss Sappington made her debut with ``Oh! Calcutta!'' the
Broadway musical that won notoriety for its nudity. She also has
worked with the Harkness Ballet, the Pennsylvania Ballet, the
Nederlands Dans Theatre, Aterballetto in Italy and the Milwaukee
Ballet.
   The Coca-Cola Co. is sponsoring her visit to China and her
project with the Central Ballet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0941EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PostmasterGeneral     08-10 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Postmaster General,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postmaster General Urges Attention to Details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service should pay attention to the
little things that keep customers happy, says Postmaster General
Anthony M. Frank.
   ``Give an extra smile, open the door for the customer who comes
at one minute after five, and ask an employee, `What do you
think?''' Frank said Tuesday to about 1,500 delegates at the 85th
convention of the National League of Postmaters. The group
represents more than 22,000 postmasters nationwide.
   The Postal Service lost customers to private delivery businesses
because of service cutbacks imposed in February, Frank said. The
cutbacks and a rate hike in April did ``serious harm to the postal
service's public image,'' he said.
   Frank urged postmasters to improve employee relations and help
educate the public about the postal service by giving speeches and
conducting open houses.
   Retail services eliminated because of cutbacks are scheduled to
be restored Sept. 10.
</TEXT>
