<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Swindall-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0431 08-10 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Corrects spelling of LeChasney, sted LeChansey, in grafs 4,10
pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall met with the House ethics
committee investigating whether he violated the law or House rules,
and he gave the panel copies of tape recordings made during a
federal money laundering probe last year.
   Swindall met behind closed doors for nearly three hours Tuesday
with the House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct.
   The committee decided in June to conduct a preliminary
investigation to determine if Swindall violated the law or House
rules in pursuing an $850,000 home construction loan after being
told it likely would be financed with drug money he would be
helping to launder.
   Swindall said he gave the committee copies of tape recordings
made last year of conversations between Swindall and two men,
Charles LeChasney, who later was indicted on money laundering
charges, and Michael Mullaney, an Internal Revenue Service
undercover agent.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr in Atlanta refused earlier to provide
the committee with the tape recordings because he said the money
laundering investigation has not been completed. Swindall has not
been charged in connection with the federal probe.
   Swindall said that among other things, he also gave the
committee a copy of a constituent newsletter listing a ``summary of
facts'' about the case.
   ``All I am doing is turning over information that I promised to
turn over to the ethics committee so that they can look into my
request, which was that they consider all of the information,''
Swindall said.
   Committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., and other committee
members refused to answer questions about the investigation or
about the meeting with Swindall.
   Swindall requested the ethics committee probe after The Atlanta
Journal and The Atlanta Constitution obtained copies of the tape
recordings and reported details of the loan negotiations.
   Swindall at one point accepted a $150,000 check from LeChasney,
but returned it uncashed several days later. The tapes show that he
broke off the negotiations after Mullaney told him he would have to
accept the loan proceeds in cash and sign a receipt for them.
</TEXT>
