<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HolyHoney     08-10 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holy Honey,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bee Hive In Church Drips Holy Honey On Cathedral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bees that made their home in Trinity
Episcopal Cathedral's rafters for the last decade left a donation
before being evicted.
   At least 1,000 pounds of honey remain in the walls of the
church, said the Rev. John Fricke, senior pastor.
   ``It drips a little holy honey when it gets hot,'' Fricke said.
``It comes down a pillar support right onto the floor. We've put
aluminum foil around the pillar to make kind of a drip dish. It
tastes wonderful.''
   In July, the church hired Roger Miller of Miller Apiaries to
remove the bees and honeycombs so workers could safely paint the
windows and gutter frames.
   Miller said he vacuumed up about 15,000 bees and turned them
loose and exterminated the remaining 15,000 to 35,000 bees lodged
in wall cavities beyond his reach.
   ``I salvaged about 100 pounds of the honey from a two-inch
slot,'' Miller said. ``I'm going to bottle it and put these little
gold crosses on them. I'll give it back to the church, and we've
talked about selling it with a slogan like `Honey From on High.'''
   The church has not decided whether to sell the honey, said
Fricke. But any proceeds might go toward rebuilding Trinity's
50-year-old pipe organ.
</TEXT>
