<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-PhoneTap     08-10 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Phone Tap,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Resigns In India In Phone-Tapping Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief minister of an
opposition-governed southern state resigned today after he was held
responsible for tapping the telephones of journalists and rival
politicians, a news report said.
   Chief Minister Ramakrishna Hegde, the highest elected official
in Karnataka state, denied involvement in the bugging, but accepted
responsibility and said he was stepping down on moral grounds, the
United News of India reported.
   Hegde told a news conference in New Delhi he would submit a
formal letter of resignation to the state governor on Thursday, the
news agency said.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi on Tuesday accused Hegde, leader of
the opposition Janata Party in Karnataka, of violating laws and
invading the privacy of citizens.
   Gandhi made his comments in Parliament after the Times of India
newspaper said police were listening to the telephone conversations
of 51 politicians and journalists in Karnataka. Those affected
included state leaders of Gandhi's Congress Party, a newspaper
editor and members of Hegde's party.
   Hegde has been faced with mounting dissatisfaction in the Janata
Party but survived two votes of confidence in the state legislature
in recent months. Some of the dissent has been caused by the
upcoming merger of the Janata Party with three other opposition
groups, a move Hegde supports.
   Under the Indian Telegraph Act, tapping of telephone lines is
permitted only if criminal activity is suspected.
   ``The Karnataka government has violated rules under the act. We
will definitely look into it and, if need be, amend the rules to
see that such violations do not take place,'' Gandhi said Tuesday.
   He denied charges the federal government also had ordered the
bugging of telephone lines of opposition political leaders.
</TEXT>
