<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CondomStudy     08-10 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condom Study,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Cites Risk in Cutoff of Funds for Condom Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has cut off funding for a
study on the effectiveness of condoms in preventing the spread of
AIDS among homosexuals for fear of infecting study participants, it
was reported today.
   The Los Angeles Times said about $2.6 million was halted for the
study by the University of California at Los Angeles. Tests
involving people had not yet begun.
   The combination of high AIDS infection rates and the possibility
of condom failure prompted the cutoff, said Dr. Jeffrey Perlman,
chief of contraceptive evaluation for the National Institute of
Child Health and Human Development.
   ``What has happened in the last two years is that gays in Los
Angeles became supersaturated with the virus so that to go ahead
with this study would mean that there is going to be a large
proportion of the recruits who would have become infected,'' said
Perlman, the grant's project officer. ``On that basis, it really
came to an ethical issue.''
   Dr. Roger Detels, the head of the UCLA study, refused to comment
on the cancellation of the project's funds.
   The money would have been used to study how effective condoms
are in stopping the spread of the AIDS virus during anal sex.
   Project workers already have spent $1 million in federal funds
on laboratory tests to determine the abilities of different kinds
and brands of condoms to inhibit AIDS transmission.
</TEXT>
