<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pancho'sHead     08-10 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pancho's Head,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>El Pasoans Think Secretive Yale Club Hides Pancho Villa's Skull</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skull referred to in Yale University's
secret Skull and Bones society belongs to Mexican revolutionary
Pancho Villa, a group of history buffs believes.
   A lawyer for the society, which Vice President George Bush
joined in his Yale days, says the story is unfounded.
   The group of about a dozen history and archaeology enthusiasts
has tried to persuade Villa's widow and the Mexican government to
sue to recover the skull and return it to Villa's grave in Mexico.
   Francisco ``Pancho'' Villa was the leader of the last military
invasion of the United States mainland when his forces raided
Columbus, N.M., in 1916. He was assassinated in 1923 and grave
robbers stole his skull in 1926.
   The El Paso group members, who discuss their interest over lunch
every Wednesday, began the quest for Villa's skull about 18 months
ago.
   They read the memoirs of Arizona native Ben Williams, who said a
Skull and Bones member told him the society had the skull, said
Alex Apostolides, curator of El Paso's Wilderness Museum and a
member of the group.
   Enidcott P. Davison, a Connecticut lawyer who says he speaks for
the secret Yale society, said it does not have Villa's skull.
   The El Paso group also wrote an appeal to Bush asking him to
persuade the club to surrender the skull if it has it. Bush's
office in Washington confirmed the letter had been received, but
said no reply had been written.
   Neither the Mexican government nor Villa's 92-year-old widow has
expressed interest in suing. The El Paso group cannot sue because
it has no standing in the case.
</TEXT>
