<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BakkerSuit     08-10 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bakker Suit,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Couple's Lawsuit Against Bakkers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed a couple's
lawsuit accusing Jim and Tammy Bakker of fraud and racketeering.
   The suit, filed in July 1987, accused the Bakkers and former PTL
Executive Director Richard Dortch of overselling $1,000
partnerships guaranteeing three free nights' lodging at PTL's
Heritage Grand Hotel each year for life.
   U.S. District Judge Robert D. Potter on Monday said that David
and Sarah Combs of West Virginia had no grounds to sue under the
federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act and that
the suit was filed in the wrong state.
   Ryan Hovis, an attorney for Bakker, said the ruling averts a
possible class-action lawsuit in which about 55,000 lifetime
partners could have been eligible to collect damages.
   Two other suits are pending against the Bakkers, Hovis said. One
is another RICO lawsuit filed by a PTL partner and the other was
filed by PTL.
   Bakker left PTL in March 1987 amid a sex-and-money scandal, and
the organization he built is mired in bankruptcy court with debts
estimated at $130 million.
   Bakker said he and his wife were ``absolutely elated'' by the
dismissal.
   ``It's just confirmation of what Tammy and I have said all
along: Once responsible people start reviewing these claims by
these people who are trying to hurt us, they'll know that we've
done nothing wrong,'' Bakker said.
   The Combses had charged that PTL sold more lifetime partnerships
than the hotel could accommodate and that they couldn't get a
reservation.
</TEXT>
