<HEAD>Feds Raid Defense Contractor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized records of a West
Virginia defense contractor in an investigation into allegedly
defective life rafts sold to the Navy, a newspaper reported today.
   The Defense Criminal Investigative Service and the FBI on Monday
raided Rubber Crafters Inc., a Grantsville, W.Va., company that
received $17.3 million to produce a 25-man lifeboat from 1984 to
1987, The Pittsburgh Press said.
   ``Voluminous amounts of records were seized,'' U.S. Attorney
William Kolibash said. ``The next step is to see what's in the
records and what action to take.''
   An affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in Wheeling, W.Va.,
quoted unidentified employees of Rubber Crafters as saying that
rafts were constructed of inferior material and shipped to Navy
supply centers in Norfolk, Va., and Oakland, Calif., and that
records were falsified and tests rigged to conceal the defects.
   ``We have no comments,'' said a woman who answered the phone at
Rubber Crafters today. She refused to identify herself.
   Kolibash said the investigation is not related to the
wide-ranging probe of alleged bribery in the awarding of military
contracts.
