<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DeportedNazi     08-10 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deported Nazi,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Orders Former Nazi Camp Guard Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Nazi concentration camp guard
arrested in northern Italy was deported today to West Germany,
police said.
   Officials in West Germany said Anton Maloth, 76, could be freed
when he arrives in Munich because no criminal charges are pending
against him.
   Maloth was sentenced to death in Czechoslovakia in 1948 for war
crimes, but Italy and Czechoslovakia have no extradition treaty.
West German citizens cannot by law be extradited to a foreign
country.
   A police official in Bolzano, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Maloth left Verona this afternoon on a plane bound
for Munich.
   The official said Maloth held an expired West German passport,
which was why he was being sent to that country. He said Maloth had
been expelled to West Germany from Italy twice before, in 1965 and
1972.
   Czechoslovakia submitted an extradition request Tuesday. But
even if the two countries had an extradition treaty, Italian law
forbids extraditing someone facing the death penalty because Italy
has no capital punishment.
   Maloth was arrested last week at his wife's home in Merano.
   Vienna-based Nazi hunter Simon Wiesenthal said Maloth had been
hiding with his family in Italy for 15 years. Maloth was a member
of the Nazi SS and a guard at the Theresienstadt concentration camp
in wartime Czechoslovakia.
   In West Germany, the Foreign Ministry today confirmed that
Maloth was being deported and would arrive in Munich today.
   A ministry spokesman, Peter Rothen, said in Bonn that he did not
know whether Maloth would be taken into custody in Munich.
   ``We have determined that he is a German citizen, and therefore
under the constitution cannot be extradited,'' Rothen said.
   Klaus Schacht, a West German prosecutor in charge of the Maloth
case, said investigators intend to question Maloth. ``When Maloth
comes to Munich, I will have the border police ask him where he
intends to settle in West Germany, and then we will question him,''
Schacht said.
   ``So far, there are no criminal charges against him,'' the
prosecutor said.
</TEXT>
