<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietInspections     08-10 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspections,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Wind Up Inspections At Two Sites As Part of INF Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet missile experts today completed
their inspections of U.S. cruise missiles at two sites in Belgium
under the new treaty to eliminate medium-range nuclear weapons, a
U.S. spokesman said.
   U.S. Army Capt. John Driggers said a team of 10 Soviet
inspectors wound up their work at 8 a.m. at Florennes Air Base, 40
miles south of Brussels.
   A second group of 10 experts finished their missile checks an
hour later at the European Repair Facility at Gosselies, 10 miles
north of Florennes.
   The two teams began their tasks on Tuesday under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, which gives the Soviet
Union and the United States an unprecedented opportunity to inspect
each other's facilities.
   The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States and five
Western European countries. U.S. experts are inspecting 133 sites
in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   Each inspection can last up to 24 hours, with a possible
eight-hour extension.
   Driggers said the Soviet teams and their American escorts would
write up, as required, reports on the inspections before returning
to Brussels in the afternoon.
   He said it was not yet known when the missile experts would
leave for Moscow. They arrived on Monday and officially notified
authorities Tuesday morning that they wanted to inspect the two
sites.
   It was expected they would leave Brussels later today or
Thursday.
   Sixteen ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares are kept
at the Florennes base along with four launchers and eight spares,
according to U.S. officials. The base houses the 485th U.S.
Tactical Missile Wing.
   The sleek, ground-hugging weapons arrived in March 1985.
   There was no indication how many unarmed cruise missiles are
currently at the repair facility, which is run by the Belgian
defense contractor Sabca. On June 21, there were 55 missiles at the
plant, according to U.S. officials.
   The operation is the only one of its kind in Europe set up to
maintain and repair the weapons.
   Soviet teams earlier visited missile sites in Germany, Britain
and the Netherlands as part of the 60-day inspection process that
began July 1. They have not yet gone to sites in Italy.
   The treaty provides for elimination within three years of all
U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges from 300 to 3,400
miles. It was signed in December in Washington by President Reagan
and Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MayorsRace     08-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayors Race,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Councilman Won't Hire Consultants Whose Memos Castigated Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayoral challenger Zev Yaroslavsky has
disavowed memos from campaign consultants disparaging Mayor Tom
Bradley's intelligence.
   ``They are not my consultants nor are they any longer under
consideration,'' the city councilman said. ``I do not agree with
many of their ideas and I find many of their statements to be
insulting, insensitive and not reflective of my views.''
   The memos published in Tuesday's Los Angeles Times came from the
consulting firm BAD.
   ``The reason why BAD thinks you can beat Bradley is: You've got
50 IQ points on him (and that's no compliment.) But your IQ
advantage is of no electoral advantage if you don't use it,'' the
consultants wrote.
   The consultants also predicted Bradley ``will excite black
voters to outvote the white electorate especially if there is a
runoff where his mayoral office is seen as jeopardized by a
perfidious Jew.''
   Bradley is black and Yaroslavsky Jewish.
   Bradley said of the memos, ``The background quality by which
they propose to start the campaign is so offensive.''
   Yaroslavsky aide Ann Hollister said the memos were stolen her
office. The newspaper said the documents were delivered anonymously
to a reporter.
   Yaroslavsky, who plans to challenge Bradley in the non-partisan
mayoral primary in April, said he did not ask for the memos.
   ``I have a very high personal regard for Tom Bradley,'' he said
Tuesday. ``I would not in any way countenance demeaning his
personal stature, his intelligence or his commitment to what he
thinks is right.''
</TEXT>
