<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-JimmyCarter     08-10 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Jimmy Carter,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter To Be Honored For Climbing Mount Kilimanjaro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter and
two of his sons will be honored by the government for climbing
Mount Kilimanjaro, Africa's highest mountain, a government-owned
paper said today.
   The 64-year-old Carter, leading a 17-member party through snow
flurries and near-zero visibility, reached the volcanic mountain's
second highest peak, Gilman's Point, early Monday after a three-day
climb.
   Reaching Gilman's Point at 18,640 feet traditionally is
considered a successful climb, although the 19,340-foot Uhuru Peak
farther around the summit's crater is the mountain's highest point.
   Eight people who began the climb dropped out, including Rosalynn
Carter and three of the Carters' grandchildren. Mrs. Carter climbed
to 17,500 feet, while grandchildren, Jason, 13, James Early, 12,
and Sarah, 10, reached 17,000 feet.
   The party started down the mountain Monday and arrived at the
northern Tanzania town of Moshi late Tuesday.
   The group left today for four days of viewing wildlife in
Tangire, Manyara, Serengeti and the Ngorongoro Crater national
parks.
   President Ali Hassan Mwinyi will present certificates to Carter
and his sons, Jack, 41, and Jim ``Chip'', 38, at a ceremony marking
the climb Sunday in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania's capial, according to
the government-owned Daily News.
   Carter and his party leave Dar es Salaam on Sunday for
neighboring Kenya.
</TEXT>
