<1ST_LINE>r w PM-California-Oil     08-10 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California-Oil,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Negotiators Agree to Prohibit Drilling Off Northern
California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators have agreed to a
year's prohibition on oil and gas drilling off the northern coast
of California, Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said today.
   Panetta said the action came Tuesday as a joint conference
committee continued to negotiate differences in the fiscal 1989
Interior Department appropriations bills passed by the two chambers.
   The language would bar any sales of offshore petroleum leases in
Area 91 through Oct. 1, 1989, as well as prohibit any test drilling
in the area, according to Panetta.
   He said the renewed ban would represent the end of eight years
of tussling over the northern California waters with Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel and his predecessor, James Watt.
   ``We can finally declare victory over the Watt-Hodel effort to
put our coast up for sale,'' Panetta said. ``As hard as this
administration tried, it failed in its attempt to allow oil and gas
drilling up and down the California coast.
   ``Now the focus turns to the upcoming election,'' he said. ``The
next president will determine the future of the California coast.
The candidates must tell us whether they are prepared to implement
a comprehensive national energy policy that emphasizes good
stewardship of our natural resources and preserves the most
sensitive areas of our coastline.''
</TEXT>
