<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru   08-10 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0532,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Calls for New Round of Nicaraguan Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 4th graf ``Shultz left...'' to update with Shultz flying
ot Ecuador.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
called for renewed Nicaraguan peace talks after meeting with
President Oscar Arias, who said he thinks Washington is more
interested than ever in a diplomatic solution.
   Shultz is on a mission to involve the United States more closely
in the year-old Central American peace initiative, which Arias
authored.
   After meeting with the Costa Rican leader, he flew to
Tegucigalpa for talks with Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo and
later to El Salvador for a visit with acting President Rodolfo
Castillo Claramount. He flies home Thursday.
   Shultz left Costa Rica at 8:19 a.m. (10:19 a.m. EDT) on a
four-hour flight to Ecuador, the last stop of his Latin American
tour, to attend the inauguration of President-elect Rodrigo Borja.
   Shultz said today that other Central American governments view
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government as ``way out of step with
everybody else.''
   ``From the standpoint of the people of Nicaragua, their
government is a complete failure,'' he said on NBC-TV's ``Today''
show. ``Around them is freedom, there is democracy asserting itself
more and more.''
   The visit to Quito gives Shultz a further opportunity to talk
with Latin and Central American leaders. Among those attending the
inauguration are presidents Fidel Castro of Cuba and Daniel Ortega
of Nicaragua.
   Shultz is scheduled to meet privately with the new president, in
addition to President Virgilio Barco of Colombia, but he ruled out
meeting with Ortega or Castro.
   Castro ``doesn't deserve it,'' he told NBC. ``He hasn't done
anything for his people. And he is part of the problem here in
Central America.''
   On Tuesday, Shultz said the U.S.-backed Contra rebels are ready
to return to peace negotiations with Nicaragua, but not in Managua,
the capital.
   The most recent round of talks broke off June 9.
   ``I hope there will be another round of negotiations, not in
Managua but in another country ... like for example, Costa Rica,''
he told reporters after meeting Arias.
   The Contras insisted on another, more neutral, location before
the last round of talks but then agreed to return to Managua.
   The talks are aimed at establishing a permanent cease-fire in
the nearly 7-year-old war. A temporary truce took effect March 21
and has been extended several times by the Sandinistas, who accuse
the Contras of numerous cease-fire violations.
   Arias himself left for Quito shortly after meeting with Shultz
and told reporters at the airport, ``Washington is attaching more
importance to Central American problems.''
   ``I believe Washington is convinced _ now more than ever _ that
it is worthwhile to attempt peace through dialogue and
negotiation,'' the Costa Rican president added. Arias has long been
critical of U.S. support for the Nicaraguan rebels.
   It was Arias who conceived the regional peace plan that was
signed Aug. 7, 1987 by himself and the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Honduras, and Guatemala. The effort brought him last
year's Nobel Peace Prize, but peace remains a distant hope in the
region.
   Arias said his discussion with Shultz involved nothing new.
   ``Mainly, I was informed of his visit to some of the South
American countries, and I told him my impression of events in
recent days,'' Arias said. ``But really, I've heard nothing new,
because between the last time I saw him and now, nothing special
has really happened.''
   They last met in June.
   Arias noted that he recently wrote Ortega asking the Nicaraguan
president to reopen closed news media, release about 40 people
arrested at a recent anti-government demonstration and renew
negotiations with the Contras. He offered Costa Rica as a site for
new talks.
   Shultz's 10-day, nine-nation visit to Latin America is his third
in a little more than a month. He began with a stop in Guatemala
City for a meeting with the foreign ministers of Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala.
   On Monday, a bomb damaged three cars of Shultz's motorcade in
Bolivia but caused no injuries.
   ``That incident only underlined what we're fighting for and
against,'' Shultz told NBC. ``We're fighting for decency and
democracy and freedom. And those who are against those things are
willing to use violent tactics against us. That should only
underscore our resolve.''
</TEXT>
