<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rowan-Barry     08-10 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan-Barry,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Denies Report He Offered Deal to Rowan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry says
there's no truth to a published report that an aide offered
columnist Carl Rowan lenient treatment in his shooting of a
trespassing teen-ager if Rowan promised to stop criticizing Barry's
administration.
   ``Neither I nor Mr. (Herbert O.) Reid would ever interfere with
or attempt to influence prosecutorial decisions by the corporation
counsel to prosecute the Rowan case,'' Barry said in a statement
Tuesday.
   The Legal Times newspaper on Monday quoted two sources it did
not identify as saying Reid, the mayor's counsel and confidant, had
tried to make a deal through the columnist's son, Carl Rowan Jr.
   Rowan's son on Tuesday said he was prepared to testify that
Barry and Reid had hinted in separate telephone conversations that
city officials would give his father such treatment if the
journalist would write columns more favorable to the city.
   Barry called the younger Rowan's statement ``a distortion of the
truth.''
   Rowan, a syndicated columnist, is scheduled to go to trial Sept.
22 on a charge of using an unregistered handgun and unregistered
ammunition to shoot Benjamin Smith, 18, of Chevy Chase, Md., on
June 14. The columnist had discovered the youth and at least one
companion taking a late-night dip in Rowan's backyard pool. Rowan
told police he shot Smith in the hand because he thought the teen
was lunging for him.
   If found guilty of both charges, Rowan could be sentenced to two
years in jail and a $2,000 fine.
   Barry said in his statement , ``It's idiocy to even suggest that
anybody in my administration would want to trade leniency for Mr.
Rowan for a positive column.''
   Reid charged that the Rowan family was trying to divert
attention from the charges.
   ``It's a discretionary tactic and it's successful,'' Reid told
The Washington Post. ``They were able to divert the attention from
whether or not he had a gun to how the city's being run and whether
there's corruption in the district.''
   Rowan, in a July 1987 column, criticized the district government
for accusing U.S. attorneys of racism whenever they pursued charges
against corrupt black officials.
   ``Enough members of the administration of Mayor Marion Barry
have pleaded guilty and gone to jail to make it clear that
corruption exists,'' Rowan wrote.
</TEXT>
