<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protests,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Falwell Joins Anti-Abortion Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell joined about 200
protesters today at the latest in a series of anti-abortion
demonstrations at a clinic here, and police arrested more than 40
people for blocking the entrances.
   The founder of the Moral Majority said he would use his TV
ministry and his pulpit at his Virginia church to encourage such
protests. ``We can break the back of the abortion industry and stop
the holocaust,'' he said.
   Police today began arresting demonstrators who ignored their
order to stop blocking the entrances to the Feminist Women's Health
Center.
   By 10:45 a.m., more than 40 had been arrested.
   During earlier protests over the past three weeks, 276 people
were arrested. Dozens remain in jail because they refuse to give
their names.
   Police and clinic workers today helped carry a patient into the
clinic after she was blocked by protesters sitting at the entrance.
The patient shouted at the protesters, ``Leave me alone.''
   Falwell said he came to Atlanta to endorse the strategy of the
group, Operation Rescue, and to bring a $10,000 check to pay for
the bail of Operation Rescue leader Randall Terry, who was arrested
during a protest last week.
