<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 1stLd-Writethru a0412 08-10 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0412,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Concedes It May Re-Evaluate Position On Aid Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with White House saying it
likely will have to reassess position on Democratic Contra aid
plan. Editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
today that the Reagan administration will have to reconsider its
opposition to a Democratic-sponsored Contra aid plan if a rival
Republican package fails.
   Fitzwater told reporters the administration still hopes that a
rival measure sponsored by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole will be
enacted, ``but if not, and something else happens, we'll go to
`Plan B' '' _ the bill sponsored by Senate Majority Leader Robert
C. Byrd.
   The spokesman said that if the administration is forced to
reassess its opposition to the Byrd bill, ``that'll be a hard
decision.''
   ``We have a lot of problems with the Byrd bill, a lot of
reservations about it. We don't like it. It doesn't do the job. ...
`Plan B' at the moment is to consider the Byrd bill.''
   The Byrd plan would provide the Contras with $21.1 million in
non-lethal ``humanitarian'' assistance beginning Oct. 1 to sustain
them through next March. This would include $10 million for
relocating Contra soldiers into Nicaraguan society, a feature hotly
protested by some conservatives.
   It also sets up possible House and Senate votes this fall on
releasing $16.3 million in already approved military aid from
warehouses in Central America if President Reagan certifies that
Nicaragua's government has disrupted peace efforts.
   An alternative proposed by Dole, R-Kan., includes the $21.1
million in non-lethal aid, provides for the release of the $16.3
million in warehoused military supplies and adds $20 million in new
arms assistance. Dole is being urged to drop that proposal and
support the Byrd plan.
   The administration has said it believes the Byrd bill provides
inadequate mechanisms to get aid delivered to the Contras.
   Fitzwater's latest statements came a day after Democratic and
Republican senators appeared close to a grudging agreement on a new
U.S. aid plan for the resistance fighters, although they accused
each other of seeking political advantage.
   After days of inconclusive negotiations, some Republican
senators said many of their number appeared ready to accept the
Democratic-drafted compromise Contra aid plan. That package holds
out the possibility of releasing stockpiled arms to the rebels
opposing Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   If agreement is reached, it will be because a majority of
Republicans realized that the alternative may be no aid at all,
these senators said.
   ``I go home with high hopes,'' Byrd, D-W.Va., said Tuesday at
the end of another long day of repeated conferences on and off the
Senate floor.
   But he added: ``Time is running out. The sands in the hour glass
are falling, one by one.''
   Byrd made clear that if there is to be a unified Senate position
on Contra aid, including the possibility of renewing some military
assistance, the concessions will have to be made by the GOP.
   ``On my side of the aisle, it's a fragile coalition and I'm not
going to tamper with it,'' Byrd said. ``There's just no more give
on this side. Our coalition would just fall apart.''
   Several key Republican senators, most of them moderates, urged
that a compromise be reached, saying the alternative might be no
Contra aid of any kind.
   The Democratic plan would provide immediate humanitarian
assistance but would not provide military aid unless both House and
Senate approved a subsequent request from President Reagan.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., appealing to his colleagues to rally
behind a single, unified package that would be sponsored by both
Byrd and Dole, told the Senate: ``It's far more important than any
political consideration that if, even in this election year, we can
speak with one voice'' to Nicaragua's Marxist Sandinista rulers.
   ``We're so close,'' Rudman said. ``It's almost at the point
where we ought to join together. ... It would take only a small
concession from the majority and minority leaders to do it.''
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla, a strong Contra-aid supporter, accused
Republicans of playing politics with the issue and said the
reluctance of GOP senators to embrace the Democratic aid package is
``a real test of their sincerity.''
   ``If they really want aid to the Contras, I don't see how in the
world they can turn their backs on this proposal,'' Boren said,
adding that it represents the only way to get aid to the Contras
through Congress without a filibuster by aid opponents.
   Contra aid has become more sensitive for Democrats as the
campaign for the presidency unfolds.
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis opposes Contra
aid. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas., his vice presidential running
mate, has voted for it.
   Some Democrats say their GOP counterparts want a clear
up-or-down Senate vote to dramatize that difference and embarrass
Dukakis.
   Some Republicans see Byrd's Contra aid proposal as a means to
provide political ``cover'' on the issue, insulating Dukakis and
Bentsen.
   But some disagreed that politics is a central element.
   ``It's not giving Dukakis and Bentsen cover ... or to give our
side cover,'' Dole said. ``We're trying to help the Contras.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hamadi-Pilot 1stLd-Writethru a0539 08-10 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi-Pilot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot in 1985 Hijacking Says Hamadi Could Be Telling Truth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 3, Testrake said, to include Hamadi's first name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a TWA jet airliner hijacked in
1985 said today the admitted hijacker of the plane could be telling
the truth when he testified that he didn't kill a U.S. Navy diver.
   ``It's possible that he didn't pull the trigger, but he and his
partner were certainly in full concert throughout that whole
ordeal,'' said pilot John Testrake in an interview on ``CBS This
Morning.'' West German law, like U.S. law, makes accomplices
responsible for a crime committed by the other.
   Testrake said he could not say whether Mohammed Ali Hamadi, who
testified in his trial in Frankfurt, West Germany, on Tuesday that
he had taken part in the hijacking, was the ringleader.
   ``I think that he was, but it's been three years now and I
recognize that memory plays tricks,'' said Testrake, who is to
testify in Hamadi's trial.
   ``I remember that he was the one who spoke German and seemed to
be in command of the situation in the cockpit at the time (diver
Robert Dean) Stethem was murdered, and he was conducting the radio
conversations with the tower and demanding that they comply with
their wishes,'' Testrake said.
   Hamadi testified that he pleaded with his partner not to kill
Stethem. Testrake was not asked about that part of Hamadi's
testimony.
   The pilot said the United States ``should shoulder a a good
share of blame for a lot of the conflict that's going on in the
Middle East.''
   But he said hijacking is a ``violent, desperate act that we have
to stop.'' He said tightened security has diminished the threat.
   Testrake said he would like to see Hamadi ``put away quietly for
a good long time until his attitude improves.'' But he said no
useful purpose would be served by putting him to death. Hamadi
faces a mandatory life sentence if convicted of Stethem's death.
</TEXT>
