<DOCNO> AP880810-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-10 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0840</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   
   Aug. 4
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on disclosing unpublished information:
   Every now and then some court plays variations on the pernicious
theme that reporters are obligated to help the police.
   This has happened again in California, where an appellate court
ruled that a reporter and photographer had a duty to disclose their
``unpublished information'' about an arrest they witnessed.
   Taken at face value, the judicial rationale may seem persuasive:
newspeople are as much obliged as anyone else to testify about what
they witnessed in public.
   But second thought suggests, as a Los Angeles Times lawyer
noted, that converting reporters into ``automatic witnesses'' would
seriously weaken their rightful posture of objectivity.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 3
   Charleston (W.Va.) Daily Mail on Michael Dukakis and foreign
policy:
   Democrats are attempting to soft-pedal Michael Dukakis' lack of
foreign policy experience. They say he supports a strong defense.
   But former Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger, in an open
letter to Dukakis in Time magazine, questions whether the
Democratic nominee really is committed to a strong defense. ...
   The Reagan era has proven anew that the Soviets negotiate only
if faced with strength and resolve on matters of defense.
   Dukakis does not seem to have learned that yet, and this country
can't afford to give him on-the-job training.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 7
   Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal on the health of presidential
candidates:
   The health of the candidates for president is of vital concern
to Americans.
   While the campaign itself appears to be a pretty good treadmill
test, most voters would like to make sure that physically and
psychologically, both Democrat (Michael) Dukakis and Republican
George Bush are well. ...
   Neither candidate has released all his medical records. And it's
hard to fault them for their reluctance.
   We have for voter approval two candidates who are in good
health. It appears they're both surely good for at least four
years' work and possibly eight.
   Next issue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 6
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on the trade bill:
   After three years of struggle, Congress has passed the most
sweeping revision of U.S. trade law in decades.
   The bill started out dangerously protectionist, but President
Reagan and free-trade lawmakers got rid of the worst parts. ...
   Nevertheless, one should be wary of a 1,100-page piece of
congressional handiwork. Such monster bills traditionally are
studded with favors to special interests.
   The law had overwhelming support ... because it had something
for almost everybody. ...
   Perhaps we missed it, but we saw nothing there for consumers,
the group without a PAC (political action committee) and thus
without a loud voice in the corridors of power.
   The bill is notable for the damage it will not do: no major
tariff increases, new quotas or trade barriers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 8
   The Miami Herald on the next shuttle launch:
   The country needs a successful shuttle launch for two reasons.
   First, it would give a psychological boost to a nation
justifiably wary of the often-hollow promises of high technology.
   Second, there is a reason to believe that the advantages of
sophisticated manned flights into space will have long-term
benefits.
   But at the same time, NASA and its congressional-oversight
committees soon should re-examine the downgrading of refining
unmanned cargo-carrying flights.
   In order to promote the shuttle program, NASA has forsaken the
lead in a lucrative future market that requires, in relative terms,
a minimal investment.
   It would be wiser to split the priorities and the money on both
missions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 8
   The Baltimore Sun on Judge Hasting's impeachment:
   The House vote to impeach U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings
represents a first. It is the first time a federal official has
been impeached after a jury acquitted him of similar charges.
   Judge Hastings ... was accused in 1981 of conspiring with a
Washington attorney to solicit a bribe in a racketeering case. He
was acquitted ... but two judges ... pursued the case by filing a
misconduct charge against him.
   That led to a recommendation of impeachment by the Judicial
Conference of the United States and the congressional inquiry.
   The fact that Judge Hastings was pursued ... vigorously raises
suspicions about another first the judge represents. He was the
first black federal judge in Florida, ... and now becomes the first
black judge impeached.
   At a time when some blacks believe black elected officials are
targeted for special harassment, the proceedings against Judge
Hastings might raise troubling questions.
   But blacks in the House didn't seem to think racism was
involved. The House approved a 17-count resolution to impeach,
which is tantamount to an indictment that the Senate must now act
on, by a near-unanimous 413-3 vote.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
