<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: air force.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 5
   The Daily Journal, International Falls, Minn., on Dukakis health
rumors:
   Gossip is rarely pleasant, and it can be downright hazardous
when rumors find their way into the pages of a newspaper. ...
   An example is the Lyndon LaRouche-inspired rumor that Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis had sought psychiatric help
to overcome depression.
   Although LaRouche's minions produced no evidence to document
their claim, the rumor somehow made it to the front pages of
several of the country's newspapers.
   Dukakis has since denied that he has ever sought psychiatric
treatment, and the evidence bears him out.
   It's unsettling that the media responded to the rumor and
granted it substance by publishing the story. ...
   Seeking psychiatric help to deal with an emotional problem is no
less responsible than seeing a doctor to help cure a physical
ailment.
   In what we assume to be a more enlightened age, the LaRouche
rumor should have been quickly dismissed as a non-issue by the
media.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 5
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on Dukakis health rumors:
   Recipe for potent political poison.
   Start with ugly unsubstantiated rumors about Democratic
presidential nominee Michael S. Dukakis' mental health.
   Circulate them at a national convention in a leaflet distributed
by followers of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche. ...
   Next, wait for the national media to pick up on the rumors _
allegations which no news organization has been able to prove. ...
   The American people's right to know about a candidate's health,
mental and physical, far outweighs any politician's right to
privacy. ...
   Until (Dukakis) lets his medical records speak for themselves,
the public will not be satisfied and political opponents will be
able to raise questions and doubt because of this sordid episode in
dirty politics.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 7
   Los Angeles Times on Dukakis health rumors:
   It is too early to tell whether a physician's report giving Gov.
Michael Dukakis a clean bill of health will dispel the persistent
rumors that he sought psychiatric treatment. ...
   But, amid all the rumors and the innuendoes and the planted
stories, the only question worth raising is: Should a politician
who sought psychiatric care be considered unfit for high office?
   The answer, we submit, is no, that there should be no more
stigma attached to seeing a doctor about depression than about shin
splints or hernias or cancer. ...
   Where psychiatry is concerned, the issue should not be whether
someone once received treatment or not, but whether he or she is
currently fit to hold office.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 8
   Kansas City (Mo.) Star on Dukakis health rumors:
   Implicit in the badgering of Michael Dukakis about his health
records is a notion that if he had psychotherapy _ which he says he
did not _ it clouds his candidacy for the presidency of the United
States.
   The simple fact is that it's just the opposite.
   Seeking professional help for an emotional impasse is as
rational as getting a broken leg set by a physician.
   If the American people stop to think about it, wouldn't it be
preferable to depend on a leader who corrected a personal problem
rather than one who denied or ignored it, letting it impair
decision-making, efficiency and competency?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 7
   The Sheboygan (Wis.) Press on the honoraria law:
   Honoraria is rapidly becoming a dirty word in Washington.
   But it's an even dirtier word when it refers to direct conflicts
of interest, involving legislators in key committee positions.
   A new study by Common Cause, the self-styled citizens' lobby,
contends that members of Congress ... are wrong in taking money
from interest groups with issues coming before their committees. ...
   ``Members of Congress simply cannot fully meet their public
responsibilities when they are indebted to private interest groups
who are paying them large honoraria fees,'' contends Fred
Wertheimer, Common Cause president.
   He advocates banning honoraria because ``these fees are being
used to try to influence congressional decisions.''
   We strongly agree.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 8
   The Oregonian, Portland, Ore., on developing a food reserve:
   The drought-relief bill ought to do what it is intended to do,
which is to see the stricken U.S. agricultural industry through its
latest crisis. But it will not put one additional bushel of grain
in the nation's granaries.
   The next agricultural challenge for Congress, therefore, ought
to be development of a strategic food reserve. ...
   The shrinking harvests in this country and in Canada and China
leaves the entire world with a critical shortage of grain.
   The Worldwatch Institute in Washington, D.C., says that no more
than a 54-day supply is on hand. That compares with a 100-day
supply a year ago.
   The institute warns that food scarcity may dominate the next
decade, constituting a reversal of the problem to which the United
State has become accustomed.
   A similar reversal in congressional thinking needs to accompany
it.
</TEXT>
