<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOPConventionMoney     08-10 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Convention Money,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Orleans Reaches $5.5 Million Goal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials raising money for costs of the
Republican National Convention said today they've come up with the
city's $5.5 million share.
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy said he was pleased the city had gotten
the money through fund-raising and $800,000 from the state, instead
of using a hotel tax such as Atlanta used to help pay for the
Democratic National Convention.
   ``We are often criticized because we do not have our act
together ... This shows we are getting our act together,'' the
mayor said.
   New Orleans pledged to raise the money as part of its agreement
with the Republican Party to land the convention. According to a
final report, the city raised nearly $5.6 million.
   ``As of last night, we had $5,589,000 and contributions are
still coming in,'' said Ron Jones, chairman of the New Orleans
Special Events Fund.
   Contributors included all seven parishes in the New Orleans
metropolitan area and some outside of the region, Jones said.
Corporate contributions ranged from $100 to $250,000, said Jones.
   During an appearance last week before the state Joint
Legislative Budget Committee, which approved the use of state funds
for the convention, Jones said the convention would give Louisiana
an opportunity to attract new business and industry to the state.
   ``This is not just a message about fund-raising, it's a message
about economic development. The convention has given us the
opportunity to change the way America sees Louisiana,'' Jones said
today.
</TEXT>
