<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DeSillers 1stLd-Writethru a0516 08-10 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Hearing Over Missed Deadline, DeSillers' New Lawyer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with judge extending deadline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today extended until Thursday afternoon the
deadline for Maria DeSillers to give up a BMW car, jewelry and
other items allegedly bought with money donated for her son's liver
transplants.
   Ms. DeSillers, who missed an earlier deadline Tuesday, vowed to
defy the judge on at least one item, the deed to a cemetery plot
beside that of her son, Ronnie, a 7-year-old who died last year
while awaiting his fourth transplant.
   ``I'll be damned if I'll turn over the cemetery plot where I was
supposed to go next to my son,'' Mrs. DeSillers said. ``If they
want it, they're going to have to take me with it.''
   Probate Judge Francis Christie had earlier ordered Ms. DeSillers
to turn over the luxury items by Tuesday afternoon. But he gave her
an extension today because she replaced her attorney with Johnson.
   Her attorney, Frank Johnson, said he had not decided what steps
to take.
   The judge was to rule later on whether to charge Ms. DeSillers
with contempt for withholding financial records sought by the
curator.
   Ms. DeSillers is accused of misusing some of nearly $689,000
donated for her son's transplants, including $1,000 from President
Reagan. She claims the money is hers as Ronnie's heir.
   After Ronnie's death in 1987, his mother spent $11,000 on
jewelry, gave a total of $40,000 to her brother, ex-husband and
ex-boyfriend, and paid herself an $88,000 salary to head her
now-defunct Ronnie DeSillers National Foundation, according to the
curator of the boy's estate.
   Ms. DeSillers has refused to pay a $262,000 bill from Pittsburgh
Children's Hospital, which she faults for her son's death, a charge
doctors there vehemently deny.
   Christie has ruled that the $243,000 remaining in the boy's
estate will pay his outstanding hospital bills and may also be
given to other needy, ill children.
   Ms. DeSillers contends that she bought the disputed items with
her own money. But Robin Gievers, curator of Ronnie's estate, says
that after the boy's death, Ms. DeSillers had no job or income
source besides the donations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Fed-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0459 08-10 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fed-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0459,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts: Discount Rate Hike Likely To Mean Other Rates Move
Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `On Wall ...' to UPDATE with midday stock
prices. A version moved on the financial wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve's unexpected jolt to its key
bank lending rate _ to a 2{-year high _ likely will push other
interest rates higher, including those on home mortgages,
economists predict.
   The Fed announced Tuesday it was raising its discount rate to
6.5 percent from 6 percent, to help curb inflation and to account
for the recent rise of open-market interest rates.
   The discount rate is the interest the central bank charges on
loans to member banks. A change in the closely-watched rate is the
most dramatic move the Fed can make in signaling its credit
policies.
   Because the banks set their interest rates based on how much it
costs them to borrow money, many economists predict other rates
will edge higher due to Tuesday's action. That likely will mean
consumers will have to pay more for credit on houses, cars and
items charged on credit cards.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we had another (bank) prime rate
hike by Friday,'' said David Resler, chief economist for Nomura
Securities Inc.
   Financial markets reacted quickly to Tuesday's move, with the
dollar soaring and stock and bond prices falling sharply.
   The dollar jumped to 135.15 Japanese yen in New York from
133.725 yen late Monday, and rose sharply against other major
currencies.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell
28.27 points to 2,079.13 amid speculation of further rate
increases. It was down 33 points more by midday today.
   In the credit markets, the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond
fell by about $10 per $1,000 face amount, while its yield jumped to
9.19 percent from 9.10 percent late Monday.
   A month ago, major banks boosted their prime lending rates to
9.5 percent, the highest level in more than two years, from 9
percent in response to rising interest rates in the credit markets,
which had boosted the banks' cost of borrowing.
   The prime is a key rate used to calculate a range of fixed and
adjustable-rate corporate and consumer loans.
   Many economists had expected the Fed to tighten its reins on the
money supply this week, but few were expecting a discount rate hike.
   ``The (credit) markets have been screaming for a discount rate
increase for quite some time; the surprise was in the timing of
it,'' said Irwin Kellner, chief economist for Manufacturers Hanover
Trust Co.
   ``Not only is the Republican convention coming up, but we're in
the middle of a Treasury refunding,'' in which the government is
auctioning off $22 billion in new notes this week to pay off its
old debts, Kellner said.
   ``I don't think inflation is any worse today than it was last
year,'' said Kellner.
   Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for Nikko Securities
Co. International Inc., defended the discount-rate hike.
   ``It's the Fed's job to throw cold water on the economy when it
starts overheating and that's what it appears to be doing right
now,'' he said.
   Among recent signs of economic strength was the July
unemployment rate, which at 5.4 percent was near its 14-year lows.
   Tuesday's increase brings the discount rate to its highest level
since April 1986, when it was lowered to 6.5 percent from 7 percent.
   The hike was the second since Alan Greenspan replaced Paul A.
Volcker at the Fed's helm a year ago. On Sept. 4, the central bank
raised the rate for the first time in three years, to 6 percent
from 5.5 percent.
   While September's increase also was taken in response to
inflationary fears, some analysts later cited it as a contributing
factor to the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
