<HEAD>House Votes Additional Funds to Ethics Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday approved legislation to
give an additional $350,000 to the chamber's ethics committee for
investigations for the remainder of the year.
   The House voted 408-0 to nearly double the current fiscal 1988
appropriation of $400,000 for the House Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct, which is the panel's official name.
   The need for the additional funds was made necessary, primarily,
by the committee's investigation of House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, and its appointment of Chicago attorney Richard Phelan as
a special prosecutor to conduct the inquiry.
   The contract with Phelan's law firm for the year calls for
$300,000 from the committee's primary funding.
