   Nathaniel Glover Jr., deputy director of services for the
Jacksonville Sheriff's Office, said officials are investigaight Lifter
in Stadium
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 230-pound weight lifter and martial arts
expert foiled a bank robbery by chasing a man and taking him back
to the bank.
   ``He wasn't all that big,'' said Bob Hughes. ``It was just a
reaction. I just did it.''
   Hughes said he was driving into the parking lot of a U.S. Bank
branch Tuesday when he saw a woman run from the bank.
   ``She was yelling for someone to stop,'' Hughes said. ``I looked
around and saw this guy running down the street. I thought he had
taken her purse.''
   Hughes made a U-turn, drove down the street, stopped his car and
ran after the man.
   ``I really didn't know what to do with him, so I pinned his
hands behind his back and turned him into the wall,'' he said.
``When I saw he didn't have a purse, I realized he had robbed the
bank. Then I literally walked him back to the bank.''
   Police Detective David Simpson said Bradley R. Wilson, 37, was
accused of bank robbery and held at the Justice Center jail.
