<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0443 08-10 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Turns Reagan Rhetoric On Bush; Defends Harbor Cleanup
Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs with appearance today, editing to
conform, pickup graf 6 pvs bgng: Bush, in ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM W. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today defended his first-term
decision not to begin cleaning up Boston Harbor and shrugged off
polls showing that George Bush has cut into his lead in the
presidential race.
   The Massachusetts governor, at a groundbreaking ceremony at the
site of part of the harbor project, said those who blame him for
delaying the cleanup are preaching ``revisionist history.''
   In his first term in the mid-1970s, Dukakis decided against
proceeding with a clean-up plan. Shortly after he was voted out of
office in 1978, the state applied for a waiver from the Clean Water
Act.
   He stood by that decision today, saying there ``were very
respected people, experts in the field, who disagreed'' on what
needed to be done to rid the harbor of pollution.
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency eventually rejected
the waiver request and a subsequent appeal and the state is now
under federal court order to complete the cleanup by 1999. It is
expected to cost at least $6 billion.
   Dukakis, responding to reporters' questions at the ceremony,
said he was not surprised to see that his lead in the polls has
been cut by the Republican vice president.
   ``This is going to be a very tough, competitive 90 days,''
Dukakis said of his race with Bush heading into the November
election.
   Dukakis was spending most of today at the Statehouse before
heading back out to campaign Thursday and Friday.
   On Tuesday, Dukakis turned back Bush's latest salvo with a line
nearly copied from the president's political phrasebook.
   ``There he goes again,'' Dukakis responded to Bush's accusation
that he is on the `liberal fringe.'' President Reagan used a
similar line in 1980 as he debated Jimmy Carter.
   The vice president renewed his attack while Dukakis joined
fellow governors at a national gathering in Cincinnati, and
attended a second private session with Democratic governors who
emerged praising his candidacy and promising to support it.
   The governors ``are going to be an essential part of this
campaign, they are going to be an essential part of the next
administration,'' said Dukakis, governor of Massachusetts.
   Bush, in Pennsylvania, charged Dukakis was on the ``very, very
far liberal fringe'' and that his lead was evaporating.
   With less than a week to go before the Republicans hold their
convention in New Orleans, where Dukakis can expect to come under
intense attack, Dukakis aides maintained they were unconcerned by
the new Gallup poll showing a 10 point decline in Dukakis'
advantage over the vice president.
   The survey showed his 17-point lead had declined to a
seven-point margin of 49 percent to 42 percent.
   Campaign spokesman Mark Gearan called the decline
``understandable'' and attributed it to a public shift in focus to
the Republicans in advance of the Republican National Convention
which begins Monday in New Orleans.
   ``After the Republican convention it could be very, very
close,'' Gearan said. ``It could be dead even, if not showing
George Bush taking the advantage.''
   He said the 1984 Democratic nominee, Walter Mondale, rose
dramatically in the polls during his convention week that year _ a
rise that proved only momentary.
   At the National Governors' Association, Dukakis went to the site
of a housing development project to call attention to a resolution
passed on a unanimous, bipartisan vote calling for a new national
housing policy.
   The proposal calls for a $2.8 billion increase in government
spending on housing to help states and cities expand the supply of
affordable housing through grants and tax measures. It would
provide rent subsidies and address what Dukakis called ``the
problem of home ownership for young families.''
   ``What's missing these days is any sense in the White House that
there is a national commitment to affordable housing to the people
of this country,'' Dukakis said. ``I don't just mean families of
low and moderate income. I mean young families, who ought to have
an opportunity to own their own home, at a price they can afford.''
</TEXT>
