<DOCNO> AP880810-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0577 08-10 1026</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0577,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Things Are Looking Up As Dukakis Lead Shrinks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Dukakis reaction; pick up 5th graf pvs
bgng ``Bush still...; SUBS graf 11-14 with 5 grafs new with Dukakis
quotes at sewage plant; Picks up 15th graf pvs bgng ``Tuesday
brought..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said today the fall campaign against
George Bush is going to be ``a very tough, competitive 90 days,''
as new poll numbers and big dollar figures gave Republicans a boost
in advance of next week's convention.
   A Gallup Poll released Tuesday put Dukakis' margin at seven
points over Bush, less than half of the 17-point edge the
Massachusetts governor enjoyed coming out of the Democratic
National Convention last month in Atlanta.
   ``I like it, I like it,'' Bush said Tuesday night in
Philadelphia.
   Althought Bush was quick to say he doesn't trust the polls, he
did agree that ``Things are moving. We're beginning to get them in
focus.''
   Dukakis said in Boston today that he was not surprised by the
swinging numbers in the polls.
   ``This is going to be a very tough, competitive 90 days''
through the Nov. 8 election, the Democratic presidential nominee
said.
   Bush still has the Republican National Convention to come,
beginning Monday in New Orleans, with its four nights of prime time
partisanship designed to boost his standing with the voters. He was
spending today in Washington and working on his acceptance speech.
   The Republican National Committee got good news from its finance
officials today, hearing that the party has $13.5 million cash on
hand toward a goal of ``more than $70 million toward election of
Republican candidates at all levels'' this year.
   With Dukakis and Bush staying close to home today, former
Democratic hopeful Jesse Jackson lashed out at both men for their
recent campaign styles.
   ``This campaign ought to focus on direction and not on dirt,''
Jackson told reporters after having breakfast in Washington with
Democratic House members. ``This campaign boils down to Bush
attacking Dukakis with one-liners every day, and Dukakis is
becoming preoccupied with the Bush-Noriega connection, the
Bush-Iran-Contra connection, of exchanging drugs for arms.
   ``If it gets warped into sleaze, then there will be no hope left
for the people,'' Jackson added.
   Dukakis moved to blunt a stinging Republican attack on his
support for a clean environment.
   The Massachusetts governor took part in the ground-breaking for
a new sewage treatment plant on Boston Harbor, the first step in a
$6 billion effort to clean up what the Environmental Protection
Agency has called the filthiest harbor in the nation.
   In his first term as governor, Dukakis opposed committing
massive resources to the cleanup. Today, he defended that decision,
saying there ``were very respected people, experts in the field,
who disagreed'' on what needed to be done to rid the harbor of
pollution.
   He fired back at those who blame him for the pollution problems,
saying they are guilty of ``revisionist history.''
   Bush had been getting some political mileage out of the harbor
pollution.
   ``He goes down to New Jersey and talks about the pollution off
of New Jersey and look, over his shoulder is Boston Harbor, one of
the most seriously polluted bodies of water in this country,'' Bush
said Sunday.
   Tuesday brought good news for Bush in a new poll.
   The Gallup survey put Dukakis's support at 49 percent and Bush's
at 42 percent in telephone interviews with 1,004 registered voters
Aug. 5-7.
   Only two weeks ago, Dukakis was sporting a 17-point margin over
Bush, a 54-37 result in a Gallup Poll. Each survey had a 3
percentage point margin of error.
   That would mean that the ``bump'' Dukakis gained from the
Democratic convention had essentially evaporated.
   Larry Bathgate of New Jersey, GOP national finance chairman,
said the committee had raised $34.9 million in the first seven
months of this year. the second largest amount the RNC had ever
raised in such a time period. In addition, he said the convention
gala _ a luncheon scheduled next Thursday _ is expected to raise
between $5 million and $6 million.
   The Democrats also aren't doing badly in the money department,
House Speaker Jim Wright said in Washington, noting the party
raised about $12 million at this point, compared to a $9 million
debt in 1984.
   ``We are somewhat stunned. We just don't know how to take that
prosperity. We have a self-identify problem. We never had money in
the bank. We've always been in debt,'' Wright said after a private
meeting with Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich.
   Tuesday also brought another round of charges and countercharges
between the major-party presidential candidates on themes that may
well dominate the fall campaign.
   Each sought to raise questions about just where his opponent
stands on the issues.
   ``He's trying to run away from a record in Massachusetts on the
very, very far liberal fringe,'' Bush said of Dukakis. ``He thinks
he can pre-empt the middle.''
   ``There he goes again,'' replied Dukakis, recalling the line
Ronald Reagan used to cut down Jimmy Carter in a 1980 presidential
debate.
   Bush had labeled Dukakis the ``stealth candidate'' on Monday,
but the Democratic nominee came straight back at the incumbent vice
president.
   ``I don't think Bush's positions are clear on much of
anything,'' Dukakis said before the National Governors' Association
meeting in Cincinnati.
   In fact, Dukakis took the unusual position of claiming that
President Reagan is closer to his position on a range of important
issues than he is to Bush.
   ``It's an administration that's growing,'' Dukakis said.
``Frankly, they're coming a lot closer to where I am. ... The
interesting thing is the president and I are closer together on
U.S.-Soviet relations than he is with Bush.''
   The Republican nominee-to-be said he is still not ready to talk
about his choice of a running mate, the remaining piece of the
puzzle to set up the fall election campaign.
   ``I'm not close in the sense of like tomorrow making a final
decision,'' the vice president said, adding he is holding to his
plan to announce this choice on the convention's final day.
</TEXT>
