<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Everest     08-10 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Everest,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Team Hopes To Hoist Olympics Flag On Everest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of veteran South Korean climbers
set out Wednesday with hopes of conquering Mount Everest, the
world's highest peak, to celebrate the Seoul Olympics.
   The climbers will try to scale the 29,028-foot peak the hard way
_ via the steep South Pillar route _ ``because none of our
countrymen has ever done it in the past,'' said team leader Choi
Chang-min of Seoul.
   Although the South Pillar route is the most direct path to the
top of Everest, only two men _ one from Poland and another from
Czechoslovakia _ have succeeded in climbing it.
   From Lukla, the 20-man team hopes to reach Khumbu Glacier, their
planned base camp, by Aug. 26. The Olympics are to begin in Seoul,
South Korea, on Sept. 17.
   ``Once we are acclimatized, we will embark on the mountain,''
said Choi, 45.
   One part of the group is to climb Everest, while another plans
to climb 27,932-foot Mount Lhotse, the world's fourth-highest
mountain and one of Everest's sister peaks.
   If the Korean team reaches both peaks, it would become only the
second expedition to do so, following a Swiss team in 1956.
   ``But they (the Swiss) did not climb the two peaks on the same
day. We will try on the same day,'' said Nam Sun-wu, the team's
climbing leader.
   Ko Sang-don, the first Korean to scale Everest, reached the peak
in 1977. Last year, Heo Young-ho became the second Korean to
conquer the world's highest mountain.
   However, Ko and Heo followed the traditional Southeast Ridge
route that was pioneered by Sir Edmund Hillary and Sherpa Tenzing
Norgay in the first climb to Everest's peak in 1953.
   Asked why their team wished to climb Everest, Choi said:
   ``Because it is the highest ... So many people all over the
world have longed to go there. It is a dream of every alpinist to
be on Everest.''
</TEXT>
