<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CubanPrisons     08-10 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Prisons,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Ambassador Accuses Castro Of Cover-Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban jails where political prisoners have
been kept naked in windowless rooms are being altered to make them
appear more humane to outside investigators, a U.S. human rights
official said Wednesday.
   Ambassador Armando Valladares, U.S. representative to the U.N.
Human Rights Commission, made the accusation and released
photographs of prisoners and their cells he said were smuggled out
of one prison by Cuban dissidents.
   Valladares, who himself was a prisoner of Cuban leader Fidel
Castro for 22 years before he was released in 1982 and allowed to
emigrate to the United States, said some of the worst jail cells
have been dismantled in a prison near Havana but others remain in
more than 200 jails throughout the country.
   ``Real changes are not possible, because that would mean the end
of the dictatorship,'' said Valladares, speaking in Spanish through
a translator. He was appointed to the Geneva-based human rights
commission by President Reagan earlier this year. Castro expressed
outrage at the appointment, labeling Valladares a terrorist.
   The photos showed a wall of windowless metal doors and the
interior of dank cells with hole-in-the-floor toilets. Valladares
said the cells, including one dubbed ``the triangle of death,''
were all torn down shortly after the pictures were taken.
   He pointed out welding equipment used in the destruction in one
of the photos and displayed two tiny microphones he said were also
smuggled out by prisoners.
   Inmates from a group known as the Ricardo Bofill's Cuban
Committee for Human Rights took the pictures at the Combinado del
Este prison on the outskirts of Havana using a Soviet-made camera
using Chinese film, Valladares said.
   A United Nations delegation headed by Alioune Sene of Senegal is
to visit Cuba in September. Other members of the delegation will be
representatives from Ireland, Nigeria, Hungary, Colombia and the
Philippines.
   Valladares said the commission expects to interview hundreds of
Cubans during an 11-day trip. He said the Cuban government was
supposed to publish three telephone numbers that people can call
who want to present information to the commission.
   The commission also has a list of 5,000 names of people to make
inquiries about, Valladares said. ``Many Cubans are becoming less
and less afraid and will be willing to talk to the commission,'' he
said.
   He said delegation members have been assured they will have
freedom to move around the country and interview anyone.
   Valladares acknowledged it may be difficult to prove that
prisoners are tortured, because government's don't generally
acknowledge such activities. He said the photos of prison cells and
inmates have been sent to the delegation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
