<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NuclearEnergy     08-10 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Energy,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teller Says Fission Still Mainstay of Nuclear Energy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should move ahead with
development of advanced uranium-fueled reactors because producing
electrical power from hydrogen fusion is at least several decades
away, physicist Edward Teller said Wednesday.
   Teller, who played a key role in development of the hydrogen
bomb, told a scientific conference that ``fusion will have no
impact on electric generation during the next 40 years.''
   He said that ``at least for the next 50 years _ and much longer,
in my opinion _ the mainstay of nuclear energy ... I firmly believe
will be fission.''
   Fission, which provides the basis for all of today's nuclear
power reactors, involves the splitting of uranium atoms in a
controlled chain reaction. Fusion derives energy from the fusing
together of hydrogen nuclei under very high temperature and
pressure.
   Teller said accelerated development of nuclear power will be
prompted partly by increasing concern over the ``greenhouse
effect'' _ global warming caused by atmospheric buildup of carbon
dioxide and other gases from the burning of fossil fuels.
   Because of this and other factors, he said, the United States
``must greatly increase the funding for power reactor development.''
   Advanced fission reactor concepts under study in the United
States include high-temperature, gas-cooled reactors along with
units that would utilize liquid sodium metal as the reactor coolant.
   Also appearing at the conference was Dixy Lee Ray, former
governor of Washington and former chairman of the Atomic Energy
Commission.
   Asked how she would assess the prospects for achieving
controlled nuclear fusion, Ray said in an interview: ``I think it
is a program that we must support and must continue. I believe
there's a great deal of basic research that still needs to be
done.''
   ``It's awfully hard to make predictions, but based on experience
in other areas I'd say it's another 10 to 20 years before we can
know for sure whether it will work,'' she said. ``And once we know
it works, then it's another time to know whether it will be
economical, which is still an open question.''
</TEXT>
