<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Hijack     08-10 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Hijack,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijackers of Pan Am Jumbo Jet Appeal Death Sentences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Palestinians sentenced to hang
for the 1986 hijacking of a Pan Am jumbo jet that left 21 people
dead appealed their death sentences Wednesday in a petition to
Superior Court.
   The five were convicted and sentenced July 6 by Judge Mohammad
Zafar Barbar in a makeshift courtroom in a prison west of Islamabad.
   The judge blamed lax airport security in part for the hijacking,
in which four of the Palestinians entered the plane dressed as
security guards.
   An Indian-American was among the 21 people who died during the
hijacking ordeal, and 200 people were injured.
   The Boeing 747 on a stopover between Bombay, India, and New
York, was seized on the ground Sept. 5, 1986, in Pakistan's
southern port of Karachi with 400 people aboard, including 44
Americans.
   It sat on the tarmac for 17 hours before the Palestinians,
fearing an attack when an onboard generator ran out, sprayed the
cabin with bullets and hurled hand grenades, and Pakistani troops
stormed the plane.
   The defendants said they were innocent and blamed the killings
on Pakistani commandos.
   The hijackers claimed they planned to free their hostages and
blow the plane up over Israel in a suicide operation that would
highlight ``Israeli excesses'' against Palestinians in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In their appeal, the Palestinians challenged Judge Barbar's
legal interpretation of hijacking laws. They also asked the
Superior Court to have their fetters removed and to guarantee them
proper medical care in prison.
   The court will take up the petition on Aug. 15. The death
sentences will not be carried until all appeals have been
exhausted, which could take months.
   When the guilty verdict was returned, Mohammad Hafiz Turk, 32,
the only one of the five who was not on the hijacked plane, said:
``We don't care about the sentence.'' He was sentenced to hang for
his part in planning the hijacking. ``We care only about the
millions of Arabs and Islamic countries.''
   The other four _ Mohammad Ahmed Munawar, Khalil Hussain Rahayyal
and Saeed Abdul Rahim of Lebanon, and Abdul Latif Sairfani of Syria
_ were sentenced to hang for their role in the hijacking.
   They also were sentenced to 10 consecutive life sentences or 250
years in prison for the deaths of 10 of the 21 passengers.
   Three of the four men received an additional life sentence in an
11th death, that of the Indian-American.
   The four men, ranging in age from 18-24, also were fined nearly
$2,800 in each murder conviction. Half the money will be given to
relatives of victims.
   During sentencing, Barbar said ``security (at the airport)
seemed to be extremely lax.'' The judge questioned how the four men
dressed as security guards could board the Pan Am flight weighed
down with weapons and ammunition.
   The hijackers, he said, ``were able to collect huge caches of
ammunition unnoticed and unhindered.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
