<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 5thLd-Writethru a0608 08-10 0916</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0608,0941</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Says Protesters Behead Three Police </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New grafs 12-13 to update with U.S. closing embassy in Burma.
Picks up 13th graf pvs ``Burmese embassies...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators in Burma beheaded three
policemen today and troops in the capital opened fire on
anti-government protesters, killing more than 30 people, Radio
Rangoon said.
   The Burmese government-owned radio also said a mob attacked a
police station in Moulmein in southern Burma, killing one officer.
   Burma has reported 78 deaths, about 160 people wounded and more
than 1,500 arrests in three days of protests against the
authoritarian government of President Sein Lwin.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon, the capital, believe casualties
are substantially higher.
   Radio Rangoon, monitored in Bangkok, said security forces fired
15 times to disperse crowds in Rangoon. It said 33 people were
killed, 59 were wounded and 113 were arrested for ``violence and
looting.''
   The radio said three policemen were beheaded and another member
of the security forces and a civilian were killed in outlying areas
of the capital. It was not clear if the five were included in the
report of 33 deaths in Rangoon.
   It said another officer was taken away by a mob outside the
capital.
   In Moulmein, on the southern coast, demonstrators seized guns
from police firing to disperse them, marched to the police station
and fatally shot one policeman, the radio said.
   It said rioters set fire to buses, police stations and
government family quarters, destroyed railway lines and burned
other buildings in and around Rangoon.
   Japan's Kyodo News Agency said more than 100 people were killed
and nearly 1,000 wounded today when troops fired machine guns and
automatic weapons at the protesters in Rangoon.
   Diplomats in Rangoon and Bangkok, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said up to 200 may have been killed in three days of
protests but that access to reliable information has been difficult.
   In Washington today, State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said the United States has temporarily closed its embassy in
Burma. All official American personnel and their dependents _ a
total of 154 people _ are safe at their homes, she said.
   Mrs. Oakley was unable to say when the embassy was closed but
she said that there is no indication Americans or other foreigners
have been or might become targets of violence. She said it appeared
the anti-government demonstrations have led to a ``substantial''
loss of life.
   Burmese embassies around the world stopped issuing tourist visas
this week and have been expelling some visitors before the
expiration of their seven-day visas.
   ``They're flushing everyone from the country,'' said one British
tourist returning to Bangkok. Other travelers said they were
interrogated and jailed and several appeared near shock.
   A curfew was imposed in the capital Tuesday and gatherings of
more than five people were banned.
   ``The government hasn't gotten control of the situation yet,''
said a Bangkok-based diplomat monitoring developments in Burma.
   Most embassies in the city were staffed by only essential
personnel, with many Burmese employees staying home, the diplomats
said. One said the capital was ``half-operating,'' with a number of
stores closed and only some public transport running.
   The demonstrations _ the largest public protests since a
military coup in 1962 _ began last month shortly after Sein Lwin
became both president of the country and chairman of its sole
political party.
   Sein Lwin has been accused by students and other demonstrators
of ruthless suppression of dissent. He replaced Ne Win, who
resigned after ruling Burma for 26 years and imposing isolationist
economic policies.
   An Italian journalist of Florence's La Nazione newspaper said he
saw a large but peaceful protest Monday turn violent around the
Sule Pagoda in downtown Rangoon.
   The reporter, who asked that his name not be used, said at least
30,000 demonstrators converged on the pagoda, with students and
Buddhist monks climbing on columns and other high places to give
speeches and chant slogans denouncing Sein Lwin and demanding a
return to democracy.
   ``When the monks got up to speak there was an explosion of
clapping, an intense, emotional ovation,'' he said.
   Troops moved in and warned they would shoot if the crowd did not
leave, he said. Thousands scattered but many more remained in
place, and when troops approached, youngsters would lie
spread-eagled on the ground to stop their advance, the reporter
said.
   Before midnight, he said, more troops arrived, some in armored
personnel carriers, and sealed off the area, setting up barricades
along all streets leading to the pagoda.
   He said the troops then opened fire, first in the air and then
apparently into the crowd. The journalist said he saw people topple
over and flags they were holding sink to the ground. He said he
watched from an upstairs room of a building in which he was given
shelter.
   ``I didn't see a single weapon, not even a stick in the hands of
the demonstrators,'' he said. ``Some had flags and the Buddhist
monks carried their umbrellas.''
   A U.S. official in Washington said eyewitnesses reported seeing
demonstrators carrying bodies of dead colleagues over their heads
as they marched through the streets of Rangoon.
   Consular officials around the world have in recent weeks tried
to screen journalists attempting to enter the country under tourist
visas.
   The Associated Press has been unable to obtain entry. Its
correspondent in Rangoon, Sein Win, was arrested and jailed by
authorities late last month. No charges were filed.
</TEXT>
