<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Letter     08-10 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Letter,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Whose Letter Created Storm Reappears in Print</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Leningrad teacher whose March letter in an
official newspaper touched off an intense debate about Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms reappeared in print Wednesday to answer her
critics.
   A letter from Nina Andreeva to actor Mikhail Ulyanov, answering
his speech to the Communist Party conference at the end of June,
appeared in the weekly Moscow News.
   Ms. Andreeva's March 13 letter to the newspaper Sovietskaya
Rossiya was regarded by Gorbachev supporters as a rallying point
for conservatives opposed to the Soviet leader's reforms.
   But her latest letter was less a manifesto of the Soviet right
than a personal rebuke to the actor.
   Rumors circulating in Moscow claimed that Kremlin No. 2 leader
Yegor K. Ligachev, thought to be more conservative than Gorbachev,
was behind the publication and was seeking to undermine Gorbachev's
reforms.
   Ulyanov said in his passionate speech to the conference, which
was called to review progress on the reforms and chart a future
path, that supporters of Gorbachev did not have to answer Ms.
Andreeva directly but ``those who stand behind her.''
   He said Soviets remain afraid to act because of their society's
history of repression.
   Ms. Andreeva chided the actor on his passionate language and
offered to meet him in Leningrad ``to debate those things that so
upset you.''
   Moscow News, which has used Gorbachev's policy of greater
freedom on selected topics to publish much material that previously
would not have been printed, said Ulyanov did not intend to take
Ms. Andreeva up on the offer.
</TEXT>
