<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Jodie Foster, who got her first acting job
at age 3, college at Yale University was supposed to be her time to
live a normal life.
   Then, in March 1981, John Hinckley shot President Reagan, saying
he wanted to impress Foster, the teen-age prostitute of ``Taxi
Driver,'' whom he'd never met.
   ``It was a surreal experience,'' Foster recalls in the September
issue of Vanity Fair.
   ``In general, I felt it was my God-given responsibility to
endure this martyrdom, and it's a good thing I went through it,
because somebody else couldn't take it. ... I got applause for
being professional and not complaining and being straightforward
and strong _ I didn't get any attention for crying.''
   The 25-year-old actress, who plays a gang-rape victim in the
upcoming film, ``The Accused,'' with Kelly McGillis, says she has
been thinking about moving out from in front of the camera to
direct ``a real film about real people. A very American film about
relationships and disappointments.''
   ``I don't believe that winning makes you more mature,'' she
says. ``I'm not sure I like it, but disappointments shape you.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has ruled there is ``clear
and convincing proof'' that comedian Jackie Mason fathered the
daughter of actress and playwright Ginger Reiter.
   The Third District Court of Appeal on Tuesday upheld a lower
court decision issued earlier this year by Dade Circuit Judge John
Gale.
   The appeals panel noted that a blood test showed a 99.94 percent
probability that Mason, 57, was the father of the toddler, Sheba.
It also pointed to a ``striking resemblance between the father and
the 2{-year-old child.''
   The judges also found proof that ``the parties had an ongoing
sexual relationship during the period of conception.''
   Mason's attorney Gerald Mager said he would have to review the
decision before deciding whether to appeal.
   While the appeal was pending, Mason began paying Ms. Reiter
$1,500 a month in temporary child support, plus a payment of $2,550
to move Ms. Reiter and her daughter to another apartment.
   If the appeals court ruling stands, the case will be sent back
to Gale to determine permanent child support.
   Mason is featured in his own Broadway show and in the movie
Caddyshack II.
   Ms. Reiter, 37, of North Miami Beach, has mounted her own show,
``Oh Jackie, Oh!'' about their relationship. The show has toured
community centers in south Florida.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A CBS television movie starring Robert Urich
as a former college football star will be shot on the University of
Minnesota campus starting next month, the school says.
   ``The Comeback'' is about an old Gopher star who returns to
Minneapolis to start a new life in his old town. The movie is
scheduled to be shown in November.
   Some real-life ex-Minnesota football players may appear, but
National Collegiate Athletic Association rules forbid current
players from taking part.
   ``Everybody in the athletic department wants a part in the
movie,'' said Dana Noel, an assistant to the sports information
director. Noel is helping CBS line up some of the extras for the
movie.
   Real-life former players will portray present players in a scene
where the nostalgic ex-star watches his old team practice.
   Tentative plans call for CBS to make a contribution to the
athletic department instead of paying the extras, Noel said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter and two
of his sons made it to the top of Mount Kilimanjaro, Africa's
highest mountain, but Rosalynn Carter and three of the Carters'
grandchildren dropped out of the climb.
   The 64-year-old Carter, leading a 17-member party through snow
flurries and near-zero visibility, reached the volcanic mountain's
second highest peak, Gilman's Point, early Monday after a three-day
climb.
   Reaching Gilman's Point at 18,640 feet traditionally is
considered a successful climb, although the 19,340-foot Uhuru Peak
farther around the summit's crater is the mountain's highest point.
   There were eight dropouts, including Mrs. Carter and
grandchildren Jason, 13, James Early, 12, and Sarah, 10.
   Tanzania's president, Ali Hassan Mwinyi, will present
certificates to Carter and his sons, Jack, 41, and Jim ``Chip'',
38, at a ceremony marking the climb Sunday in Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania's capital, according to the government-owned Daily News.
   The group left Wednesday for four days of viewing wildlife in
Tangire, Manyara, Serengeti and the Ngorongoro Crater national
parks. After stopping back in Dar Es Salaam, they will go on to
Kenya.
</TEXT>
