<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everybody complains that their taxes are too
high, but hundreds of York County residents really had something to
gripe about.
   More than 400 people received personal property tax bills this
week in excess of $1 million, including one woman hit with a $21
million tab, officials said.
   The error affected about 5 percent of 8,000 property owners and
kept assessment office phones ringing for two days.
   ``Most of the problems have been addressed, and we've been
sending out the correction notices,'' said chief assessor Steve
Anderson. ``They can leave their bombs at home.''
   The annual tax bills cover personal property, such as stocks and
other investments.
   Anderson blamed the mix-up on new employees in the personal
property tax division entering data incorrectly on a new computer
system.
   ``A person who had one share _ or $500 _ was in some cases
listed as having 500 shares,'' he said. ``So that person would be
taxed on $250,000 when he really should have been taxed on $500.
   County Commissioner Ron Fitzkee called the clerical error ``a
shame,'' but said the bills were so outrageous that most people
didn't take them seriously.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roland Winbeckler's art looks good enough to
eat. But maybe that's because he puts on his palette the things
that please most palates.
   His decorations adorn Styrofoam and cardboard forms; his palette
holds buttercream frosting.
   Winbeckler, 42, of Kent, Wash., is one of more than 1,000 cake
decorators and vendors who will be in Tulsa for the International
Cake Exploration Society's 13th annual convention, Thursday through
Sunday.
   Winbeckler's creation is a foot-tall bust of Oklahoma humorist
Will Rogers, with carefully sculpted features that include
straggling gray hair on the forehead and the twist of his familiar
grin.
   It's all done with the frosting, said Winbeckler, who has
created life-size and edible likenesses of Marilyn Monroe taming a
billowing dress, Wayne Gretzky wielding a hockey stick, and
Princess Diana standing ready in her wedding dress for her marriage
to Prince Charles.
   Winbeckler's Rogers is part of a 9-foot-high Styrofoam and
frosting representation of Oklahoma history made by the Oklahomans
sponsoring the convention. It is topped by an oil derrick and has a
motorized ring of covered wagons depicting the Land Run of 1889,
when unassigned areas of land in the state were opened to white
settlement.
   It's not uncommon for cake decorators showing off their talents
to use Styrofoam forms, Winbeckler explained, particularly when the
display has to last more than a day or two.
   For his edible creations, Winbeckler prefers a dense pound cake
as his medium. ``It usually is more solid than white cake and will
hold up better,'' he said.
</TEXT>
