<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--CanalTreaty     08-10 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Canal Treaty,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Introduced Urging Abrogation of Panama Canal Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative lawmakers led by Rep. Philip
Crane, R-Ill., and Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, introduced a bill
Wednesday urging abrogation of the 1979 treaty transferring
ownership of the Panama Canal to the Panamanian government.
   Crane said the treaty is invalid because it was not ratified
properly.
   He said the Constitution prohibits transfer of U.S. property
unless both houses of Congress approve, but that the House never
voted on the canal treaty.
   Symms said the treaty also is invalid because the Senate never
ratified changes imposed by the Panamanian government in 1979 and
because it was not signed by the president of Panama.
   The two lawmakers said their resolution urges the president or
Congress ``to simply announce the abrogation of the treaty.''
   Under the treaty, the United States would abandon all rights to
the Canal Zone and it would become a part of Panama on Dec. 31,
1999.
</TEXT>
