<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreppieMurder     08-10 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preppie Murder,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer Says He Wants Judgment Against Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man convicted of strangling a young woman in
the ``preppie murder'' case said he will not fight a $25 million
judgment to be entered against him on behalf of the parents of the
slain teen-ager.
   ``My only wish is for the nightmare to end,'' Robert Chambers
said in a handwritten note dated Tuesday. He asked the court to
enter the judgment against him because ``I do not wish the Levins
to endure any more pain.''
   Steven and Ellen Levin, parents of Jennifer Levin, 18, filed the
wrongful death lawsuit against Chambers on July 22. On Monday they
sued Jack Dorrian, owner of the bar where Miss Levin and Chambers
drank hours before he strangled her in Central Park on Aug. 26,
1986.
   Chambers' request for the default judgment was filed in the
trial-level state Supreme Court on his behalf by his attorney,
Brian O'Dwyer, who said he had advised his client against the move.
   O'Dwyer said he explained to Chambers that all his property
could be attached and sold to satisfy the judgment, and that any
future salary, property, gift or inheritance he receives also could
be attached.
   But O'Dwyer said Chambers, 21, ``hoped this action might be seen
to others as a symbol of the genuine sorrow he felt about the death
of Jennifer Levin, and he knew it would live with him every day and
every hour of his life.''
   The Levins could not be reached for comment. Arnold Domenitz,
Miss Levin's maternal grandfather, refused to comment on Chambers'
action.
   Harry Lipsig, the Levins' attorney, called the action ``a ploy,
an attempt to save himself from the grilling that would necessarily
take place in connection with the suit and the ultimate proof of
all his misconduct.''
   Lipsig called Chambers' default a victory for the Levins, but a
``pathetic'' one because, ``Nothing can bring back the flower he
crushed.''
   Chambers wrote the note at Great Meadows Correctional Facility,
a maximum-security prison in Comstock, where he is serving a
five-to-15-year sentence after pleading guilty to first-degree
manslaughter in Miss Levin's death.
   Despite his Upper East Side residence and prep school education,
Chambers is not wealthy. His mother made about $70,000 last year as
a 12-hour-a-day private duty nurse, and his father is an accounts
receivable employee who earned less than $40,000.
   O'Dwyer mentioned in the court papers that Chambers has applied
to take college courses in the fall at prison. Chambers hopes to
become a teacher when he gets out, O'Dwyer said.
</TEXT>
