<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionShowbiz     08-10 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Showbiz,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Parley: `Fun, Excitement, Color' Planned For Superdome</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrats had Garrison Keillor, Lynda
Carter and Dionne Warwick, and the Republicans will fight back next
week with Charlton Heston, Sandy Patti and the Oak Ridge Boys.
   Political conventions may be serious business, but so is
prime-time television _ a fact not lost on the organizers of the
upcoming GOP parley in the New Orleans Superdome.
   ``It's no secret that a great deal of what you do is designed
for television. We are trying to reach the public here,'' says Mark
Goode, a Washington consultant and former television producer who
is producing the convention.
   A primary task of GOP planners has been to turn the 27-story
high, 87,000-seat sports arena into a smaller, warmer setting,
unmarred by banks of empty seats or cubic yards of empty air.
   Last month at the Democratic National Convention, conditions
were so crowded that legitimate delegates were shut out and the
Atlanta fire marshal was on alert all week.
   The Republicans, by contrast, have hung an enormous blue curtain
across the middle of the Superdome, cutting it in half. And they've
hung an equally imposing lighting grid 40 feet above the floor,
which ``reduces the normally cavernous feel in here,'' Goode said.
   ``It is a massive place. But it will certainly appear far more
intimate than under normal circumstances,'' Goode said. ``Had we
not felt it was suitable for television, we never would have chosen
it. It's going to work just fine for television and sensationally
for the people who will be right here. It will be very exciting _
the largest crowd ever for a political convention.''
   The Democrats hired a Hollywood production company to
orchestrate their convention, a much more theatrical spectacle than
the party usually puts on.
   Goode, who lived in Los Angeles for 24 years, is no stranger to
Hollywood production values. Nevertheless, the Republicans, known
in the past for their smooth stagecraft, are sniffing in scorn at
the Democrats' pandering to the entertainment ethic.
   ``This is not a variety show,'' said GOP convention spokeswoman
Mary Mead. ``The emphasis is on substance, not glitz.''
   ``We'll have a little fun, some excitement and some color,''
Goode said. ``But basically we are here to do business.''
   The convention will kick off Monday with a tribute to President
Reagan, including a videotape to be shown on eight huge screens
throughout the New Orleans Superdome. Before Reagan's appearance,
``we have a little surprise cooked up,'' Goode said. He would not
elaborate.
   Celebrities will be sprinkled throughout prime time, with
musician Lionel Hampton and actor Charlton Heston scheduled to lead
the Pledge of Allegiance and the national anthem to be sung on
various evenings by gospel singer Sandy Patti, soap star Shelley
Burch, the Oak Ridge Boys and a 10-year-old girl from Seattle.
   The rest of prime time will be dominated by Republican
officeholders, including a large number of women. Rep. Olympia
Snowe of Maine will help preside over the convention while Rep. Pat
Saiki of Hawaii will call the roll of the states when George Bush
is nominated.
   Other prime time speeches are tentatively scheduled for former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, former U.N. Ambassador
Jeane Kirkpatrick, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas and Nebraska Gov.
Kay Orr, chairman of the platform committee.
   Bush has the nomination sewn up, but he's hoping to build
suspense _ and ratings _ by keeping his vice presidential choice a
secret until Thursday, the final day of the convention.
   Delegates will be sitting in armchairs upholstered in red, part
of a traditional red-white-blue color scheme and unlike the salmon
and azure favored by the Democrats. Forty skyboxes will ring the
arena at the height of its third floor, and four anchor booths will
be in place for ABC, CBS, NBC and CNN.
   Some 13,500 journalists and technicians are expected to attend
the Republican convention, along with 50 to 60 satellite trucks
sent by TV stations and groups seeking localized coverage.
   The RNC is offering gavel-to-gavel coverage of the convention
via the RNC Network to any station that can pick up a satellite
feed. The proceedings will be accompanied by closed captioning and
a simultaneous Spanish translation.
</TEXT>
