<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Customs-Cocaine     08-10 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Customs-Cocaine,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Agents Seizing More Drugs Every Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs Service agents in 10 months have
seized 10 tons more cocaine than they did in all of the last fiscal
year, but officials said Wednesday the bad news was that there was
more cocaine to seize.
   ``This is one of those good news-bad news situations,'' Customs
Commissioner William von Raab said in announcing that agents had
stopped a record 108,843 pounds of cocaine from being sold on
America's streets since the fiscal year began last Oct. 1.
   ``It's true that there is plenty of evidence that the amount of
cocaine being produced has increased significantly during recent
years,'' von Raab said, ``but the amount of cocaine we have been
seizing shows that we have greatly increased our ability to stop
it.''
   Von Raab credited a new automated system that compares cargo
manifests with programmed criteria to help customs officers decide
which shipments to examine.
   The system, he said, helped pinpoint the largest cocaine
shipment ever seized _ 9,230 pounds found in plastic containers
concealed in hallowed-out lumber shipped in a container that
arrived in Tampa, Fla., on April 28.
   Von Raab said officers have used the automated program to find
33,000 pounds of cocaine in cargo containers since November 1987.
   The commissioner said state and local police have helped in some
of the seizures. Operations in all of fiscal 1987 brought in 88,000
pounds.
   With a boom in cocaine production in South America, the amount
confiscated by federal and state officials has increased every year
since 1982 when it was only 11,150 pounds.
   In addition to seizures from commercial shipments, air
operations netted 22,000 pounds of cocaine and marine operations
accounted for another 17,500 pounds, von Raab said. The remainder
came in various operations along the nation's Southwest border and
elsewhere in the country, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
