<HEAD>U.S. Airlifting Emergency Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is airlifting emergency
shelters to Sudan where hundreds are feared dead from the worst
flooding to hit the northern African country in more than 40 years,
it was announced Wednesday.
   The United States has also given $1 million for other relief
supplies, as well as 1,200 tons of grain and food for the flood
victims in Khartoum, said a statement by the Agency for
International Development.
   The agency has arranged to airlift more than 850 rolls of
plastic sheets for tents to house some of the estimated 1.5 million
Sudanese left homeless by the high waters, AID said.
   In addition, an agency flood relief expert is en route to Sudan
to assess the damage. Once his report is completed, the United
States will determine how much additional aid it will provide to
the international effort getting under way to ease the flood
suffering, the statement said.
   American officials in Khartoum have already undertaken an aerial
survey of Khartoum and the Gedaref region to assess the damage, AID
said.
