<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--PianoContest 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Piano Contest, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0603,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 Pianists To Compete In Norwegian Competition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with three last-minute dropouts;
picks up 5th graf, ``The seven-member ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven pianists from 14 countries will
compete in the Crown Princess Sonja International Music Competition
starting Thursday.
   A committee of Norwegian pianists and music professors selected
the contestants _ 19 men and 8 women _ based on tapes from more
than 150 applicants aged 18-30.
   Representing the United States in the nine-day competition are
Steven Hayman, 28, of Syracuse, N.Y., and Jeffrey Biegel, 28, of
Plainview, N.Y.
   Other countries represented are Canada, China, Czechoslovakia,
Denmark, Finland, Hungary, Japan, Norway, South Korea, Sweden, the
United Kingdom, the U.S.S.R, West Germany and Yugoslavia.
   The committee originally had selected 30 pianists, but three
dropped out Wednesday because of illness.
   The seven-member jury is headed by New York-based Israeli
pianist Joseph Kalichstein.
   The prize money, $40,500, will be divided among six finalists,
with the winner receiving $18,100. The competition ends Aug. 19
with each finalist playing a 60-minute program.
</TEXT>
