<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Levchenko     08-10 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Levchenko,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass: Cosmonaut Died of Brain Tumor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brain tumor killed Cosmonaut Anatoly Levchenko,
who was in line to fly the new Soviet space shuttle, the Tass news
agency said Wednesday.
   The agency on Tuesday reported that Levchenko, 47, had died, but
did not mention the cause of death. Other obituaries said only that
he died Saturday of a ``grave illness.''
   Doctors operated on the test pilot after discovering the tumor
but were unable to save him, the official news agency said. The
obituary was the first confirmation that Levchenko was involved in
the shuttle program.
   ``In recent times he participated in research of space
technology and could have become a crew member of a future Soviet
reusable spaceship,'' Tass said.
   His death could set back the fledgling shuttle program.
   In an obituary signed by fellow cosmonauts and Soviet leaders,
the Communist Party daily Pravda said Wednesday that Levchenko
helped improve the effectiveness of his country's air force.
   Levchenko, born in the town of Krasnokutsk in the Ukraine,
joined a team of cosmonauts testing space vehicles in 1981, Tass
said.
   Earlier Soviet media reports have said Levchenko was preparing
for the first flight of the Soviet space shuttle.
   Levchenko last entered space on Dec. 21, when he and cosmonauts
Vladimir Titov and Musa Manarov lifted off aboard a Soyuz TM-4
capsule and docked two days later with the orbiting space station
Mir.
   He returned to Earth on Dec. 29 along with Alexander Alexandrov,
who had been aboard Mir since July 1987, and Yuri Romanenko, who
had spent a record 326 days in space.
   Titov and Manarov remain aboard Mir, and Soviet officials have
said the station will be manned permanently.
   Soviet space officials concede they are having problems
developing the space shuttle and have also given conflicting
indications about whether its first flight would be piloted or
unmanned.
   Officials have indicated the Soviet shuttle would be similar to
the U.S. space shuttle that has been grounded since the January
1986 explosion of the Challenger, which killed all seven crew
members.
   The Kremlin has not announced when the first launch of the
Soviet shuttle will take place, but officials had said privately
that the flight would probably be in the first half of this year _
a timetable that has not been met.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
