<1ST_LINE>r a AM-American-Expansion     08-10 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Expansion,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carrier Adds Crew Bases In Miami, Nashville</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines announced plans Wednesday to base
as many as 700 pilots and flight attendants in south Florida,
leaving it ready to capitalize on problems facing Eastern Airlines
and Pan American World Airways.
   ``American Airlines is deeply committed to the Florida market
and believes Florida will play a critical role in our future
expansion,'' said Robert W. Baker, senior vice president for
operations of the carrier, based in Fort Worth, Texas.
   A spokeswoman for Miami-based Eastern said American's plans
shouldn't affect the struggling carrier. Miami-area business and
government leaders expressed delight at American's plans, which the
carrier's officials estimate will pump more than $70 million a year
into the south Florida economy.
   ``I am very, very, extremely pleased,'' said Clara Oesterle, a
Dade County commissioner who attended American's news conference.
``This means a lot to this community.''
   She noted that Miami International Airport relies heavily on
user fees. Eastern and Pan Am, the two largest users of the
airport, have said they need labor concessions to avoid cutting
back operations.
   American's expansion to south Florida is based on expectations
that the Florida and Caribbean markets will continue to grow, not
on problems competitors are having, Baker said.
   ``The specific and well-known problems of Eastern really had
very little to do with our decision,'' Baker said, but added the
expansion in Miami will ``give us some additional flexibility'' in
case some of the Latin American routes now flown by Pan Am and
Eastern become available.
   American, based in Texas, also plans to add a flight attendant
crew base in Nashville, Tenn., one of five American hubs. American
also has hubs in Dallas-Fort Worth, Chicago, Raleigh-Durham and San
Juan.
   The Miami and Nashville crew bases bring American's total crew
bases to 12. American said it will staff a new flight attendant
crew base in Nashville with 75 flight attendants in October and
perhaps as many as 600 in the early 1990s.
   American officials were unsure how many employees might
eventually be added. Baker said several hundred American employees
already live in south Florida and commute to the hubs.
   By January, American will base 160 flight crew members in Miami,
Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach, Baker said. The total will
reach 700 ``within a few years,'' he said.
   Eastern, with its corporate headquarters here, has some 850
pilots and 1,800 flight attendants based in Miami, she said.
   ``I don't think it will have any effect,'' Eastern spokeswoman
Paula Musto said, referring to American's move. ``American is in a
growing mode, and if Miami is their choice, I say more power to the
Miami community and economy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
