<DOCNO> AP880810-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AfricaTour     08-10 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa Tour,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Inner-City Youngsters Return from Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They returned in triumph from travels half a
world away _ 10 black youngsters who overcame considerable odds to
make their dreams of Africa come true.
   The children from Suder Elementary School, ages 11 to 14, raised
$30,000 in less than 10 months to pay for the two-week trip that
took them from one of Chicago's poorest neighborhoods to Senegal,
Ivory Coast and Togo on the West African coast, the ancestral
homeland of many American blacks.
   The excited young travelers stood out Tuesday in the bustling
crowds at O'Hare International Airport, with their carved walking
sticks and identical green knapsacks proclaiming ``Africa.''
   All had stories to tell.
   ``We just spoke French a little because so many people we met
knew English, but we did say `bonjour' a lot,'' said Yo-seanda
Baines, 13.
   ``We saw the slave houses where they kept the slaves. We saw the
Senegal museum. It was wonderful,'' said Hardy Shorter, 12. ``We
saw the African sculptures from long ago.''
   ``We had food pretty much like we have here,'' said Charnae
Harmon, 13. ``We learned to eat like the Africans, though, using
our fingers.''
   ``We had fish and rice a lot, and chicken and rice a lot, too,''
said her twin sister, Renee.
   Souvenirs were chosen carefully _ and imaginatively.
   Charlene Brown came home with a new braided hair style, courtesy
of her Senegalese pen pal's mother.
   ``It was a souvenir I could take everywhere,'' she said.
   ``Most of the boys bought some noisy hand games where you
clatter wooden balls together, and the girls mostly bought tribal
jewelry and handbags,'' said Suder Principal Brenda Daigre, whose
previous travels in Africa made her the driving force behind the
student effort.
   ``We all bought a lot of carved wood, but no ivory. We're poor
people.''
   The students prepared for the trip by writing to African pen
pals, taking after-school classes in African culture and art, and
studying French for a year. All three countries are former French
colonies.
   But the big hurdle was the money.
   Some of the funds came from churches and community groups, but
the students raised much of it by running a candy store at school
and by putting on a talent show and basketball and volleyball
games, Mrs. Daigre said.
   ``We taught them how to set long-range goals,'' the principal
said of the youngsters, most of whom live in the Henry Horner
public housing project.
   Some parents were skeptical.
   ``I remember last October, when they came home from school and
said: `Guess what? We're going to go to Africa,''' said George
West, as he waited for his sons, Brian, 12, and Daryl, 11, to clear
customs.
   ``I just said, `Yeah ... right,' but ... they made a believer
out of me.''
   Mrs. Daigre said an earlier visit to Africa made her feel she
had ``come home,'' and that she wanted her students to have a
chance to discover their own African roots.
   The principal, who accompanied the youngsters, said the trip
worked out so well she wants to arrange another one and is working
on a permanent cultural exchange with a journalist the travelers
met in Senegal.
   ``It was a complete success,'' the principal said. ``Nobody got
sick, nobody got lost and nobody spent too much money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
