<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MedicareCare     08-10 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicare Care,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Care Inadequate for More Than 6 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 6 percent of Medicare patients are
receiving substandard hospital care, with lower quality more likely
in small, rural hospitals, according to government figures released
Wednesday.
   The study of hospitalized Medicare patients in fiscal 1985 found
that 6.6 percent received substandard care, particularly omissions,
mistakes, unnecessary procedures and inadequate documentation of
medical records.
   ``Small hospitals had the highest overall rates of poor quality
patient care,'' the Department of Health and Human Services report
said.
   Hospitals with fewer than 100 beds had a rate of 11.4 percent of
substandard care, the report said. By comparison, hospitals with
between 100 beds and 200 beds had problems in 5.1 percent of
patients. Large hospitals had a 3.5 percent rate of substandard
care.
   By location, rural hospitals recorded poor quality care in 10.7
percent of cases, compared with 4.1 percent for urban hospitals,
the study said.
   Non-profit and profit-making facilities had similar rates: 5.7
percent for the profit-makers and 6.7 percent for non-profits.
   Teaching hospitals did well, with 3.0 percent getting poor care,
compared with 7.9 percent for non-teaching facilities.
   Most patients receiving substandard care had multiple problems,
the report found. The illnesses most often associated with lack of
good care were strokes, penumonia, respiratory failure, fainting,
kidney and urinary infections.
   Overall, the study estimated that the government paid hospitals
$1.2 billion in 1985 for patients who received poor quality care.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
