<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0664,0952</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Vows to Fight Palestinian Statehood</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf pvs `Troops meanwhile ...' with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with death of wounded Palestinian. Picks up last graf pvs
`Elsewhere 1st...' .
^LaserPhoto JRL1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir called on
Palestinians Wednesday to end their uprising and negotiate peace
with Israel, and he vowed he would fight the establishment of an
Arab homeland in the occupied lands.
   ``Israel will prevent in the most determined way any attempt to
carry out any idea _ to the extent that there are madmen who raise
it _ of establishing a Palestinian government,'' Shamir told
Parliament. ``Such people will be met with an iron fist that will
leave no trace of their attempts.''
   A declaration of independence published last week called for a
Palestinian state in the West Bank, Gaza Strip, parts of the
Galilee and east Jerusalem.
   The proposal came after Jordan said it was severing legal and
administrative links with the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. Jordan
had maintained the ties even though Israel captured the territories
in 1967.
   King Hussein of Jordan said he severed the ties because the
Palestine Liberation Organization is the sole legitimate
representative of Palestinians.
   In his first public comments on Hussein's move, PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat said his group is capable of taking over Jordan's
administrative role.
   Arafat also criticized Jordan and the PLO's Arab allies, who had
been forewarned, for failing to notify the PLO before Jordan acted.
   ``The PLO was not consulted beforehand and was not officially
notified until after the measures (by Jordan) were announced, when
it (the PLO) is the party that is directly concerned in all this,''
said Arafat.
   He insisted the PLO is capable of assuming Jordan's
administrative role in the occupied lands, and he assured the 1.5
million Palestinians living there that the PLO's institutions ``are
capable of absorbing everything.''
   Arafat's remarks were published Tuesday in the Saudi Arabian
newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat. Copies of the paper were obtained in
Bahrain on Wednesday.
   Shamir, responding to left-wing critics, told Parliament during
a special session that Jordan's move would ``harm the Arab
residents and not the state of Israel, which will continue to
maintain legal and security control as always.''
   The session was called by leftist factions protesting Israel's
failure to seek a dialogue with Palestinians and its tough tactics
in quelling the eight-month uprising in which 238 Palestinians and
four Israelis have died.
   ``At this fateful moment, what does our government say to the
Palestinians? Nothing, but force them to live in degradation,''
said Gad Yatziv of the socialist Mapam Party. ``How long will you
go on deceiving yourselves before you realize the bombings and
deportations won't do any good?''
   Shamir, whose 20-minute speech was interrupted half a dozen
times by catcalls, said Israel sought a dialogue with Palestinians
but would never negotiate with the PLO or countenance attempts to
create a Palestinian state.
   ``It must be clear as the noon sun ... the state of Israel will
not play this game,'' said Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud
bloc.
   In an earlier closed-door Cabinet meeting, Shamir argued with
his coalition partner, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the
left-leaning Labor Party, about peace policies, Israel radio
reported. Shamir accused Peres of siding with Arabs who contend
Likud is blocking peace, the radio said.
   In a related development, Labor ministers said the party, which
has based its peace strategy on Jordan, was considering a change in
its platform for November elections in the wake of Hussein's latest
steps.
   Energy Minister Moshe Shahal told The Associated Press the party
may add a plank saying Israel would speak ``either to Palestinians
from the West Bank and Gaza or Jordanians, but preferably
together.''
   The platform now calls for peace talks with a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation and favors territorial compromise
with Jordan.
   Arafat told the Saudi newspaper he opposes sending a
Palestinian-Jordanian delegation to a proposed Middle East peace
conference because ``that idea has been erased from our dictionary
even though Jordan has been repeating it.'' He said the PLO prefers
sending a pan-Arab delegation that would include Egypt.
   In Cairo on Wednesday, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Murphy ended his Middle East tour after failing to initiate
Arab-Israeli peace talks. Besides Egypt, Murphy visited Lebanon,
Syria, Israel and Jordan.
   On Tuesday, Murphy said Egypt failed to arrange a Cairo meeting
between him and Palestinian representatives. He gave no reason, but
a Palestinian source, who demanded anonymity, said Murphy objected
to two proposed participants because they were closely linked to
the PLO.
   Also on Wednesday, an Israeli soldier was burned in the face and
hands by a firebomb thrown at a military jeep in the West Bank city
of Ramallah. An Arab woman also was slightly burned on the leg in
the attack, the army said.
   Troops, meanwhile, fatally wounded a 17-year-old Palestinian in
a clash with Arab protesters who stoned a military fuel tank in the
village of Tubas, Al Ittihad Hospital officials said.
   The youth, Ahmed Salah Darameh, died on the operating table at
the hospital after he was shot in the chest, according to a
hospital official who demanded anonymity. His death brought the
number of Palestinian deaths in the eight-month revolt to 239. Four
Israelis also have died.
   Elsewhere, 1st Lt. Orit Wolf said the army had begun using
attack dogs against Palestinian rioters in the West Bank, three
newspapers reported. The army said this was against military policy
and it was checking the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
