<1ST_LINE>r i AM-French-Oil     08-10 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-French-Oil,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Company Sinking Well on Edge Of Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil company is drilling an exploratory well just
outside Paris under a permit that could lead to similar projects
inside the capital.
   The company, Societe Nationale Elf Aquitaine, said drilling the
6,000-foot-deep hole in the southern suburb of Ivry-Sur-Seine will
take about three weeks.
   The exploratory well at Ivry, 1\ miles outside the Paris, is the
first under the Paris-Ile de France permit shared by Elf, Total
Compagnie Francaise des Petroles and British Petroleum.
   The permit, awarded in December 1985, covers 590 square miles
and includes the city of Paris. The area is part of the Paris
Basin, a 50,000-square-mile region that stretches from Paris
eastward to the West German border.
   It has 40 million tons of known oil reserves.
   The drilling at Ivry is being done on an industrial site owned
by the state-run power company, Electricite de France. The
exploratory well is the culmination of extensive seismic studies of
the permit area which found several structures that might contain
hydrocarbons, Elf officials said.
   Total has said it will drill a well on its share of the permit
by the end of the year. British Pertroleum has not disclosed its
plans.
   Jean Perrot, Elf's assistant director of exploration in France,
has said the drilling at Ivry, which began Tuesday, will help
determine the size of the structure there and whether it contains
oil in marketable quantities.
   A success at Ivry would encourage more extensive testing inside
Paris, where seismic tests were limited and particularly difficult
because of the subway system, sewerage lines and other
interferences, a spokesman for Elf, Alexis Poutchkovsky, said in a
recent interview.
</TEXT>
