<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LiquorWarnings     08-10 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liquor Warnings,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Asked to Delay Alcohol Labeling Bill Pending Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration asked Congress on
Wednesday to delay acting on a proposal to require health warning
labels on alcoholic beverages until a study of the bill's impact is
completed.
   William T. Drake, deputy director of the Treasury Department's
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, told a Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation subcommittee that his agency is studying
the issue and would report to Congress by the end of the year.
   ``While the administration is on record as recognizing that the
health hazards related to alcohol consumption comprise one of the
nation's most serious problems, we believe any legislation should
await the completion of studies on the impacts of alcohol
labeling,'' Drake said.
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., would
require five rotating labels on beer, wine and distilled spirits.
They would warn against abuse of alcohol during pregnancy, the
dangers of liver disease, hypertension and cancer, impaired driving
ability, the danger of combining alcohol with other drugs and the
addictive nature of alcohol.
   ``Not only does common sense tell us that consumers need to be
more aware of the effects of alcohol, experts in the field have
long been calling for alcohol warning labels,'' Thurmond said.
   Thurmond displayed a pamphlet he said had been recently
distributed to all Senate offices by the Distilled Spirits Council
of the United States, claiming to reflect ``the latest findings in
alcohol research.''
   Thurmond said the pamphlet `` contains not one word about the
dangers of drinking while pregnant, not one word.''
   A committee spokeswoman said the liquor industry declined to
testify at the hearing.
</TEXT>
