<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NATO-NuclearWeapons     08-10 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Nuclear Weapons,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Making `Significant' Cuts in Short-Range Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization is
studying a ``fairly significant'' cut in short-range atomic weapons
that could be announced later this year, NATO's top military
officer said Wednesday.
   The cuts will be part of a package aimed at modernizing NATO's
arsenal of tactical atomic weapons, in which older weapons are
replaced by newer weapons, U.S. Army Gen. John R. Galvin said.
   Galvin's staff is halfway through a study involving the
modernization of NATO's battlefield nuclear weapons, he told
reporters.
   ``My own judgment of it (the study) is that it will result in
another reduction in the overall number of warheads and it will be
a fairly significant reduction, but the reduction will be
contingent on the modernization we can get,'' Galvin said.
   The study will be finished in December or January, Galvin said.
He declined to say how many weapons would be involved.
   ``I don't want to quantify now and I can't quantify now because
I really don't know what the number would be and I don't want to
make any guess at it. I would say it's going to be a significant
number,'' he explained.
   The United States and the Soviet Union now are conducting
preliminary-round inspections as part of the Intermediate-Range
Nuclear Forces treaty, which requires both sides to eliminate all
medium- and short-range nuclear missiles within three years. The
INF cuts will eliminate weapons with ranges of 320 miles to 3,000
miles, but still will leave both sides with large arsenals of
so-called tactical weapons with ranges of less than 320 miles.
   After INF, NATO still will have about 4,200 tactical nuclear
weapons, including bombs, artillery shells and the Lance missile.
The Lance, with a range of 70 miles, is one of the prime weapons
NATO wants to modernize.
   The newest cuts would come out of the 4,200 total, Galvin said.
   The Soviets do not publish any statistics about their nuclear
weapons inventory, but are estimated to have far more
tactical-range weapons than NATO. For example, the Soviets have an
estimated 9,100 artillery and missile launchers capable of being
loaded with atomic-tipped weapons.
   The issue is politically sensitive, particularly in West
Germany, where many of the tactical-range weapons are based. If
those weapons are used, they are likely to fall upon German soil,
Galvin noted.
   The upcoming cuts ``will help express to the Germans that we are
aware of their concerns,'' said Galvin. He contended that ``there
is no political purpose or intention in bringing this up now.''
   On two other occasions in recent years, NATO has announced
unilateral reductions, Galvin noted, including a cut of 1,000
warheads and a second decrease of 1,400.
   ``This is going to be a unilateral reduction, as the other ones
were,'' Galvin noted.
   ``I don't think we've taken enough credit for the fact that
we've already made two very large unilateral reductions,'' he said.
``The Soviets would have made that a massive propaganda campaign''
had they made similar cuts, he said.
   One of the reasons for the reductions will be the fact that the
Soviets will lose some of their most threatening nuclear weapons
because of the INF pact, Galvin said.
   ``It isn't a question of what do we have, it is a question of
what do we have versus what do they have,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
