<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOPMoney     08-10 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Money,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Orleans Surpassses $5.5 Million Goal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Orleans has surpassed the $5.5 million
goal set for its share of costs for the Republican National
Convention, officials announced Wednesday.
   ``As of last night, we had $5,589,000 and contributions are
still coming in,'' said Ron Jones, chairman of the New Orleans
Special Events Fund.
   More than $3 million, including $800,000 from the state, was
raised since May 11, when oilman Pat Taylor, in charge of
fund-raising at first, complained that it was going too slowly and
that big corporations were reluctant to dig into their bank
accounts.
   Taylor's group, the Greater New Orleans Convention Fund, had
raised about $620,000 in about eight months.
   ``Ninety days ago, we were several hundred thousand dollars
short of being halfway to our goal,'' he said Wednesday. ``Amongst
the things I had to say then was that I knew this city would come
together. It has come together.''
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy said it was significant that New
Orleans' money came from donations instead of a tax like the one
Atlanta used to help pay for the Democratic National Convention.
   ``This day has proven that New Orleans is a major-league city.
That ... we are all wearing the same jersey. We are all pulling
together,'' he said.
   The money was needed for work pledged by the city to bring the
Republican Party to New Orleans for the conventionn Aug. 15-18.
   Those costs include $1 million each for the lighting system set
up for the convention and for electrical work; $900,000 in
construction, $700,000 for security and $630,000 for insurance.
   The 950 to 960 donors included all seven parishes in the New
Orleans metropolitan area and some outside of the region, Jones
said. He said corporate contributions ranged from $100 to $250,000.
</TEXT>
