<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Art     08-10 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Art,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Probe to Determine if Two Statues Smuggled to California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian magistrate is investigating whether two
6th century B.C. statues were stolen from an archaeological dig in
Sicily and smuggled to California, a Culture Ministry spokeswoman
said Wednesday.
   The two marble heads were believed taken in 1979 from an illegal
excavation site in Morgantina, Sicily, said the spokeswoman, who
demanded anonymity.
   Judge Silvio Raffiotta, an investigating magistrate in Enna,
Sicily, was trying to determine whether the artifacts had turned up
in California through an illegal art-trafficking network, she said.
   Some reports have said the two statues wound up in the J. Paul
Getty Museum in Malibu, Calif., but the spokeswoman said that had
not been determined.
   She said she could provide no more details of the statues or the
investigation. ``The case is very delicate,'' the spokeswoman said.
``The investigation is covered by judicial secrecy.''
   Raffiotta's investigation is separate from another investigation
into the background of a 5th century B.C. Greek statue that
recently went on display at the Getty museum. Italian investigators
and Interpol are checking whether that statue, believed to be of
the goddess Aphrodite, was stolen from an illegal dig in Morgantina
in 1979.
   Italian newspapers reported Wednesday that the two marble heads
were of greater historical and artistic value than the statue.
</TEXT>
