<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Iceland     08-10 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iceland,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iceland's Prime Minister Hopes Arms Talks Succeed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Thorsteinn Palsson of Iceland
told President Reagan on Wednesday he hopes the United States and
the Soviet Union find agreement on slashing stockpiles of
long-range nuclear weapons.
   Palsson, who heads the government of a tiny nation of 250,000
with no defense force, said that maintaining world peace depends to
a large extent on the success of the superpowers' negotiations in
Geneva.
   Reagan, in a departure statement after hosting Palsson for a
meeting and lunch, noted that Iceland had hosted his historic
October 1986 summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``on
such short notice.''
   ``In the wake of the Moscow summit, I must note that the talks
that the general secretary and I had in Hodfi House (in Reykjavik)
were an important milestone in the development of our current
dialogue with the Soviet Union,'' the president said.
   Reagan credited solidarity in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization with helping the United States achieve the
Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces accord, eliminating an entire
class of medium- and shorter-range superpower missiles. That pact
was consummated during the May summit that Reagan and Gorbachev had
in Moscow.
   During the Reykjavik summit, Reagan and Gorbachev discussed
banning long-range nuclear missiles. That summit disintegrated amid
what the United States said was a Soviet insistence that Reagan
abandon his Star Wars missile defense program.
   In his salute to the 40-year-old Palsson, head of the
Independence Party and head of government since July 1987, Reagan
noted that he was the first Icelandic prime minister to make an
official working visit to the United States.
   Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway, who specializes in
Canadian and European affairs, said Iceland has a ``special
interest'' in the strategic missile talks in Geneva ``in what is
done about sea-launched nuclear cruise missiles. But beyond
expressing that special interest, the prime minister did not go
into details.''
   The United States views Iceland as a small but highly
significant NATO ally, located strategically to monitor Soviet
ships and installations.
   Also on the agenda of Palsson's four-day Washington visit are
meetings with congressional leaders and with Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci. On Friday, Palsson travels to the Atlantic
Forces command in Norfolk, Va., for a tour of the aircraft carrier
Theodore Roosevelt.
</TEXT>
