<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MigrantAid     08-10 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Migrant Aid,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heinz Donates $50,000 For Migrant Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Money Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heinz USA said Wednesday it has donated
$50,000 to help cover travel costs of migrant farm workers, whose
season picking tomatoes and cucumbers in the northern Midwest has
been cut short by the drought.
   The president of the Farm Labor Organizing Committee, Baldemar
Velasquez, praised Heinz's efforts, but criticized Ohio for not
providing enough emergency relief to migrants.
   ``It is currently recognized that due to the drought, there will
be reduced earnings on the part of the local producers and farm
workers,'' said Ronald Brooks, Midwest Agricultural Manager for
Heinz USA in Fremont, a division of H.J. Heinz Co.
   ``This program is positioned as a supplement to these reduced
earnings. ... It will not replace the earnings. But it is our
intent that it will aid them in returning to their homes or their
next work site,'' Brooks told a news conference. ``It is clear that
this sum of money will not meet all the needs. However, it is a
start.''
   The money will be offered in northwest Ohio and southeast
Michigan through the Migrant Farmworker Emergency Assistance
Program. It will be administered by WSOS Community Action
Commission Inc., of Fremont, and Ohio Farmworker Opportunity Inc.,
of Bowling Green. Both agencies have agreed to donate
administrative costs.
   Growers are being asked to complete forms about family size and
income. Families with incomes at least 25 percent below normal as a
result of the drought will be eligible for payments of up to $150.
   In addition, Velasquez said the Farm Labor Organizing Committee
has donated $1,100 to the fund, and is seeking donations from other
processors in the area.
   Paul Blausey, president of the Fremont Pickle and Tomato Growers
Association, said the program will help retain people to harvest
crops in a very difficult year.
   About 10,000 migrant workers come to the region each year to
pick fruits and vegetables. But this year, because the drought has
severely damaged tomatoes and cucumbers, many have been unable to
find work and left before the harvest. Others have not made enough
money to return home.
   There are about 6,500 migrant workers in northwest Ohio and
southeast Michigan now, Velasquez said, citing estimates that 60
percent of them will earn less than 75 percent of their normal
income.
   Velasquez said he is disappointed that the state has not
provided enough emergency help for Ohio farm workers, who pick $85
million worth of crops each year.
   The union has recommended to the state drought task force that
money be provided for emergency unemployment compensation to the
farm workers who are unemployed or underemployed because of the
drought.
   ``We have not been contacted by the state in terms of the
necessary needs that are out there and what kind of programs could
be created to alleviate the situation,'' he said.
   ``We are running out of time. ... We are still in a crisis and a
race against time. Pretty soon it is going to be too late,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
