<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Marshall     08-10 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marshall,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marshall Says Fight Against Racism Far From Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall said
Wednesday ``racism is broader and stronger than before'' and
America has a long way to go to achieve racial equality.
   ``We're not gaining ground, my friends. We might be losing
ground,'' Marshall, the only black ever to sit on the high court,
told the annual convention of the National Bar Association, an
organization of black lawyers and judges.
   ``One thing I'm sure of: This is no time to stop'' fighting for
racial equality, he said.
   Marshall urged his listeners to work toward ``a goal that is the
basis of true democracy.''
   That goal, he said, is to assure that ``a Negro child born ...
in a state like Mississippi or any other state like that, born to
the dumbest, poorest sharecropper'' has the same rights of a child
``born to a white parent, the wealthiest person in the United
States.''
   Marshall received an enthusiastic round of applause for the
remarks and a sustained ovation when he was given a crystal pyramid
as the ``justice of the 20th century.''
   Marshall, 80, was named to the Supreme Court by President
Johnson in 1967. For decades, his name was synonymous with the
fight for civil rights. He served as chief counsel of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People for 23 years.
   Marshall recalled that the National Bar Association, which now
has 12,000 members and conducted its annual meeting in one of
Washington's finest hotels, could not always afford such plush
surroundings.
   ``Indeed, we couldn't come in the front door,'' he said.
   Marshall rejected what he said was the suggestion by some that
the fight for racial equality has been won.
   ``Why do we have to have a National Bar Association today _ this
late date, as some people would think?'' Marshall asked. ``Well,
the answer is simple. It's not that late.''
   The association was created in 1925 to promote civil rights and
to provide black lawyers with an alternative to the American Bar
Association, the nation's largest lawyer group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
