<DOCNO> AP880810-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoolKid     08-10 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cool Kid,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cool 9-Year-Old Lays Low, Turns In Burglar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quick-thinking 9-year-old who spotted
a burglar hid behind a couch, waited until the man walked to the
other end of the house, then grabbed a phone and called police.
   ``This is an emergency. Somebody just broke into a house,''
Tyson, whose parents asked that his last name not be made public,
told police during the break-in Monday at his family's suburban
home.
   Tamara Garcia, the communications officer who took the call,
spoke to the boy softly, hoping to keep him calm and gather
information.
   ``Try and stay as quiet as you can,'' she advised. ``And stay on
the line with me, OK? Did you see the person?''
   Tyson, shaking with fear, managed to remain hidden and keep his
voice to a whisper for four minutes, giving Garcia his address.
   ``I could hear him throwing things around,'' Tyson said. ``I
knew he was back there.''
   Deputies say they caught Robert Petocchelli, 31, of Miami,
ransacking the master bedroom, said Sgt. Ken Deischer of the Palm
Beach County sheriff's office. Petocchelli, charged with armed
burglary and possession of burglary tools, was released from the
county jail after posting $13,500 bond Tuesday, a jail spokesman
said.
   Deischer said Petocchelli confessed and said he is an associate
of Peter Salerno, a cat burglar whose gang plucked millions of
dollars worth of jewelry from southern Florida homes during the
1970s.
   Tyson kept calm and stayed out of sight the whole time, Deischer
said, and Petocchelli never saw him.
   The officer praised the boy for possibly giving detectives a
break in a recent string of daytime burglaries outside Boca Raton.
   ``A kid has to have a little bit of courage to do something like
that,'' he said. ``He deserves some kind of recognition.''
   Deputies are asking their superiors to give Tyson a citation for
bravery. In the meantime, Tyson's parents are just glad their son
could handle the pressure.
   ``We told him he didn't act like a child, he acted like a man,''
his mother said.
</TEXT>
