<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VincennesReunion     08-10 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Reunion,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USS Vincennes Reunion Supports Captain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VINCENNES, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year, Capt. Will C. Rogers III stood
before the USS Vincennes Association, a guest at its annual
reunion. This year, the group stands behind Rogers, skipper of the
vessel that shot down an Iranian jetliner.
   The association is open to crewmen from any of the four USS
Vincennes ships, the first of which was commissioned in 1826.
   As the more than 130 veterans arrived at a hotel this week for
the group's 15th reunion, they passed by a copy of a telegram the
organization sent to Rogers and his crew expressing support after
the accidental downing of the jet July 3 over the Persian Gulf. All
290 people aboard the plane died.
   A Pentagon inquiry is reported to have blamed human error caused
by the stress of first-time combat. The inquiry found no evidence
that the ship's sophisticated Aegis radar system malfunctioned,
sources said.
   ``Our hearts are heavy for the captain, but we feel he made the
proper decision,'' Antonio A. Coito, first vice president of the
association and a gunner on the third USS Vincennes. ``His first
decision is to the ship and crew and equipment.
   ``I would prefer to make a mistake rather than have men injured
and damaged. We feel the captain should not be reprimanded or
penalized in any way,'' Coito, 62, of Charlotte, Mich., said
Tuesday.
   Ed Michalowski, 76, of East Islip, N.Y., agreed. ``You only have
a certain amount of time _ seconds and minutes _ from the time you
sight something until the time you have to go into action,'' said
Michalowski, a fireman 1st class aboard the third Vincennes, the
light cruiser CL-64.
   ``You saw what happened to the Stark. He waited,'' Michalowski
added.
   The USS Stark, a guided missile frigate, was struck by a missile
from an Iraqi fighter during Persian Gulf duty in 1987. Thirty
seven crew members died and the captain was relieved of his duty
and retired from the Navy.
   The reunion runs through Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
