<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Gulf     08-10 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Arabs, Japan To Help Fund Peacekeeping Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Wednesday urged Arab
nations and Japan to donate money to the U.N. military observer
group that will monitor the cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   The United States is the most delinquent contributor to the
U.N.'s regular budget, accounting for $467 million of the $602
million in unpaid assessments.
   ``If we continue at this rate,'' the United Nations will be
bankrupt before October, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   The U.N. also is monitoring the Soviet withdrawal from
Afghanistan, preparing to supervise independence elections in
Namibia, submitting peace proposals in the Western Sahara guerrilla
war and preparing to help warring parties in Cambodia reach a
power-sharing agreement.
   The General Assembly will reconvene in a special session next
Tuesday to assess its 159 members for the $74 million that the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group will cost in its first six months.
   The United States expects to be assessed about $23 million of
that amount, said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley in
Washington.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States also owes $70 million to the
U.N. peacekeeping budget, which is separate from the regular
operating budget.
   The 350 U.N. observers are to be in place within a week. The
cease-fire in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war is to take effect
Aug. 20.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said: ``We
do intend to urge the gulf states, who are the chief beneficiaries
of this settlement, to share in the cost through voluntary
contributions.
   ``We'll be giving the same message to other countries like Japan
and others who have an interest in the gulf,'' he said. Japan
imports nearly all its oil from the gulf region.
   Japan donated $20 million in April to U.N. peace efforts,
designating half for the Iran-Iraq peace effort and half for the
Afghanistan accords.
   Those funds are being used as the seed money to begin the
Iran-Iraq cease-fire monitoring effort, said Giuliani.
   The Security Council met Wednesday in informal consultations to
approve the secretary-general's list of nations sending officers to
monitor the cease-fire.
   The nations are: Argentina, Australia, Austria, Bangladesh,
Canada, Denmark, Finland, Ghana, Hungary, Indonesia, India,
Ireland, Italy, Kenya, Malaysia, New Zealand, Nigeria, Norway,
Poland, Senegal, Sweden, Turkey, Yugoslavia, and Zambia.
   The United States' U.N. dues are more than $200 million a year,
a quarter of the world body's regular budget.
   The United States has said it is holding back funding to press
for reform in the budget-making process, personnel cuts and changes
in personnel practices that it says leave Soviet U.N. employees
under Moscow's control.
</TEXT>
