<HEAD>St. Marys May Get Visit From NBC Weatherman After All</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. MARYS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What started out as a cruel hoax on the
people of St. Marys could get a happy ending in November if popular
TV weatherman Willard Scott makes it for a visit.
   A spokesman for NBC in New York said Scott, the genial
weatherman on the ``Today'' show, wanted to do something to ease
the disappointment of residents, who found out earlier this month
that news of a pending visit by Scott was a hoax.
   ``We are trying to arrange a visit to St. Marys for sometime in
November,'' said spokesman John Bianchi. ``It's definitely in
response to that unfortunate incident. Willard felt bad, so he said
to try to work out the details because he didn't want to disappoint
the folks down there.''
   Bianchi said Tuesday that Scott will not do be able to do a show
in St. Marys, but would spend a day getting to know the people. He
said details will be worked out later.
   In late July, a woman visited the tiny coastal town, which
borders Florida's east coast, and said she was with NBC. She began
making detailed plans for Scott and newsman John Palmer to visit
the area and do a documentary on the impact of the Navy's Kings Bay
submarine base on the community.
   Martha Newsome, executive director of the Kingsland Tour and
Travel Association, said people in St. Marys and her nearby town
developed ``a real Willard-mania'' because of Scott's reported
visit.
   She described them as ``flabbergasted'' after they discovered
that Scott had no plans to visit Georgia.
   The mysterious woman, who stayed in town 10 days, suddenly
checked out of her motel Aug. 2 and has not been seen since.
   ``Today'' spokeswoman Kathy Graham said the woman does not work
for NBC.
