<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WrongRunway     08-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong Runway,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tired Airliner Crew Mistook Highway for Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tired cockpit crew working illegally long hours
mistook a busy British highway for a nearby airport runway and were
preparing to land their packed airliner on it, aviation experts
said Wednesday.
   They said the captain was looking at the M-56 highway instead of
Manchester Airport when he told air traffic controllers he had the
runway in sight and would land visually.
   The highway landing was aborted at the last moment after the
co-pilot realized the error, the Royal Air Force Institute of
Aviation Medicine said. The aircraft touched down safely at the
airport.
   The report quoted the co-pilot as saying he realized the flight
would mean he would exceed his limit of 11{ hours continuous duty,
but the pilot was under commercial pressure and asked him to say he
came on duty one hour later than he did.
   The institute passed the report to the Civil Aviation Authority.
The authority finances the institute program for the discovery and
study of stress problems. The number of people aboard the airliner
was not given, nor were names, airline or date of the flight
disclosed.
   Identifying details would never be published because air crews
were invited on a pledge of secrecy to submit such accounts, the
authority said.
   The institute said it gets about 250 reports of this nature each
year. They are printed in Royal Air Force bulletins subscribed to
by 13,000 people around the world and enable pilots to learn from
the errors of their colleagues.
</TEXT>
