<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf
Jr. on Wednesday defended attacks on Michael Dukakis as ``the
unvarnished truth'' and said the Democratic presidential nominee is
trying to deflect legitimate criticism by accusing opponents of
negative campaigning.
   In a speech to the Republican National Committee, Fahrenkopf
cited Democratic attacks on Vice President George Bush and said,
``See if you can find any better examples of negative campaigning.
And the Democrats have the nerve to point the finger at us.''
   Meeting less than a week before the opening of their convention,
GOP officials also were told the national committee began the month
with $13.5 million in the bank and would spend more than $70
million to help party candidates at all levels.
   Larry Bathgate, chairman of the party finance committee, said
his group raised $34.9 million during the first seven months of the
election year and expected to raise up to $6 million at a luncheon
the final day of the convention.
   A sampling of national committee members all cited Bush's speech
accepting the presidential nomination as the most important moment
of the convention.
   ``We all want to hear a good strong speech, issues oriented,''
said Jennifer Dunn, Washington GOP chairman.
   Spencer Abraham, Michigan GOP chairman, said Bush muist use the
convention ``to establish that he has become the head of the
Republican Party.''
   Fahrenkopf cited Bush's appearance ealier in the week before the
GOP platform committee when the vice president referred to Dukakis
as ``the stealth candidate'' and said the Massachusetts governor
was invisible on the issues.
   ``Dukakis is already crying foul,'' said Fahrenkopf. ``But how
can Dukakis call this negative campaigning and go unchallenged?
   ``Yes, the vice president's remarks were critical. ... But the
vice president used a memorable rhetorical device to make a point
grounded in fact _ that Dukakis will not discuss the issues.''
   Fahrenkopf said criticism of the Massachusetts furlough program
under which convicted murderers were allowed to spend weekends away
from prison ``was not mudslinging, because it was the unvarnished
truth.''
   The GOP chairman also accused Dukakis of using negative tactics
during the Democratic primary campaign and said, ``Dukakis is using
the oldest trick in politics: he and his people say the most
outlandish things, and then denounce any response as mudslinging.''
