<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtest     08-10 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protest,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Falwell Lends Support, Gives Money To Abortion Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion protesters from several states rallied
with evangelist Jerry Falwell on Wednesday, 57 were arrested for
blocking clinic entrances and the number jailed since
demonstrations began rose to more than 300.
   Asked if he planned to join those being arrested Wednesday,
Falwell said, ``Not today, but I'm willing to be, and I'm sure
before it's over it will happen.''
   Police said 57 people, many clutching Bibles, were charged with
criminal trespass and giving a false name after they blocked the
entrances to Feminist Women's Health Center.
   About 200 people picketed or held signs with graphic displays of
aborted fetuses. They cheered, clapped and sang hymns as their
companions were arrested and taken away in prison buses.
   While some protesters blocked entrances, others confronted
patients as they tried to enter the clinic, shouting, ``Don't kill
your baby! We can help you! We can give you anything you need!''
   Several patients were escorted through the protesters by clinic
workers wearing identifying T-shirts, and at one point, police
helped lift a patient over seated demonstrators.
   Wednesday's arrests pushed to 333 the number of people charged
in seven scattered days of protests, which began last month during
the Democratic National Convention. Most of the seven Atlanta
clinics that perform abortions have been targeted during the
demonstrations, which are unannounced but highly organized.
   In a related protest in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., 42 demonstrators
remained in jail Wednesday in the wake of a three-day vigil and
march to free Joan Andrews, who is serving a five-year sentence for
leading a 1986 raid on a Pensacola abortion clinic.
   Several dozen protesters remain in jail in Atlanta because they
refuse to identify themselves, instead giving their names as Baby
John Doe or Baby Jane Doe. Organizers say those still in jail are
committed to remaining indefinitely.
   Among those arrested Wednesday were ministers and some in a
busload of people from Mississippi who arrived Wednesday morning.
Pickets said they were from North Carolina, South Carolina,
Virginia, Kansas and Florida as well as Georgia.
   Falwell presented Randall Terry, leader of the protest
organizing group Operation Rescue, with a check for $10,000 to help
pay legal expenses. Terry was arrested during a protest last week,
charged with being a party to a crime.
   Saying he came to Atlanta to ``sanction and endorse the new
concept in the pro-life movement of non-violent civil
disobedience,'' Falwell promised to use his television ministry to
rally support for Operation Rescue and other non-violent abortion
protests.
   ``In the next few months, this will be breaking out all over
America,'' said Falwell, a Baptist preacher from Lynchburg, Va.
``I'm challenging my preacher friends everywhere, who've stood with
us on every other issue, to stand up now in this one and endorse
non-violent civil disobedience.''
   A clinic spokeswoman said the protests had provided free
publicity, and that the normally competitive clinics have begun
referring patients to each other when necessary.
   ``These kind of tactics don't dissuade anybody from having an
abortion, it just makes them wait longer,'' said Ann Rose, director
of community education for Midtown Hospital, which performs
abortions and other services and has been the site of previous
demonstrations.
   ``We're busier than ever. It's good publicity for us in a lot of
ways. People now know where we are and they know a lot more about
abortions than they did before,'' she said. ``When they get
pregnant, they know who to call now. They don't have to go looking
through the Yellow Pages; they heard it on TV.''
</TEXT>
