<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDEmployee     08-10 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AID Employee,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aid Agency Official Plans to Plead Guilty to Embezzlement, Lawyer
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former employee of the Agency for
International Development intends to plead guilty to charges that
he embezzled $1.2 million from the government, his lawyer said
Wednesday.
   Defense attorney David Addis said former AID financial officer
William J. Burns would plead guilty to charges of embezzlement,
filing a false claim and tax evasion contained in a criminal
information filed in U.S. District Court.
   ``It's a tragedy for him and the whole family,'' Addis said.
``He will be doing everything he can to make an unfortuate
situation as right as he possibly can.''
   The defense lawyer declined to say whether Burns had agreed to
try to make restitution for the embezzled money. Addis said the
terms of the guilty plea would be outlined at a proceeding Thursday
before U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson.
   Justice Department prosecutor James Cole refused comment on the
case.
   The criminal information charged that Burns, 48, embezzled $1.2
million between 1982 and 1988 and evaded federal income taxes
totaling $475,685. He also is charged with filing false claim forms
in June to obtain more than $56,000.
   Burns was arrested last month. The charges resulted from a
six-month investigation that began after his lavish lifestyle
attracted the attention of AID officials.
   Late last year, AID officials conducting a routine security
check noticed that Burns, whose annual salary was $35,108, lived in
a neighborhood of $500,000 homes in Burtonsville, Md. His house was
worth $330,000, according to investigators.
   Burns spent $80,000 to landscape the property, according to
court testimony last month.
   At the time of his arrest, AID said Burns had purchased
``expensive cars, travel, exquisite home furnishings and other
embellishments'' normally beyond the reach of government officials
of his position.
   According to testimony before a federal magistrate last month,
Burns filed phony claims for travel expense money. Checks were
issued to a Vincent Kauffman, in whose name Burns had opened a bank
account.
   Burns was photographed while using an automatic teller card to
withdraw cash from the account, a government investigator testified.
   AID, an agency of the State Department, administers foreign aid
programs.
