<DOCNO> AP880810-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CondomStudy     08-10 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condom Study,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Halts AIDS Condom Study To Ponder Ethical Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clinical study on the effectiveness of
condom use for prevention of AIDS has been halted while government
officials search for a way to do the research without compromising
medical ethics, officials said Wednesday.
   Jeffrey Perlman, chief of contraceptive evaluation for the
National Institute of Child Health and Human Development, said a
panel studying the problem decided to cancel condom tests among a
selected homosexual population in Los Angeles because the research
might encourage some people in the study to not use condoms while
engaging in high-risk sex.
   Perlman said the study, as originally designed, would have an
``intervention'' group that would be given condoms and spermicide
and a ``control'' group that would not receive these items.
   The goal was to later compare the amount of AIDS infection
between the two groups.
   Perlman said a National Institutes of Health committee worried
that ``there might be too many people (in the control group) who
were getting infected because they were not using the condoms.
   ``That raised the ethical concern,'' he said. ``The concern was
not that the condoms were not going to work, but what would happen
to the people who were not going to use the condoms.''
   Perlman said that delaying the test does not mean the federal
government has changed its official policy that advises the use of
condoms when engaging in high-risk sex. High-risk sex would include
relations with homosexuals, with many partners or with partners who
are promiscuous, or with intervenous drug users. Perlman said the
government still recommends the use of condoms and spermicide.
   The clinical studies were to be conducted under the direction of
the University of California, Los Angeles, under a $2.6 million
contract. UCLA already has done laboratory quality tests on condoms
and was to supervise the clinical tests among gay men.
   Dr. Roger Detels, professor of public health at UCLA who was to
direct the study, said he agreed with the NIH decision.
   He said a classical intervention test requires that half of a
selected group use the device being tested, and that half not use
it.
   ``From other studies ... it's clear that if you engage in
high-risk sexual activities you are better off with condoms than
without,'' Detels said in a telephone interview. ``Based on that
fact, it is not ethical to have a control group in the usual sense
of a control group. ... The study has to take into consideration
that the control group has to be encouraged to use condoms as well
as your intervention group.''
   Perlman said the original study has been withdrawn and is now
being redesigned to adjust for the ethical concerns. He said the
NIH will be asking for bids on the new study and he hopes UCLA will
reapply.
   The new study, he said, probably will be a modified intervention
test in which both groups in the study will receive education on
the advisability of using condoms. But he said only half of the
group will receive condoms and spermicide from the administrators
of the research. The control group will be encouraged to use the
protection, but will have to purchase it commercially.
   Perlman said there also will be a retrospective study in which
people in high-risk groups will be interviewed to determine how
their sexual practices, including the use of condoms and
spermicidesm, may have affected their exposure to AIDS.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a
virus that is spread through semen, blood, blood products or from
birthing mother to child. The disease destroys the body's immune
system, causing the victim to contract and die from infection or
rare types of cancer. No one is known to have recovered from the
disease.
</TEXT>
