<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StMoritzFire     08-10 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-St Moritz Fire,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minor Fire Knocks Out Power at Manhattan Hotel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 guests at the St. Moritz Hotel were
packed off to other lodgings Wednesday after a smoky electrical
fire left the 33-story building without power.
   The 792-room hotel overlooking Central Park was evacuated
shortly after 11 a.m. when fire broke out in a cable leading from
an electrical transformer into the basement, authorities said.
   The fire, which was controlled in slightly more than an hour,
sent some smoke into the lower floors and cut off power to the St.
Moritz and four nearby buildings, according to Fire Department
spokesman Efrain Parrilla. The cause was not immediately determined.
   One woman was taken to a hospital for smoke inhalation. She was
listed in stable condition. It was unclear what the woman was doing
at the hotel.
   Another woman was trapped in an elevator on the 22nd floor for
about half an hour after the power outage, said Robert Mason, the
Fire Department's deputy borough commander for Manhattan. She was
not injured, Mason said.
   A spokesman for the hotel, executive vice president Frowen Feld,
said the St. Moritz was completely booked Wednesday but few guests
were in their rooms when the fire broke out.
   A loudspeaker system failed because there was no electricity, so
hotel workers knocked on room doors to evacuate people, Feld said.
   Feld said the St. Moritz is equipped with smoke alarms and
sprinklers, but none were activated because the fire and most of
the smoke was confined to a sub-basement.
   Dan Klores, a spokesman for St. Moritz owner Donald Trump, said
electricity was expected to be restored Wednesday night.
   In the meantime, Klores said, the St. Moritz offered its guests
lodging at the Plaza or Grand Hyatt hotels and about 500 people
agreed to be transferred. Several hundred others remained at the
St. Moritz, he said.
</TEXT>
