<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0681 08-10 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Defends Boston Harbor Record; Shrugs Off Shrinking Lead In
Polls</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 3 grafs after 12th graf bgng: ``Nobody could ... to
UPDATE with Bush campaign manager's statement. Picks up 13th graf
pvs bgng: Earlier this ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINTHROP, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, shrugging off a poll
showing his lead eroding in the presidential race, on Wednesday
defended his decision not to start cleaning up the Boston Harbor
during his first term as governor.
   The Democratic presidential nominee helped break ground to begin
a major phase of the multibillion-dollar cleanup of the harbor, now
considered the nation's filthiest, and spent most of his day at the
Statehouse tending to state business before heading out on a
five-state campaign trip Thursday.
   He dismissed a cautionary advisory from a watchdog panel that
said state revenues may not live up to projections in the new state
budget.
   ``This is Massachusetts, not Washington,'' Dukakis said. ``We're
going to balance our budget and pay our bills.''
   A new Gallup survey put Dukakis's support at 49 percent and
George Bush's at 42 percent in telephone interviews with 1,004
registered voters Aug. 5-7. Only two weeks ago, Dukakis was
sporting a 17-point margin over Bush, a 54-37 result in a Gallup
Poll. Each survey had a 3 percentage point margin of error.
   ``The race has always been tight,'' Dukakis said. ``This is
going to be a very tough, competitive 90 days.''
   Dukakis traditionally dismisses polls as meaningless, although
he did offer his interpretation of the latest survey.
   ``The only thing that these numbers tell you is that the
Democratic ticket is competitive in every region of the country and
in every state of the country,'' he said.
   To that end, Dukakis was readying for a campaign trip that will
take him to three key states in his effort to break the Republican
stronghold in Electoral College politics _ New York, New Jersey and
Florida. Dukakis also was to visit Connecticut and Virginia before
heading to Cape Cod Friday night to spend the weekend with his wife.
   He left the office at midmorning to attend the groundbreaking at
Deer Island in Winthrop, future site of a massive sewage treatment
plant included in the harbor cleanup plan. Construction beginning
there now is for a giant pier for barges carrying components of the
plant.
   After a speedboat ride across the harbor from Boston to
Winthrop, Dukakis defended his decision not to build new treatment
plants during his first term.
   ``Nobody could really tell us what to do to clean up this
place,'' Dukakis said. ``There were very respected people, experts
in the field, who disagreed.''
   Lee Atwater, George Bush's campaign manager, said in a
statement: ``If it takes the governor of Massachusetts 11 years to
clean up his own harbor, Americans must question his commitment to
the even larger environmental questions which face our nation.''
   Atwater said the delay ``will increase the average Boston water
bill from $300 to nearly $1,200 over the next eight years.''
   ``If I were from Massachusetts, I'd say the whole thing stinks
in more ways than one,'' Atwater said.
   Earlier this year Dukakis said that in hindsight it was a
mistake not to begin the cleanup during the first term. But he
seemed unwilling to go that far Wednesday, complaining of
``revisionist history about this project'' that blamed him for
delays. That criticism, Dukakis said, ``may or may not be connected
with the presidential campaign.''
   The harbor cleanup, with a current pricetag of $6 billion, is
the largest public works project in Massachusetts history. Dukakis,
as he did last week in California, boasted of the jobs it would
create.
   ``There are jobs and economic opportunity in environmental
quality,'' Dukakis said.''
   Dukakis decided against going forward with the plan in the
mid-70s because of disputes over whether secondary sewage treatment
was needed to clean up the harbor.
   His administration began the process of requesting a waiver to
Clean Water Act requirements for sewage treatment and the waiver
request was filed by then-Gov. Edward J. King shortly after Dukakis
left office in 1979.
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency ultimately rejected
the waiver request and a subsequent appeal and the state now is
under a federal court timetable to complete new primary and
secondary treatment plants and to stop dumping sludge into the
harbor. The project is scheduled to be completed by 1999.
   Dukakis, faced with the EPA decision and state and federal court
action, has made the harbor cleanup a priority since returning to
office in 1983.
</TEXT>
