<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pentagon-Levin     08-10 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon-Levin,410</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Levin Threatens Confirmation Boycott if FBI Report Withheld</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan said Wednesday he
would seek to block confirmation of all executive appointments
unless the White House releases an FBI report on a former official
targeted in a Pentagon procurement investigation.
   Levin, a Democrat and member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, sought the report on Melvyn Paisley, former assistant
secretary of the Navy, from the FBI and the White House.
   He said both refused to give him the report, which was a
background check the FBI conducted on Paisley during his 1981
confirmation hearings for the Navy post. Levin said the FBI may
have heard allegations of misconduct on Paisley's part, but the
information was not available to most committee members at the time
the panel considered the nomination.
   ``In light of the White House refusal, the integrity of the
confirmation process has been called into question,'' Levin said.
``Future confirmations are at risk until this particular issue is
satisfactorily resolved.''
   Levin's press secretary, Willie Blacklow, said the senator
intended the statement as a threat.
   The senator believes Paisley's confirmation may show an
underlying flaw in the confirmation process, Blacklow said. ``It
would only be fair that we hold up confirmations until we find out
where the flaw lies,'' he said.
   Senate tradition allows members to block consideration of a
nomination for reasons they do not have to disclose.
   Paisley resigned his Pentagon post in 1987 and became a
consultant to major defense contractors. Federal law enforcement
officials now are investigating allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former members of the
military, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that
could be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   ``It is important to the confirmation process ... that we
determine just what the FBI and the White House knew about Mr.
Paisley at the time of his Senate confirmation and the extent to
which that information was made available to the Senate,'' Levin
said.
   Blacklow said Levin intended his threat to apply to all
executive nominations sent to the Senate and believed other members
would support withholding action on confirmations until the report
was released.
   ``There is no reasonable justification for either the FBI or the
White House to withhold from the members, or at least the
leadership, of the ... Senate Armed Services Committee information
about ... Paisley that should have been available during his
confirmation,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
