<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachWaste     08-10 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Waste,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Relieved Beach Waste Is Limited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F. ALAN BOYCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines hit 26 miles of beaches this
week, not to fight an enemy but to collect trash: bags and bags of
medical and other waste dumped by Navy vessels and washed ashore.
   At the Atlantic Beach fire station, 25 giant trash bags were
emptied into steel and plastic containers. All 25 bags had been
filled since Sunday, including two filled Wednesday.
   Much of the medical debris, such as syringes and vials that may
contain blood, were taken by state officials for testing, said Dr.
Ron Levine, state health director. Charges may be filed if
regulations have been broken, he said.
   Levine said he was relieved to find that the mess appeared to be
limited.
   ``Today, they found virtually no medical refuse of any sort,''
he said. A second search involving 40 Marines in four-wheel-drive
vehicles started in heavy rain at low tide Wednesday afternoon.
   Levine said he was pleased with the military's response. ``They
have conceded their responsibilities,'' he said. ``They will clean
up the entire situation, no matter how long it takes, and dispose
of the waste properly.''
   It is not clear if North Carolina statutes outlaw such dumping,
Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan said at a news conference in Raleigh. He has
requested an opinion from the state attorney general on the law
covering such situations, proposing a law to prohibit dumping of
waste into the ocean if the attorney general rules it is not
covered by current law.
   Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, a Navy spokesman, said most of the debris
that washed up on the beaches is ``typical trash.'' Some had come
from the USS Newport and the USS Nassau, both based in Norfolk,
Va., he said.
   Navy regulations allow dumping of biodegradable garbage within
12 miles of shore, Lloyd said. Other trash may be dumped 25 miles
or more from shore, but medical refuse that may be contaminated or
connected with dangerous drugs is held for incineration in port, he
said.
   ``It's not a contamination problem and I can say it's definitely
not related to the beach problems in New York and New Jersey,''
Lloyd said.
   Levine said the main danger posed by the refuse is the chance
that someone might be cut by a piece of glass or broken syringe.
``And that chance is very, very low, considering the amount of
stuff they found,'' he said.
   Navy officials are checking the logs of the two ships to
determine how much waste might have been dumped, Lloyd said. He
said it was uncertain whether any regulations had been violated or
what penalty such a violation might incur.
   Marines were expected to remain on the beaches through Friday.
</TEXT>
