<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Radon     08-10 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bill To Fight Radon Pollution in Schools,
Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee on Wednesday approved a $46
million package calling for federal and state action to combat
cancer-causing radon pollution in houses and schools.
   The legislation, which cleared the Energy and Commerce Committee
for floor action by a voice vote, would set a national long-term
goal of making the air inside buildings as free of radon gas
concentrations as the air outside buildings.
   It would require the Environmental Protection Agency to update
and revise its ``Citizen's Guide to Radon'' to include information
about health risks posed by various indoor levels of the naturally
occuring gas.
   Currently, EPA sets 4 picocuries of radon per liter of air as
the level at which a homeowner should take steps to reduce levels
of radon, which is an odorless, radioactive gas produced by the
decay of uranium deposits.
   Health experts have warned, however, that this so-called action
level is too high because living in a house with a 4 picocurie
reading is believed to be the equivalent of smoking half a pack of
cigarettes a day.
   EPA has estimated that radon may be present in dangerous
concentrations in one of every eight single-family homes and that
it may be responsible for up to 20,000 lung cancer deaths annually.
   The legislation would mandate EPA to develop model construction
standards and techniques for controlling radon levels in new
buildings and to rate the values of various radon measuring devices
and radon-abatement contractors.
   The bill would provide federal money to states to survey radon
levels, run public information programs and control radon in
existing and new structures.
   EPA would be authorized to spend $1.5 million to study the
extent of radon problems in schools, propose ways to rid schools of
radon contamination and carry out remedial work at test schools in
high-risk areas.
   The bill is similar to legislation passed by the Senate in July
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForestArchaeology     08-10 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Archaeology,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Archaeologists Open Woods Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for Antigo, Wis., datelined story on AM-News Advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOLET NATIONAL FOREST, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists who dug
quietly in national forests for about 20 years worked in front of
campers this week in what officials said is a trend toward public
involvement.
   A team of seven archaeologists scraped dirt Wednesday in about
half a dozen carefully marked, shallow pits in the pine-covered
knolls of Boulder Lake campground in this northeastern Wisconsin
forest.
   The site about 60 miles northwest of Green Bay is believed to
have been a seasonal Indian settlement about 1,000 years ago.
   It was neither large nor rare from an archaeological standpoint,
said Mark Bruhy, archaeologist for the Nicolet and Chequamegon
National forests in Wisconsin. But its location provided an
opportunity to teach people about work that is normally done
quietly in remote areas, he said.
   ``To me, there's a little irony that a favorite prehistoric
campsite has become one of our biggest campgrounds today,'' said
Michael Beckes, regional archaeologist for the U.S. Forest
Service's eastern district.
   ``In the past, we've been concerned about the security of the
sites ... but we've come to the conclusion that this is public
archaeology,'' he said.
   The Forest Service has normally kept its archaeological
locations confidential to prevent digging by amateur treasure
hunters, which on federal land is a felony, Beckes said.
   But the Forest Service began experimenting with opening sites to
the public a few years ago, he said.
   In the eastern region, which includes 14 forests in 22 states
from Minnesota to New England, three excavations were open to the
public this summer, Beckes said.
   ``It's a national trend toward greater public involvement and
public awareness,'' he said.
   About 100 people have come each day this week to Nicolet to
watch the work at plots about 3-feet-by-5-feet and less than 5
inches deep and talk to the archaeologists.
   ``It's an opportunity to see something in action that you don't
normally see,'' said Steve Straavaldsen of Madison, who watched the
work with his wife and two children. ``You see the finished product
in (museum) display cases, but you don't normally see this.''
   For the archaeologists, it was an opportunity to recruit
volunteers.
   ``I've had 50 people who have come out here and asked if they
could help,'' Bruhy said.
   Since the 1960s, the Forest Service has had archaeologists to
identify, study and help preserve sites that might have historic
value, Beckes said.
   That, however, was about 30 years late for the Boulder Lake
site, which was inadvertently damaged when the 99-site campground
area was developed in the 1930s, Bruhy said. Grading work disturbed
the ground and placement of centuries-old bone and pottery
fragments as did years of erecting tents and building fire rings,
he said.
   Bruhy found bandages and bottletops mixed in with the small
chert and quartz arrowheads, pottery shards and burned bone refuse
left by American Indians living in the area around the year 800.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0214 </DOCNO>
