<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0600 08-10 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Bush, Dukakis to Drop Focus On Sleaze, One-Liners</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 5th graf bgng: Jackson, who ... to add that comments are
Jackson's first public criticism of Dukakis since Atlanta
convention.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson urged George Bush and Michael
Dukakis on Wednesday to drop their focus on one-liners and sleaze
charges and campaign for president on issues, ``not on dirt.''
   ``If it gets warped into sleaze,'' Jackson, the former
presidential candidate, told reporters, ``then there will be no
hope left for the people.... This campaign ought to focus on
direction and not on dirt ... on the live choices the people must
vote on in November.
   ``This campaign boils down to Bush attacking Dukakis with
one-liners every day, and Dukakis is becoming preoccupied with the
Bush-Noriega connection, the Bush-Iran-Contra connection, of
exchanging drugs for arms,'' Jackson said.
   ``I hope the campaign will stay at the level of what can be done
to begin to build affordable housing ... to fight a serious war on
drugs ... to enforce laws at the Justice Department to protect
people's vital interests,'' he said after a breakfast meeting with
Democratic members of the House.
   Jackson, who battled Dukakis all the way to the Democratic
convention, said the ticket of Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas is in the best interest of the country. But Jackson offered
his first public criticism of Dukakis since the two men reconciled
in Atlanta last month.
   He defended Dukakis' civil rights record even while suggesting
the Democratic nominee should have made more of a statement about
the struggle for racial equality during an appearance last month in
Philadelphia, Miss. It was near there that three young civil-rights
campaigners were murdered during the 1960s.
   Speaking in Philadelphia, Dukakis made only passing mention of
civil rights.
   ``His staff should afford even more emphasis to Philadelphia,
Miss., because of what it means to people,'' Jackson told a
questioner. ``After all, 25 years ago the great problem was around
the search'' for the three young people.
   ``Dukakis had met a number of black and white leaders even
before he made the address,'' Jackson recalled. ``It would have
been an opportune time to have spoken about'' the three youths.
``It would have been a profound message to the blacks and Jews, and
maybe even a wreath should have been laid.''
   That said, Jackson added, ``you must look at Dukakis in my
judgment in the cumulative. In the cumulative, his commitment to
social justice, his commitment to fairness is well-established....
His commitment to civil rights has been expressed rather clearly.''
   Jackson criticized as ``a rather token gesture'' President
Reagan's selection Tuesday of Lauro F. Cavazos, president of Texas
Tech University, to be secretary of education.
   Reagan was trying to send a signal to the Hispanic community on
the selection of one of their own, Jackson said. ``But after eight
years, the fact that he did not (earlier) find a Hispanic person to
be a Cabinet officer is a sure measure of their regard for that
segment of our population,'' he added.
   House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas hosted the breakfast for
Jackson.
   ``We had a very interesting discussion this morning,'' Wright
said. ``All our members were thrilled and strongly motivated'' by
Jackson, whom the speaker called ``one of the great thinkers of our
party, not afraid to say what needs to be said.''
   Wright said members and Jackson talked about legislation calling
for expedited voter registration, sanctions against South Africa
and underlying problems in the economy.
   Wright said the issue of aid to rebels in Nicaragua, a question
that divides Dukakis and Bentsen, was mentioned only peripherally.
   Jackson, talking to reporters, reiterated his position against
the Contras.
   ``The Contras have no base in Central America,'' he said.
``Let's pursue now a course of peace that will end the war.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
