<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Closes Embassy in Burma</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Senate resolution after 3rd graf, ``She
said''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has temporarily shut down
its embassy in Burma following anti-government demonstrations that
appear to have led to a ``substantial'' loss of life, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   All official American personnel and their dependents _ a total
of 154 people _ are safe at their homes, spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
said.
   She said the United States deplores the shooting of unarmed
demonstrators by Burmese security forces and she expressed concern
about reports that troops were seeking out groups of protesters and
firing on them.
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., introduced a resolution condemning the killings and mass
arrests by the Burmese army and supporting an end to one-party rule
in Burma.
   The measure, which will probably be voted on by the Senate later
this week, also urges President Reagan to raise the question of
human rights abuses with Burmese authorities.
   Mrs. Oakley was unable to say when the Rangoon embassy was
closed, but she said there is no indication that Americans or other
foreigners have been or might become targets of violence.
   Widespread anti-government demonstrations erupted last month
after the appointment as president of a military commander who had
been accused by students and others of ruthless suppression of
dissent.
   Mrs. Oakley said an official U.S. notice urging Americans to
exercise caution in Burma remains in effect. It calls on Americans
traveling to that Asian country to seek information from the State
Department or U.S. diplomatic posts to inquire about current
conditions there. There are normally about 80 American visitors to
Burma at any given time.
   The spokeswoman said the ``casualty numbers appear
substantial,'' citing Burmese government reports of 33 dead and 59
wounded. Some of the casualties apparently were members of the army
and security forces.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Oakley said, a U.S. Embassy officer driving to
work became trapped in a demonstration. After a bullet struck his
car, demonstrators loaded wounded protesters into the vehicle and
the officer was forced to drive them to a safe location. He left
the scene unharmed, she said.
</TEXT>
