<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Nicaragua     08-10 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Says 26 Nicaraguan Soldiers Desert, Nicaragua Denies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras said Wednesday that 26
Nicaraguan soldiers and 115 relatives crossed the border seeking
political asylum, but a Nicaraguan military source said Contra
rebels probably had kidnapped civilians.
   A statement by the armed forces public relations office said the
Nicaraguan soldiers, including officers, entered Honduras on Sunday
in the Pranza area of isolated Gracias a Dios province along the
Segovia River.
   ``A total of 26 deserters from Nicaragua's Popular Sandinista
Army ... and 115 members of their families, including women,
adolescents and small children entered national territory,'' the
statement said.
   It said the group came from northeastern Nicaragua but gave no
details or identities. According to the statement, the soldiers
brought all their combat gear, including Soviet-made AK-47 rifles,
a machine gun, anti-tank weapons, ammunition, rocket-propelled
grenades, flares and other military supplies.
   The Nicaraguan men and their families had gone to Nicaragua in
May under a repatriation and amnesty plan after living in Honduras
as refugees from Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, it said.
   Members of the group were quoted as saying the soldiers decided
to desert because they were inducted into the Sandinista army and
assigned to patrol the Honduran border.
   People who returned were told they would not be prosecuted or
investigated for connections with the Nicaraguan rebels, known as
Contras, if they promised to shun anti-government activity.
   Some deserters were quoted as saying they were mistreated and
forced to carry out ``harassment patrols'' along the border. No
details were given.
   Sources at the Nicaraguan Defense Ministry in Managua denied the
report.
   One called it ``totally false'' and added: ``What's more like it
is a kidnapping of an undetermined number of civilians by the
Contras in coordination with the Honduran army.''
   ``We have reports that forces of the 5th Infantry Battalion of
the Honduran army brought in vehicles on the morning of Aug. 8 to
carry away the kidnapped,'' the source said.
</TEXT>
