<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Pilot     08-10 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Pilot,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wounded Pilot Reaches Iraq After Six-Day Walk</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi pilot said he walked for six days
through enemy territory to reach his homeland after being shot down
in Iran and wounded.
   Kassem Hassan Hamid Dulayni, an air force captain, said he
escaped capture twice on the 25-mile trek through rugged Iranian
countryside. He spoke to Iraqi reporters and his account was
carried by the official Iraqi News Agency.
   Dulayni said he was ejected when his jet was hit, but did not
give the date or location.
   ``When I landed on the ground ... I didn't get caught, so I
decided to do the impossible and return to the homeland,'' he said.
The agency report said he suffered arm, leg and neck injuries.
   ``It was God who gave me patience and faith,'' Dulayni said, and
``it was a very good omen for me that I was accompanied on my
journey by a very strange bird, a bird with black and white
feathers.''
   The captain said he walked three miles the first day and climbed
a peak, from which he scanned the surrounding land, and found a
cave in which to sleep.
   In the morning, he set out with a compass toward the Himreen
Mountains on the border.
   ``I was really very thirsty, so I was forced to drink my own
urine, although I knew it was dangerous,'' he said. ``But it was
hot and I couldn't avoid it.''
   He felt feverish for much of the journey and dug holes in the
ground to cool off and sleep, Dulayni said.
   His green uniform blended with the grassy terrain, he said, and
he escaped detection by an Iranian patrol and a tank.
   ``The most difficult part was when I had to cross a small bridge
on a river near the border,'' he told the reporters.
   Dulayni waved a white flag at Iraqi border troops, who first
thought he was an Iranian but then realized he was an Iraqi and
``carried me on their shoulders.''
</TEXT>
