<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Murphy     08-10 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Murphy,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Murphy Winds Up Mideast Swing By Seeing Mubarak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Murphy, special U.S. envoy to the
Middle East, met with President Hosni Mubarak at the end of his
current tour Wednesday but there was no sign of progress in
reviving Arab-Israeli peace efforts.
   Before coming to Cairo on Tuesday, Murphy visited Lebanon,
Syria, Israel and Jordan to evaluate prospects for peace talks. He
leaves for home Thursday.
   The Murphy-Mubarak meeting took place the day after Murphy, an
assistant secretary of state, announced that Egypt had been unable
to arrange meeting for him in Cairo with Palestinian
representatives.
   Murphy gave no reason, but a well-connected Palestinian source
said the Americans objected to two of six proposed Palestinian
participants, apparently because they were closely linked to the
Palestine Liberation Organization. The source spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Mubarak received Murphy at the presidential residence, where the
media is barred. Murphy said later their talks covered regional
topics and the ``major issues (of) the coming months.''
   Murphy also met with Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and
Osama Baz, Mubarak's chief political adviser.
   ``I am now in a much better position going back and presenting
my report to President Reagan's Secretary (of State George P.)
Shultz,'' Murphy told reporters after his 90-minute meeting with
Baz on Wednesday.
   Baz said: ``We (the Egyptians) stressed the need to continue
moving in an attempt to hold the international conference next
spring, with a U.S. role in issues still in conflict such as
Palestinian representation, the preparations for the conference and
its legal basis.''
   His statement was the first reference to an attempt at
scheduling the conference for next spring.
   A peace plan presented by Shultz this year initially aimed for
an international conference last May, including all the parties
concerned under the auspices of the U.N. Security Council's five
permanent members: The United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain
and France.
   Shultz's plan remains on the table but there has been no
movement. The plan won qualified Egyptian support but Israel,
Jordan, Syria and the Palestinians balked.
   In a chat with reporters Tuesday, Mubarak refused to concur with
a questioner's suggestion that the Shultz plan was dead because of
last week's decision by King Hussein of Jordan to sever
administrative and legal links with the Israeli-occupied West Bank,
where about 850,000 Palestinians live.
   Mubarak said Hussein remains committed to the Middle East peace
process, a view Murphy also expressed before leaving Jordan for
Egypt.
</TEXT>
