<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Scelsi     08-10 0095</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Scelsi,0101</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giacinto Scelsi, Avant-Garde Composer, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer Giacinto Scelsi, known for avant-garde
choral and symphonic music, died of a stroke, officials at Gemelli
Hospital said Wednesday. He was 83.
   Hospital officials said he died Tuesday.
   Scelsi studied dodecaphonic music in Vienna and later moved to
France, where he spent much of his career. Dodecaphonic
compositions are built on 12-tone scale that includes half-tones
absent from traditional eight-note scales. Scelsi was known in
Europe for using spiritual themes and for Eastern influence in his
work.
   Funeral services were set for Thursday.
</TEXT>
