<HEAD>There Will Be Music At the GOP Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wage demands apparently won't stop the music
at the Republican National Convention.
   Entertainment before each session of a national political
convention traditionally is provided free. However, the Musicians
Mutual Protective Union, Local 174-496, ruled last month that its
members could not play unless paid union scale.
   Convention officials said Tuesday that local bands are now
expected to play at two sessions in the Louisiana Superdome, and
either non-union or outside bands at the other four.
   New Orleans bandleader Jimmy Maxwell said he will personally pay
the members of his orchestra so it can perform the first night.
   He said he was motivated both by ``a sense of civic spirit and
desire to help the city look good.''
   The other union band expected to appear is the New Leviathan
Oriental Fox-Trot Orchestra. Spokesman John Kraft said he expects a
corporate sponsor to pay the salaries so the band can play before
the final session.
   The band that performs during the convention sessions is paid.
It will be led by Manny Harmon, a California bandleader.
