<DOCNO> AP880810-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-B-1     08-10 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-B-1,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspin Says Faulty B1-B Bomber System May Not Be Worth Fixing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-1B bomber has such serious problems that
the Pentagon should consider halting spending on the new long-range
plane and using the money for other nuclear weapons, a key
congressman said Wednesday.
   ``Is it really worth it to spend any more money on the B-1B?''
said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee and one of the leading critics of the plane that
President Reagan resurrected in 1981.
   ``We have a very serious problem on our hands,'' Aspin said.
``If a case cannot be made for the B-1B, I do not see how we can
spend any more money on it.''
   Aspin's questions and criticisms were posed in a letter to
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and a speech Aspin planned to
deliver on the House floor Thursday.
   The Air Force continued to defend the long-range bomber,
although it admitted in a statement that it has been unable to fix
the problems with the B-1B's electronic countermeasures equipment,
which is the computer-driven system designed to keep the bomber
from being shot down by enemy planes or missiles.
   The B-1 originally was killed in 1977 by President Carter, but
Reagan reversed that decision four years later and approved the
purchase of 100 B-1s for a total of $27.3 billion. The chief
contractor is Rockwell International, which already has built all
100 planes.
   Reagan said the plane was needed to replace the aging B-52s in
the nation's long-range bomber arsenal until the ``stealth'' bomber
becomes available. That plane, named after its intended capability
to evade enemy radar, will be rolled out publicly for the first
time in November.
   The B-1B has run into a series of highly publicized problems,
which the Air Force first said were the types of problems
associated with any new plane.
   But fixing the electronic countermeasures problem is not so
easy, the service said.
   ``Here the solutions are not so well defined and the
uncertainties were much greater,'' its statement said.
   Two months ago, the statement said, ``the Air Force determined
that work was behind schedule and the solutions being pursued would
not provide for the full ECM system maturity the Air Force
desired.''
   ``There has been progress in the ECM system and it adds
significantly to the aircraft's capability. However, that progress
has not been satisfactory and the management of the ECM system has
not met our expectations. We are currently working out the most
appropriate action in the face of those facts.''
   Aspin asked Carlucci to tell Congress how much it will cost to
improve the B-1B, whether the additional money will provide
additional capability and how the plane's mission can be changed if
the money isn't spent.
   Unless the questions are answered, ``we may well be faced with
the prospect of parking the B-1B,'' Aspin said.
   He suggested that perhaps the money which would be spent on the
B-1B could be better used for other long-range atomic weapons, such
as land-based nuclear missiles.
   From now until the year 2004, the United States will spend a
projected total of $425 billion for strategic weapons and $242
billion of that total, or 57 percent, will go for bombers, he said.
   ``We need to ask ourselves if this money would not be better
spent on systems that do not have as many uncertainties as the B-1B
program,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1900EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-EmergencySpending     08-10 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Spending,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Passes $633 Million 1988 Supplemental Spending Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed legislation on Wednesday
granting $633 million to several federal programs running low on
money, a measure that was stalled for nearly a week because of an
election-year fight over aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   Lawmakers approved the legislation on a voice vote without
objection. The Senate now must work out a compromise bill with the
House, which passed a different version of the measure July 27.
   The measure was touted as a ``dire emergency'' spending bill
because it is supposed to provide money for programs that are in
danger of running out of funds, including programs in the
departments of Justice and Agriculture, the Coast Guard and the
Veterans Administration.
   Supplemental spending bills such as this one often become grab
bags for lawmakers eager to provide pet projects for their
constituents. But last fall's budget summit pact between President
Reagan and congressional leaders specified that the bill should be
limited to emergency spending.
   Most floor action on the bill was completed last Thursday.
   Final passage was delayed as Democrats and Republicans spent
days fruitlessly trying to work out a plan to aid the Contras.
   Just before final passage of the spending bill, the Senate
rejected a GOP amendment, 57-39, that could have provided the
Contras with $20 million in military aid beyond what the Democrats
prefer.
   The delay frustrated Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., who complained to reporters that administration
intransigence on the Contra aid package threw a roadblock in front
of the spending legislation.
   ``They shouldn't hold the supplemental hostage to Contra aid,''
Byrd said.
   The bill, which also allows the transfer of nearly $200 million
among the budgets of several government agencies, is for the 1988
fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
   It contains $530 million in new spending and transfers for the
Veterans Administration, which needs the money for increased
benefits and for a higher than expected caseload.
   The bill initially contained $297 million for veterans, but
lawmakers added $233 million more on a voice vote after Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the Veterans Affairs Committee,
argued that the extra spending was required by law.
   The legislation also would provide $75 million for the
Department of Justice, mostly to pay for the costs of last year's
uprisings by Cuban detainees in federal prisons in Atlanta and
Oakdale, La.; $60 million for the Coast Guard to cover the costs of
patrols; and $55 million to help the Agriculture Department pay for
drought programs.
   Programs paying benefits to people who lose their jobs because
of imports would get $49 million; the government's black lung
disease program would receive $43 million; and the FBI would get
$23 million to help its agents observe Soviet inspectors monitoring
American compliance with the new nuclear weapons treaty.
   The House bill contained only $189 million in new spending and
included no funds for veterans. It also has money for state
unemployment offices and for the costs of processing refugees from
the Soviet Union and other countries who want to come to the United
States. The Senate deleted those provisions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
