<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Sinking     08-10 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Sinking,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tourist Boat Sinks On Nile</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sudan-Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nile tourist boat carrying 100 people sank
in a storm Wednesday and 34 people were missing and feared dead,
the state-run Middle East News Agency said. A police official also
reported one person known dead.
   Rescue teams were searching for 17 missing Italian tourists and
17 Egyptian crew members, MENA said.
   An Aswan police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the body of an Egyptian crew member was recovered.
   ``An extremely violent storm hit suddenly, and in 30 seconds the
huge ship had gone to the bottom,'' tour director Paolo Fissora
told the Italian news agency ANSA in a telephone interview. ``I
don't remember it all too well. In just a few minutes I found
myself in the water.''
   The ship, The Nubia, was sailing 150 miles northward from Aswan
to Luxor. It capsized and sank in strong winds near Edfu, about 500
miles south of Cairo, the reports said.
   MENA said 34 Italian tourists and 27 Egyptian crew were saved.
   In Rome, a Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said 50 Italians were on
board and 17 were missing.
   ``Until the morning, when the light comes, we won't know
anything (about the missing),'' said the spokeswoman, who refused
to give her name.
   She said 33 Italians were rescued and were recovering in local
hospitals from minor injuries and shock.
   There was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy in
figures from the different accounts.
   Late Wednesday, ANSA quoted Fissora as saying the rescued
Italians had been released from the hospitals.
   Best Tours of Milan, which organized the trip, reserved a plane
to fly the survivors home, ANSA said.
   Many Nile River towns in southern Egypt are tourist sites, rich
with ancient monuments and remains, and ships regularly cruise
along the waterway.
</TEXT>
