<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Demonstration,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Chain Themselves To Fence To Protest Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty women chained themselves to a
fence Wednesday at the shuttered building where Congress used to
meet to protest the government of President Augusto Pinochet.
Twelve protesters were reported arrested.
   Police used water cannons to disperse about 50 youths who
blocked traffic and chanted slogans in support of the women,
witnesses said.
   The women, who identified themselves as relatives of political
prisoners, wrapped a long chain around their waists and padlocked
it to the Congress building in downtown Santiago. They held up
signs reading ``Open Chile's Jails. Freedom for Political
Prisoners.''
   Police arrived about five minutes later and used bolt cutters to
snap the chain. They took 12 women into custody, according to
lawyers for the Association of Political Prisoners' Relatives.
   No immediate word came on what charges the women faced but the
lawyers said the courts were asked to clarify their status.
   Congress was suspended when Pinochet took power in a 1973 coup.
According to human rights groups, more than 400 opponents of his
authoritarian government now are jailed. Most were accused of being
involved in leftist guerrilla activity.
