<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Love-SmittenDefector     08-10 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Love-Smitten Defector,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Polish Dancer Defected For Love</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish dancer who performed at an Israeli
folk festival defected hours before he was to leave the country,
apparently because he fell in love with an Israeli woman,
authorities said Wednesday.
   Police said they were searching for the Pole, who defected
Tuesday and was identified as Sigmund Irinauch, in his late 20s.
   Officials would not reveal the woman's name, but said she is a
Jerusalem folk dancer who met Irinauch when their troupes performed
in Canada two years ago.
   Yossi Gavrieli, who is director of the woman's troupe and knows
Irinauch, said the Polish dancer is Jewish.
   If that is true, he qualifies for automatic citizenship and need
not request political asylum. Israel's Law of Return grants
automatic citizenship to all Jews who want to live in Israel.
   ``It is very sensitive, so I don't want to say anything more,''
said Gavrieli, whose Hora Jerusalem group appeared with Irinauch's
Slovianki dance troupe in Canada. ``He is Jewish, but he has not
yet received asylum. Everyone is very concerned about him.''
   A Foreign Ministry official said Irinauch had not applied for
asylum but is allowed to remain in Israel until his visa expires.
   Dancers in the 46-member Polish troupe, which performed at the
festival in Haifa, searched for Irinauch on the Technion University
campus where they were housed, then left for home Tuesday via
Romania, the newspaper Yediot Ahronot reported.
   It said Irinauch left his roommates a letter saying: ``I didn't
want to tell you about it so I would not get you in trouble. I will
write to you from Israel. Give my warmest regards to all the
troupe.''
   Slovianki was in Israel for two weeks, one of three Eastern
European folk groups performing at the festival.
   Gavrieli described Irinauch as a star of the Polish troupe.
   ``He is a super professional, a maddening dancer,'' Gavrieli
said. ``He is also a very nice guy, unusually so, warm and lively.''
   A Polish-born dance teacher who acted a tour guide for the
Warsaw group said Irinauch appeared to know a lot about Israel but
gave no indication he was about to defect.
   ``When the group visited the Sea of Galilee, he could point out
the sites better than I,'' Tamar Goldner said. ``He knew every
place. He surprised the Israeli guides with his knowledge.''
   She added, however: ``He was the last person I thought would
defect. He was quiet and did not stand out in any way.''
</TEXT>
