<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DomesticSpending     08-10 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Domestic Spending,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 12:01 a.m. EDT Thursday, Time set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Government Employee Union Cites Spending Cuts During Reagan Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House and Congress have cut domestic
government programs by a total of $158.6 billion in terms of the
services delivered since President Reagan assumed office, according
to a report commissioned by a union of government workers.
   Federal aid to state and local governments over the past seven
years is 16.5 percent, or $123.6 billion, below what it would have
been had programs in place in 1981 been maintained at then-current
service levels, said the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
   Cumulative government payments to individuals such as college
aid, Social Security and food stamps over the seven years are $35
billion less or 2.3 percent below what they would have totaled had
the programs been maintained at 1981 levels, the AFSCME study said.
   The 1.1-million-member union said in the report prepared for
release Thursday that the decreases on domestic speding from 1981
levels amounts to a total of $642 over the seven years for every
man, woman and child in the country.
   The biggest percentage decreases, according to the AFSCME study
_ titled ``The Republican Record: A 7-Year Analysis of State Losses
of Federal Funding'' _ was state aid to provide free or
reduced-price milk to schoolchildren.
   Federal spending on the milk program has totaled $131 million
over the past seven years, or 86.2 percent below the $950 million
that would have been spent had the program been maintained at is
1981 funding level, the report said.
   However, federal aid to state and local governments for
providing supplemental food assistance to pregnant or
breast-feeding women and children under age 5 has increased over
the past seven years by a total of 39 percent.
   Cumulatative figures show federal spending on those programs for
pregnant mothers and infants totaled $10.1 billion, or about $2.8
billion above what it would have been had the program been only
maintained at the 1981 level.
   Other programs where federal aid to state and local government
has decreased are bilingual education, vocational and adult
education, job training, health services, welfare, juvenile
delinquency counseling, subsidized housing and special programs for
the elderly.
   Programs in which the cumulative federal aid over the seven
years has exceeded 1981 funding levels include drug education, Head
Start, libraries, science and math education, elderly nutrition,
child welfare services, Food Stamp administration and highways.
   ``Taken togehter, programs aiding children and families were cut
by almost $80 billion while programs aiding the elderly were cut by
almost $49 billion,'' the union said.
   The computations for the study were done by Fiscal Planning
Services Inc., a consultant that analyzes the federal budget for
state and local government
</TEXT>
</DOC>
