<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhiteSupremacist     08-10 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White Supremacist,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town GOP Chairman Quits After White Supremacist Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A town Republican chairman resigned
Wednesday under pressure from party leaders outraged over white
supremacist views he expressed in two newspaper articles.
   ``Because of the political pressure that's being put on me, it
would be better for the party if I resigned,'' Elmer A. Chipparoni
told The Associated Press.
   State GOP Chairman J. Michael Levesque and Gov. Edward D.
DiPrete were among Republicans calling for Chipparoni's resignation.
   ``The governor totally disagrees with his views and thinks there
is no room for them in the Republican Party,'' said DiPrete's
spokeswoman, Nanci Martin.
   Chipparoni, 68, was quoted in the Standard-Times of North
Kingstown and The Providence Journal as saying that ``white
America'' is committing ``genetic and cultural suicide'' by
allowing in too many blacks, Hispanics and Asians.
   He said that if non-whites ever became a substantial majority in
the United States, ``I wouldn't want to live here.''
   Asked if his views could be interpreted as being white
supremacist, Chipparoni replied, ``I'd hate to put it that way, but
I wouldn't disagree.''
   Chipparoni told The Associated Press in a brief telephone
interview that his views were taken out of context, but he did not
elaborate.
   He said he was giving up both his town party post and his seat
on the state party's central committee.
   A replacement will be chosen at the next meeting of the
35-member town committee, which has no black members, vice chairman
James S. Wilson said.
   In the newspaper stories, Chipparoni said U.S. immigration
policies should be changed to permit entry by fewer people from
Third World countries and more whites from Western Europe.
   ``I'm not saying white is the only way to go,'' said Chipparoni.
``But it does make a difference in the quality of a country.''
   He said that whites have a capability for achievement that ``is
in the genes.'' Chipparoni said his views are his own and not his
party's.
   ``He's not as bad as Hitler, but he'd make a good KKK member,''
said Harold F. Smith, president of the neighboring South Kingstown
Town Council.
   ``The term that upsets me most is ``white America,'' said Smith,
who is black and is the affirmative action officer at the
University of Rhode Island. ``You can't have a white American _
that's not America.''
</TEXT>
