<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-USMilitary     08-10 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-US Military,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German State Objects To U.S. Plans For Additional Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The central state of Hesse
strongly objected on Wednesday to U.S. military plans to increase
the number of aircraft stationed at a base outside Frankfurt.
   State government spokesman Alexander Gauland told a news
conference in Wiesbaden the increase in aircraft at the U.S. base
in Erbenheim would present increased danger to civilian aircraft in
the area.
   Erbenheim is less than 12{ miles west of Frankfurt Airport, the
busiest hub on the Continent.
   West Germany's Defense Ministry will have the final say, but has
not yet decided about the increase. The U.S. military wants to
boost the number of military aircraft stationed at Erbenheim from
53 to 181 by 1993.
   Gauland said a National Air Traffic Safety office report showed
an increase in military aircraft in the area would raise the danger
of disruption to departing or arriving civilian aircraft.
   He said increased air traffic also would raise noise levels and
increase air pollution.
   Congested air space has been a topic of controversy after a
series of U.S. and other military plane crashes in West Germany in
the past four months.
   The Defense Ministry on July 29 announced plans to cut by 2,000
hours the number of NATO military flight hours in West Germany.
</TEXT>
