<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare     08-10 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Controversial Child Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided House panel on Wednesday
approved the $2.5 billion Act for Better Child Care Services, but
like its Senate counterpart left some fundamental controversies
unresolved as the bill headed to the floors of both chambers.
   The 19-14 vote in the Education and Labor Committee on the
so-called ABC bill, the major Democratic initiative in the
politically hot child care arena, came during the third day of work
on the measure.
   Rep. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., was the only Republican to vote in
favor of the bill. Two Democrats, Pat Williams of Montana and Tim
Penny of Minnesota, voted no.
   As approved by the panel, the bill would authorize $2.5 billion
next year to go to states, with 75 percent of it to be used to help
low- and moderate-income families pay for child care either through
vouchers or direct payments to providers.
   While most of the money would go to the working poor, states
theoretically could give some help to households earning up to 115
percent of the state's median income _ over $40,000 in some places.
   Committee Democrats beat off two attempts to lower the income
eligibility level. But they accepted an amendment lowering the age
level of eligible children from 15 to 12.
   Republicans on the panel tried unsuccessfully to eliminate the
bill's requirement for a commission to develop minimum health,
safety and training standards that would be mandatory for those day
care homes and centers accepting the federal aid.
   As introduced, the ABC bill would have allowed federal funds to
church-based day care centers only if they did not promote religion
in any way. They would have had to comply with federal bans on
religious discrimination in hiring and admissions.
   But the version passed by the committee says only day-care slots
paid for by the federal government would have to be available to
all children regardless of religion. The ban on hiring
discrimination was dropped.
   Committee Chairman Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., said in a
statement after the vote Wednesday that he is still concerned about
the church-state and admissions issues.
   ``While I would prefer more precise language ensuring that
religious indoctrination will not occur, I support the current
language at this time in order to move the bill forward,'' he said.
``I want to make clear that as a general proposition, all persons
should have equal access to day care programs supported in whole or
in part by federal financial assistance.''
   The church-state issue and others debated by the committee were
discussed in subcommittee and are expected to arise again on the
House floor.
   Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa, sponsor of a rival child care bill
centered on tax credits and vouchers, contended the ABC bill
discriminates against families with a parent at home. He also
claimed it would narrow parental options and raise child care costs.
   Other Republican objections centered on the cost of the bill.
   Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., said there is no way in a
non-election year that the appropriations committees would allocate
more than $1 billion to a new program. And Rep. Dick Armey,
R-Texas, proposed authorizing up to $100 billion _ what he called
the true price tag for ``a fiscal time bomb'' _ rather than the
$2.5 billion called for in the bill.
   He was voted down.
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee last month
approved the ABC bill after lowering the income eligibility level
to 100 percent of median income, targeting money more pointedly
toward low-income families, including states in the standards
development process and giving them two years to comply with
caregiver training requirements.
   However, before the senators voted, ABC supporters agreed to sit
down with Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and try to work out compromises
on the cost of the bill and the federal standards issue. Meetings
have occurred but there have been no concrete results thus far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
