<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Georgia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident GOP and Robertson Backers Gain Control of Georgia
Delegation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5 grafs for grafs 2-4 pvs to update with committee
decision; Subs 10th graf pvs, Stuckey said, to update with comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of dissident Republicans and
supporters of television evangelist Pat Robertson on Wednesday
gained control of the Georgia delegation in a peacemaking deal that
left party regulars outraged and considering a boycott of the
national convention.
   Republican National Committee Chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr.
said afterward that despite the bitterness in the dispute, he hoped
it would not damage the party's prospects in Georgia in the fall
election.
   The national committee approved the deal worked out by the
Committee on Contests, but even after the decision, the two sides
in the dispute could not agree on exactly what it meant.
   Georgia GOP Chairman John Stuckey said it gave 28 of the state's
48 national convention delegates to the dissidents, while Brant
Frost IV, chairman of the dissident group, said the division was
26-22 in his faction's favor.
   The division of the delegation caps a bitter six-month fight for
control of the Georgia Republican Party. Vice President George Bush
won the state's March 8 primary but Robertson supporters overran
the party's machinery at caucuses and conventions that followed the
primary.
   National officials of both the Robertson and Bush campaigns
became directly involved in negotiations to settle the dispute, and
in the end, Stuckey said that their will prevailed.
   Asked if the Bush campaign had leaned on him to accept an
agreement, Stuckey replied, ``No, they fell on me.''
   Negotiators included Rich Bond, deputy manager of the Bush
campaign, and Mark Nuttle, who had been manager of the Robertson
campaign.
   ``We are striving to get our family together on this and aim our
fire at Michael Dukakis and not at each other,'' Bond said.
   However, Stuckey said he doubted that the settlement would
achieve party harmony in Georgia.
   ``If the object of this exercise is to buy peace, it will have
the same effect as Mr. (Neville) Chamberlain ... to buy peace,''
said Stuckey, referring to the former British prime minister's
attempt to negotiate peace with Nazi Germany before World War II.
   Stuckey, who was picked as a delegate, asked the RNC to throw
out the deal. After losing he said he would not appeal the decision
and would not attend the national convention next week. He refused
to rule out that he would resign as state party chairman.
   ``I'm going to go home tonight, get a good night's sleep, get up
tomorrow, saddle my horse and go riding with my daughter,'' Stuckey
said.
   The two sides argued their case earlier this week amid
allegations of death threats and complaints of strong-arm tactics.
   Republicans failed to hold their state convention last May
because a dispute over who could be seated as delegates disrupted
the proceedings to the point that Stuckey said he feared a riot
would break out.
   The dissidents continued the May convention and chose their own
delegates, while Stuckey and other party leaders met later to elect
delegates. Although all 48 Georgia delegates are obligated to vote
for Bush, the fight was over who will cast those votes.
</TEXT>
