<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Asia-Population 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asia-Population, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0672,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Population of Asia Population Reaches 3 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-3 DELETE population figure containing typo in 3rd
graf. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The designation ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The population of Asia topped 3 billion on
Wednesday, according to United Nations estimates.
   The report, issued by the U.N.'s Asian Forum of Parliamentarians
on Population and Development, estimated that the population hit
the 3 billion mark Wednesday at 12:47 a.m. Greenwich Mean Time
(8:47 p.m. EDT Tuesday).
   Seven babies are born every second in Asia, and the continent
accounts for about 60 percent of the global population, according
to the forum, which represents 19 Asian countries.
   ``The designation of a day marking the birth of the 3 billionth
baby in Asia is very symbolic,'' said Shigemi Kono, director of
Japan's National Institute of Population Problems. ``But I
personally think it is nonsense, because there is no way of
actually knowing when the 3 billionth baby was born.''
   Among Asian countries, India, Bangladesh and Pakistan face the
most serious population growth problems, Kono said.
   U.N. figures show that India, with 818 million people, has an
annual population growth rate of 2.08 percent. Pakistan, with a
population of 115 million, has a 3.45 percent growth rate and the
110 million population of Bangladesh is growing at a 2.67 percent
rate, according to the United Nations. By the year 2025, Asia will
have 4.5 billion inhabitants, according to the Tokyo-based Asian
Population and Development Association _ roughly equal to the
increase in the total world population from 1950 to 1980.
   The world population passed the 5 billion mark in July 1987,
according to the United Nations.
</TEXT>
