<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Journalist'sNotes 1stLd-Writethru a0776 08-10 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journalist's Notes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0776,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist No Longer Suspects FBI Stole His Notes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``Obviously, I ..., with four grafs to UPDATE
Dougherty's comment; picks up 5th graf: `Two weeks ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI obtained a journalist's confidential notes
indirectly through a CBS News colleague and not by breaking into
his home in Costa Rica, the reporter said.
   Tony Avirgan said he learned last weekend that the FBI got the
material indirectly through Carroll Dougherty of CBS.
   Avirgan said Dougherty told him he gave copies of the notes to
Jack Terrell, a former mercenary who was giving the FBI information
on alleged illegal activities connected with a private Contra aid
network, and that Terrell gave the FBI access to some of them.
   Avirgan told The Boston Globe that Dougherty's passing along of
the material was unauthorized and unethical, but Dougherty said he
thought he had Avirgan's permission to share it with Terrell.
   ``Obviously, I had no idea the material would end up in the
hands of the FBI,'' Dougherty said. He said he and Avirgan were
working together on a story in Costa Rica in 1985 when they shared
their notes.
   ``Both Tony and I were victimized by Jack Terrell, who was
working with the FBI and we had no knowledge of that,'' he said.
Dougherty said he had introduced Avirgan to Terrell at Avirgan's
request.
   ``I did so many things for Tony,'' Dougherty said. ``For him to
turn around and call me unethical after I created the whole
Terrell-Avirgan nexus at his request, I find shocking and a bit sad.
   ``I think they needed to find a scapegoat after the first story,
about the FBI breaking in. I don't think it was good enough for
them to just say the FBI didn't break in. They needed a scapegoat.
So I'm taking the hit.''
   Two weeks ago, the Globe said 39 pages of Avirgan's material
found in FBI files apparently were obtained during two breaks into
Avirgan's home in Costa Rica.
   Avirgan said at the time there was no other way the material,
including notes of interviews and private memos to his editor,
could have been acquired by the FBI.
   ``But after investigating this incident thoroughly, we now
realize that the FBI did not obtain the documents as a result of a
break-in or any other unethical or illegal action,'' Avirgan told
the Globe.
   ``We did suffer two break-ins, in 1985 and 1986, in which files
were rifled and, perhaps, photocopied,'' he said. ``We're still
looking for an explanation of those break-ins.''
   Dougherty's role was discovered last week when his handwriting
was found on one page of the material released by the FBI, the
Globe reported Wednesday.
   Avirgan said CBS News sent Dougherty to Costa Rica in 1985 to
help him and his journalist wife, Martha Honey, investigate an
assassination attempt against dissident Contra leader Eden Pastora.
   Avirgan said Dougherty told him last weekend that he provided
copies of Avirgan's notes to Terrell in exchange for Terrell's
material on a private Contra aid network.
   Terrell told the Globe the material was not part of a trade.
   John Mattes, a Florida lawyer, said that when Terrell was
approached by the FBI, ``I advised Terrell to cooperate fully with
the FBI and to give them everything he had. That's how CBS material
got into their files.''
   Greg Jones, a spokesman for the FBI, said Tuesday that FBI
Director William Sessions ``has maintained throughout that the
materials came to us from an individual who voluntarily provided
them to us. The FBI did not solicit the information nor did we know
how it was obtained.''
   Avirgan and Terrell said the FBI should have followed up on
material indicating illegal activities by members of the private
Contra aid network.
   ``We always said we wanted the FBI to carry on our investigation
and act on information we had uncovered,'' Avirgan said. ``We even
contacted the FBI in New York, and they showed no interest. Now we
know there is evidence of crimes sitting in their own files, and
still the FBI took no action.''
   The FBI's field office in Miami declined to release material on
the attempted assassination of Pastora because it is part of an
investigation, the Globe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
