<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0648 08-10 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radar Staff Saw Collision Coming But Couldn't Warn Pilots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADING throughout, with planes on radar up to collision. No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILBURN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radar operators watched two Royal Air
Force Tornado jet fighters heading for a collision but couldn't
warn them because the planes were keeping radio silence in
simulation of wartime conditions, the RAF said Wednesday night.
   Four airmen, three Britons and a West German trainee navigator,
were killed in the Tuesday night collision while on separate
flights in low-level night training exercises over the Cumbrian
hills of northwest England.
   The Defense Ministry launched an inquiry.
   Rescuers on Wednesday recovered the four bodies. Wreckage from
the $30 million, two-seater jets was scattered over a wide area
round the village of Milburn 240 miles from London.
   Hill rescue teams, guided by helicopters with powerful lights,
searched for the victims through the night in the remote, sparsely
populated area.
   Fifteen members of a local branch of the Round Table business
club were being shown around the RAF base at Spadeadam in Cumbria
as guests at the time of the collison. The base operates an
electronic warfare range against which the Tornado crews test their
skills.
   The business people told Wednesday how radar operators at the
base monitored the two planes up to the moment of collison without
being able to warn them of the impending disaster.
   George Beattie, one of the 15, said: ``There were two lines on
the screen representing the planes. Suddenly one disappeared and
the other changed to a dotted line which indicated a distress
signal. From that point on everyone knew something was amiss.
   ``There was a stunned silence. The only sound was the voice of a
controller at another base trying to make contact with the two
missing aircraft. Then there was nothing. There was a feeling of
shock and total disbelief among everyone.''
   The ministry identified the victims as three RAF flight
lieutenants, pilots Colin Oliver and John Watts and navigator
Anthony Cook, and West German Air Force Lt. Ulrich Sayer, 23, who
had been on retraining with the RAF since May.
   The RAF said in a statement that one plane had taken off from
the RAF base at Cottesmore in the English Midlands piloted by
Watts, an instructor at the Tornado Training Unit there. Sayer was
the navigator.
   The other plane, piloted by Oliver with Cook as navigator, had
taken off from the RAF base at Marham in eastern England
accompanied by a third Tornado.
   The crew of the third Tornado saw the collision but their craft
was not involved. Unable to help, they returned to Marham.
   ``A big red ball (of fire) came in the sky. I didn't know
whether it was the sun coming up,'' said witness Alan Knell,
landlord of the village pub, the Stag Inn.
   ``It was just a mass of bright red ... and then rockets and
flares went off and then there was another sort of explosion,''
Knell said in a radio interview.
   He said the planes narrowly missed the pub.
   The armed forces minister, Roger Freeman, said in a BBC radio
interview: ``Low-flying training, which is mostly at day with a
small proportion at night, is absolutely essential for our air
crews.
   ``They file a flight path with their station and it is logged
centrally but there would be no reason why a single aircraft would
know another military aircraft was in the vicinity.''
   The RAF said that in simulation of wartime conditions, the
low-flying Tornadoes traveling at more than 400 mph, maintain radio
silence and that the only way to avoid a collision in such
circumstances is visually to spot the other plane coming.
   The area is regularly used for such flights, in which the jets
skim a few hundred feet over hills and farm buildings, practicing
flying under radar search beams.
   The accident was the 10th involving RAF jets this year and
provoked demands from lawmakers that safety measures be tightened.
   The RAF has 220 Tornados, its main fighter, in service in
Britain and 165 on order.
   The Tornado was jointly developed and built by Britain, West
Germany and Italy and first came into service in 1979.
   Last May, two RAF crewmen were killed in the crash of a Tornado
in West Germany last May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
