<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Seals     08-10 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Seals,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seal Scientists Meet in London</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Dead Seals, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern European scientists opened a two-day
meeting Wednesday to try to shed light on what is killing seals by
the thousands along their coasts, a sponsor of the gathering said.
   The environmental group Greenpeace, which is sponsoring the
meeting with the University of London, said the scientists will try
to assess the number of deaths, their cause and remedies.
   About 7,000 diseased harbor seals have died since April, about
half the population in the North Sea waters of West Germany, the
Netherlands, Norway, Denmark and Sweden.
   Environmentalists blame the deaths on pollution, but scientists
say they are uncertain about what causes the viral infections that
are killing the animals.
   ``While governments argue over who is to blame for the current
crisis in the North and Baltic seas, the common seal in this area
faces extinction,'' said Greenpeace spokesman Andrew Booth.
   The 12 scientists at the meeting come from Britain, Denmark, the
Netherlands, West Germany, Norway and Sweden, said Greenpeace press
spokeswomen Sue Adams.
</TEXT>
