<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ecuador-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru   08-10 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Shultz, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0780,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Meets Ecuador's New President, Criticizes Anti-American
Mural</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 10th graf pvs, The mural ... describing
mural. Picks up 11th graf pvs, Shultz denied ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Ecuador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz met
Wednesday with Rodrigo Borja, Ecuador's new president, and
criticized an anti-American mural that hangs in the hall where the
country's Congress meets.
   Shultz was among numerous international dignitaries attending
the inauguration of Borja, a moderate leftist who has promised a
non-aligned foreign policy.
   The secretary was booed by part of a crowd of several hundred
people waiting outside the Congress building Wednesday evening
prior to the inauguration. Shultz, guarded by two policemen armed
with sub-machine guns, had no reaction.
   Shultz met with Borja before the inauguration and later said the
45-minute meeting was cordial and served to reaffirm ``the good
relations that exist between Ecuador and the United States.
   ``We discussed our joint interests in doing everything possible
about the narcotics problem, the terrorism problem. We discussed
economic issues, the debt problem,'' Shultz said.
   In an apparent reference to Borja's announced plans to impose
controls on Ecuador's free-market economy, Shultz said:
   ``I think that one of the things that is just crystal clear in
the world these days is that the method of running an economy by
central control, as advocated by the left, simply doesn't work.''
   Shultz, speaking to reporters after the meeting, also criticized
a huge mural hanging in the meeting hall of Congress.
   ``I have been told there is a mural and that the mural has two
messages in it. One is a message of insult to the United States and
the other is a message about the desirability, as the painter sees
it, of the programs of the far left,'' Shultz said.
   The mural, 30 yards long and 10 yards high, is painted on the
wall behind the speaker's podium. A skull with a Nazi helmet that
contains the letters ``CIA'' is depicted prominently in the mural.
   The highly impressionistic mural contains scenes of children
sleeping in the street, the struggles of landless peasants and many
scenes and symbols that reflect class struggle.
   Shultz denied local press reports that said U.S. officials had
considered boycotting Borja's inauguration ceremony because of the
mural.
   Shultz said the mural may have been designed to cause him not to
``go to this inauguration and join in celebrating democracy.
   ``I have come here to pay my respects to democracy and freedom
and the rule of law,'' Shultz said. ``This is an occasion when a
man is inaugurated as a result of an election in the democratic
tradition. So I am here to honor that.''
   The mural was painted by Ecuador's leading artist, Osvaldo
Guayasamin. It was unveiled last week and immediately sparked a
controversy because of the anti-American symbolism.
   The U.S. Embassy refused comment on local press reports that
said U.S. Ambassador Richard Holwill had complained to Borja, whose
Democratic Left Party controls Congress, and was told by Borja the
mural was solely the responsibility of the painter.
   Guayasamin, who says he is a leftist, defended the mural in an
interview in the Quito newspaper Hoy. He said his mural depicted
the political violence that is part of Ecuador's history and that
the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency is largely to blame for the
violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
