<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     08-10 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Youths At Prayer Vigil For Expelled Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers broke up a prayer vigil
Wednesday by about 500 Roman Catholics upset over the government's
expulsion of a Canadian priest, Haiti's Catholic radio station
reported.
   Troops fired into the air and arrested five people standing
guard outside the church where a courtyard vigil was being held,
Radio Soleil reported.
   The soldiers arrested the five at 2 a.m., then returned with a
judge at 11 a.m. to scatter hundreds of parishioners holding the
vigil at Gand Goave, about 30 miles west of Port-au-Prince, the
radio said.
   No reason was given for disrupting the vigil, nor was it
revealed where the five were taken. Two of them were young members
of the leftist United Democratic Confederation, Radio Soleil said.
   The Rev. Rene Poirier, the Canadian who ran the Grand Goave
church, was arrested and expelled last Friday.
   The Haitian Bishops Council said in a statement broadcast by
Radio Soleil Wednesday that it ``cannot accept the brutal manner in
which Father Rene Poirier was arrested in his presbytery in Grand
Goave.''
   A government communique accused Poirier of disturbing Haiti's
``social and political order'' after he refused to give a local
police official the names of parishioners who attended a recent
sermon, radio stations said.
   Poirier lived in Haiti for four years. He belonged to the
militant wing of the church that opposes the military government
and calls on the poor to organize politically.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy deposed President Leslie Manigat in June
and sent him into exile, ending four months of civilian rule.
Namphy previously headed a junta that ruled Haiti for two years
after former dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to France in
February 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
