<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DinoLandSigns     08-10 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DinoLand Signs,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Tries to Banish Dinosaur Land Signs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANBY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Selectmen have turned to the state for help
in banishing billboards featuring green dinosaurs in their long
battle with the owner of a dinosaur footprint museum.
   The board voted Monday to ask the Highway Department to survey
all road signs along state highways that run through the town to
see whether they are legal.
   ``What is this when they go surveying every sign in town?''
asked Carlton S. Nash, owner of Dinosaur Land, which has four
billboards along Routes 202 and 116. ``It's nothing but
harassment.''
   Owen P. Jacobsen, chairman of the board of selectmen, said the
request was prompted by the signs that advertise the quarry and
dinosaur museum, but said the town has not singled out Dinosaur
Land.
   ``It's not only enforcement of the law, but we're trying to make
our business district more presentable,'' Jacobsen said.
   Nash has owned the quarry for nearly a half-century and the
signs have stood almost that long. For 20 years or so, the signs
have also advertised what Nash calls his cancer research on
chickens.
   ``You'd be surprised the number of people who came into my shop
this weekend and said, `Mr. Nash, I'm surprised the town is getting
into such smallness about the signs,''' he said.
   Nash maintains his signs are legal even though they are 12 feet
too close to the road because a grandfather clause permits signs
that were erected before local laws were changed in 1974.
   But under a state law that supersedes town law, there is no
grandfather clause, Jacobsen said. State law requires billboards to
be 660 feet from a state highway, said Administrative Officer
Donald Kjelmyr.
</TEXT>
