<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Arias     08-10 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Arias,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Declares National Mourning for Deposed President Arias</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Arias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government decreed a day of
national mourning for Arnulfo Arias Madrid, the defiant former
president ousted three times by military coups who died in exile in
Miami on Wednesday.
   The Panamanian flag will be flown at half staff for eight days
starting Monday, the day of mourning. Arias Madrid's family said he
will be buried in Panama City on that day, when the former
president would have turned 87.
   Arias Madrid had been living in exile in Miami and died
Wednesday of a heart attack, Panamanian Consul Roberto Dominguez
said there.
   Opposition leaders in Panama, meanwhile, expressed sorrow over
the death.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, president of the Christian Democratic
Party, said the former president represented ``the figure of a
great rebel'' who had a social conscience and was ``concerned about
those who have less and for those who suffer more.'' He is not
related to Arias Madrid.
   Arias Calderon ran as a vice president on Arias Madrid's
presidential ticket in 1984 for the opposition Authenic Panamanian
Party.
   The government party's candidate narrowly won that election,
which the opposition labeled fraudulent. Many also felt the
military stole a 1964 electoral victory from Arias Madrid.
   Arias Madrid was president of Panama in 1940-41, 1949-51 and for
11 days in 1968. Each time, he was ousted by the military.
   However, he continued to speak out against the Defense Forces,
in 1986 charging them with killing opposition leader Hugo
Spadafora, who had accused the government of involvement with drugs.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's de facto ruler as head of
the 15,000-member Defense Forces, was indicted last February in
Florida on drug trafficking charges. He denies the accusations.
   Guillermo Endara, undrsecretary of the Panamanian Authentic
Party, said Arias Madrid was ``the indisputable leader'' of Panama
for the past 57 years.
   Carlos Ivan Zuniga, president of the Popular Action Party, said,
``There is no doubt that his death is going to constitute a
tremendous uncertainty, leave a vacuum. A very interesting era in
national life ... has closed.''
   The last coup against Arias Madrid marked the beginning of the
military's domination of Panama's government, first under Gen. Omar
Torrijos, who died in a 1981 plane crash, and then by Noriega.
   Arias Madrid feared returning to Panama because of his
opposition to Noriega, Dominguez said.
</TEXT>
