<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PrimariesRdp     08-10 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ben Jones Disavows `Liberal' Tag, Democrats Plot To Keep Price
Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former actor Ben Jones, chosen by Georgia Democratic voters for
a rematch against a Republican congressman, said Wednesday his
challenge is to avoid being tagged a liberal. In southern Illinois,
a Democrat who retained a vacant House seat for his party turned to
campaigning to win it again in November.
   Jones, 47, who played a mechanic on the ``Dukes of Hazzard''
television series, said he will ``take the high road'' in the fall
campaign after defeating two rivals in Tuesday's primary for the
right to oppose Republican Rep. Pat Swindall.
   ``They're going to use the `L' word as much as possible to keep
from engaging their brains,'' said Jones, who won 47 percent of the
vote in a 1986 contest with the conservative congressman.
   In Illinois, Democrat Jerry Costello won a special election for
the 4{ months left in the U.S. House term of Rep. Mel Price, who
died in April at age 83. Costello, chairman of the St. Clair County
Board, is scheduled to be sworn in Thursday in Washington.
   Republican Robert Gaffner, a community college administrator,
lost by a 51.4 to 48.6 percent margin Tuesday, but can look forward
to a rematch with Costello in November. He said he was disappointed
but not discouraged, maintaining the closeness of the contest
demonstrates Costello's vulnerability.
   In Georgia's 4th Congressional District, Jones won 62 percent of
the vote against lawyer Nick Moraitakis' 21 percent and theater
executive John Stembler's 17 percent to capture the Democratic
nomination without a runoff.
   Swindall, who was unopposed for the GOP nomination, is widely
believed to be facing an uphill re-election battle following his
admission that he considered accepting laundered drug money to
finance the expensive home he built.
   The congressman said Tuesday night he thought the district's
voters would put questions over the loan ``in perspective'' and
decide the race on the basis of political philosophy. Jones, he
said, ``is an acknowledged liberal ... Pat Swindall is a
conservative.''
   Georgia Democratic voters also nominated David Worley, a
29-year-old lawyer, to challenge Republican Rep. Newt Gingrich.
Gingrich challenged Worley Tuesday night to an extensive series of
debates, saying he intended to show voters that organized labor and
the Democratic establishment in Washington were helping finance
Worley in retaliation for Gingrich's attack on the financial
dealings of U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright.
   Eight of Georgia's 10 congressmen won renomination without
opposition in the primary election. Both of those opposed were
victorious.
   Colorado had primaries in six congressional districts, but
almost no tight races, so voter turnout _ possibly as low as 10
percent of registered voters _ was ``atrocious,'' said state
Democratic Party Chairman Buie Seawell.
   Exact figures were unavailable, but calling the turnout poor
would be ``sort of the understatement of the decade,'' said
Secretary of State Natalie Meyer.
   In the contest that generated the most interest, Republicans in
a suburban district that includes Boulder County chose state Rep.
David Bath over former Secretary of State Mary Estill Buchanan, who
lost to Gary Hart in the 1980 Senate race.
</TEXT>
