<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AriasProfile     08-10 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arias Profile,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arias, Ousted by Military, Became Panama's Symbol of Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Arias and AM-Panama-Arias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This country's powerful military
three times overthrew former President Arnulfo Arias Madrid, but it
unwittingly turned him into a national symbol of democratic
aspirations.
   The 86-year-old former president, who died Wednesday in exile in
Miami, ran for president again just four years ago. He was the top
contender in the country's first presidential election in 16 years.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, the president of the Christian
Democratic Party, said Wednesday, ``We feel a little orphaned by
his death.''
   ``Arias became the symbol of our nation's claim to have a
civilian government, in a democracy,'' he said. The two men are not
related.
   Nicolas Ardito Barletta won the 1984 presidential elections,
defeating Arias by a margin of 1,713 votes out of about 640,000
ballots cast. The count took place behing closed doors.
   When the official tally was released, Arias' supporters cried
fraud and foreign diplomats also questioned the results.
Demonstrators clashed with police and dozens were injured.
   Arias spent most of the last 12 months in Miami, while Panama
was undergoing a severe political and economic crisis.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the country's de facto ruler as
head of the Defense Forces, was indicted last February by a grand
jury in Florida and the United States has been applying strong
diplomatic and economic pressure to force him to resign and leave
the country.
   Persistent rumors over the past six months that Arias would soon
return to Panama appeared to invigorate his Authentic Panamanian
Party. However, younger people had taken over the party, and he
played no active role in the opposition's efforts to force
Noriega's resignation.
   A close aide of Arias said before the 1984 election that he had
tried to convince the Harvard-educated physician not to run for
president because of his age.
   ``I couldn't convince him because somebody from the (National)
Guard (now called the Defense Forces) had called him in December to
say that he wasn't acceptable as a candidate. Nobody can tell the
doctor what to do, and after that call there was no stopping him,''
said the aide, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The winner, Ardito Barletta, was the military's choice, but he
held office only 11 months before he was pressured to resign.
   His vice president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, was moved into the top
office. He served from September 1985 until last February, when he
tried to fire Noriega and the general had him replaced, too.
   Born Aug. 15, 1901, in Penonomee, a small town about 90 miles
west of Panama City, Arias had been active in Panamanian politics
since 1931.
   He frequently tangled with the military, which overthrew him in
1941, 1951 and 1968. Of his three four-year terms, the military let
him stay in office only a total 2{ years. In 1968, he lasted only
11 days.
   In addition to claiming victory in the 1984 election, his
supporters said he won in 1964.
   His brief terms in office were characterized by nationalistic
fervor aimed mainly at the powerful U.S. presence here. In later
years, he toned down the rhetoric and said he was a friend of the
United States.
   A staunch anti-communist, Arias said in an interview before the
1984 election that he had not sought the support of the Reagan
administration because, ``I don't want to seem like an instrument
of American initiatives.''
   He said Central American communists ``aren't interested in the
wars in Guatemala, Nicaragua or El Salvador but in obtaining
control of the Panama Canal.''
   Two of his major accomplishments while in office were to give
women the vote in 1940 and create a social security system.
   His reaction to his overthrow in 1941 became legend.
   ``You, fellow party members, fulfilled your obligation. I, as
president, fulfilled mine. These are traitors,'' he said of the
military as he left the presidential offices. ``We will return.''
   His periods of exile, including four years after the 1941
overthrow, turned the words ``We will return'' into a slogan.
   Arias was to be buried in Panama City on Monday. It would have
been his 87th birthday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
