<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiberaceTrial     08-10 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Trial,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Accused of Introducing ``Sleaze'' Factor During Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys in a lawsuit over Liberace's
will accused each other of introducing sleaze into the trial
Wednesday as they delved into the private lives of the entertainer
and his associates.
   The exchange came as former Liberace valet and houseman George
Llinares of Palm Springs, Calif., recounted his years of service
with Liberace, who died Feb. 4, 1987, of complications of AIDS.
   Llinares at one point testified that housekeeper Dorothy McMahon
had a ``very close'' relationship with Cary James, Liberace's
companion the last six years of his life.
   James and Ms. McMahon are two of five plaintiffs in a lawsuit
that seeks to have Beverly Hills, Calif., lawyer Joel Strote
removed as executor of Liberace's vast estate.
   Harold Gewerter, the attorney for the five, objected frequently
as defense lawyer John O'Reilly questioned Llinares about the
relationship between James, Ms. McMahon and Liberace.
   Llinares said Ms. McMahon used to ``cover up'' for James and
Scott Thorson, Liberace's former companion.
   ``When they went out, she would tell him they had gone shopping
or something,'' he said. ``I reminded her she should remember who
she worked for.''
   Llinares said Ms. McMahon and James were ``very close'' and
would ``lock themselves in a room for an hour.''
   Gewerter objected vigorously, saying the questioning was getting
``downright sleazy.''
   O'Reilly responded that he was simply following up on issues
raised when the plaintiffs presented their case earlier this summer.
   James and Ms. McMahon were visibly upset by the questioning and
the housekeeper walked down the hall sobbing loudly during a
morning break.
   Strote also appeared agitated during the session and left the
courtroom before the break.
   Angie Liberace, the sister of the late entertainer and one of
the plaintiffs, bowed her head and sobbed when Llinares claimed
that Liberace didn't want her around his house.
   At one point, state District Judge Michael Wendell lectured the
attorneys, saying, ``I'm interested in one thing _ should Joel
Strote be removed as executor. I'm not interested in personalities,
not interested in morals. We're getting far afield.''
   Under cross-examination, Llinares admitted he had written a book
about Liberace and was trying to find a publisher. He said he
worked for Liberace twice, from 1975 to 1977, and 1979 to 1984.
   Llinares said he quit Dec. 29, 1984 in a huff because he wanted
to go to France to see his family. He said the parting was bitter
and he told Liberace ``God will make you pay for that.''
   Llinares testified that Liberace referred to Strote as ``Mr.
Fixit'' because of his legal expertise and often said ``Thank God
for Joel Strote.''
   Plaintiffs in the case contend Liberace was too ill to
understand a new will and trust he signed 13 days before he died,
making Strote executor of his estate and head of the Liberace
Foundation for the Performing Arts.
   Those filing the suit contend that Strote has taken excessive
fees as head of the foundation. But testimony Tuesday indicated
that the assets of the Liberace estate had climbed from $14 million
to $18 million under his guidance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
