<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique-Rebels     08-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique-Rebels,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Town; 21 Reported Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas fighting the Marxist
government killed 21 people and injured 22 in a pre-dawn attack on
the town of Maragra, 45 miles north of Maputo, the national news
agency AIM reported Wednesday.
   It said about 300 guerrillas of the Mozambique National
Resistance attacked the town early Tuesday, burning huts, stealing
goods and shooting residents.
   The guerrillas have waged a hit-and-run insurgency against the
government since 1977, two years after Mozambique gained
independence from Portugal.
   Western diplomats and relief workers have supported government
allegations that the guerrillas are responsible for numerous
massacres and other atrocities.
   Mozambican rebels meanwhile claimed Wednesday to have killed 16
troops and six Tanzanian soldiers in attacks on five government
posts Monday in northeastern Cabo Delgado province.
   The Mozambique National Resistance said in a statement
distributed in Lisbon, Portugal, that it also destroyed in central
Manica province part of an important oil pipeline that runs from
Mozambique to neighboring Zimbabwe.
   It claimed it captured two military officers.
   No independent confirmation of the group's claim emerged.
   Troops from neighboring Tanzania, Zimbabwe and Malawi fight the
rebels in Mozambique, mainly to protect transportation and oil
routes.
   Augusto Pereira, 48, of Lisbon, said Wednesday in Maputo, the
Mozambican capital, that he escaped from a rebel camp after being
kidnapped from his wood business in Manica province June 29, the
LUSA news agency of Portugal reported.
   LUSA quoted Pereira as saying the rebels forced him to march
about 250 miles to a camp near the border with Zimbabwe.
</TEXT>
