<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Hostages     08-10 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Hostages,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leader Holds Secret Hostage Talks, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian official met Archbishop of Canterbury
Robert Runcie in secret talks in London Wednesday to discuss
British hostages in Lebanon, the British domestic news agency Press
Association reported.
   The reported 75-minute meeting followed other recent contacts
between church officials and the Iranian government and signs of
improving relations between Britain and Iran. The 18 foreign
hostages in Lebanon are believed held by pro-Iranian groups.
   Press Association said Church of England officials arranged a
meeting with Mohamed Reza Said Mohamedi, an Iranian Foreign
Ministry official based in Tehran, at Lambeth Palace, Runcie's
official London residence. Runcie is spiritual leader of the Church
of England.
   The agency said no details about the meeting were disclosed, but
that it was believed the discussions included the fate of Runcie's
special envoy, Terry Waite; television journalist John McCarthy and
teacher Brian Keenan.
   Waite vanished in Beirut on Jan. 20, 1987, while seeking the
release of American and other foreign hostages. No group claimed
responsibility for his disappearance.
   McCarthy was kidnapped on April 17, 1986.
   Keenan has been missing since April 11, 1986. Keenan from
Belfast, Northern Ireland, holds dual British and Irish
nationality, and the Irish government is also seeks his release.
   The longest-held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for the Associated Press, who was taken captive March
16, 1985.
   John Lyttle, a senior adviser to Runcie, who was in Tehran in
June for talks with Iranian religious and government officials,
also attended Wednesday's meeting, the agency said. It said Lyttle
confirmed Mohamedi met with Runcie Wednesday but said Lyttle
declined to give details.
   On Monday, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
announced it will send a British diplomat to Iran this week for the
first time in a year.
</TEXT>
