<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChavezFast     08-10 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez Fast,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders of 2 Million-Member Unions Back Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asoociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Farm Workers leader Cesar Chavez
persisted Wednesday for a 25th day of a water-only fast, the same
length of time he went without food in 1968 to gain recognition of
his union.
   The 61-year-old Chavez remained bedridden but in stable
condition Wednesday as he picked up support from two officials of
other unions representing nearly 3 million workers.
   Chavez says he is fasting to promote a consumer boycott of
California table grapes, whose growers refuse to sign union
contracts and use pesticides he says endanger field workers and
their families.
   ``Cesar has raised the ante. He has made us feel ashamed,'' said
Gerald McEntee, president of the 1 million-member American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees. He promised to
urge members to hit the streets and support the four-year-old
boycott.
   ``Cesar Chavez in the minds of many of us represents the soul of
the American labor movement,'' said Jack Henning,
secretary-treasurer of the 1.9-million member California Labor
Federation.
   Henning acknowleged the boycott hasn't taken hold even in
California but said the public is beginning to realize the
sacrifice by Chavez and his message.
   ``The implementation of a boycott in the long term is not an
easy task. We have a renewal here through Cesar's fast,'' said
Henning.
   Hollywood stars and children of the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy
have traveled to Delano in recent weeks to publicize the boycott.
But these visits and the ensuing publicity have had a negligible
effect on California table grape sales, according to state
regulators and a California Grocers Association official.
</TEXT>
