<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-USBases     08-10 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US Bases,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Will Leave Vietnam If U.S. Quits Philippines, Official
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet official Fjodor Ivanovich
Potapenkno was quoted as saying Thursday that without the shadow of
a doubt, Soviet forces would leave Vietnam if the United States
withdrew from the Philippines.
   Potapenkno, who recently returned to the Soviet Union after
being ambassador in Malaysia for four years, spoke in an interview
published in the editorial page of the daily New Straits Times.
   ``The Soviet Union is reducing its military activity and
presence in the (Southeast Asia) region,'' he was quoted as saying.
``There is no shadow of doubt that if United States forces leave
the Philippines _ for the United States _ Soviet forces will also
leave Vietnam.''
   The United States maintains two military bases and four minor
installations in the Philippines and the Soviets have close ties to
Vietnam.
</TEXT>
