<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     08-10 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claim Iraq Using Poison Gas Against Kurdish Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi troops are using poison gas in an
offensive against Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in
northeastern Iraq, Kurdish and Iranian sources said Tuesday.
   They said about 30,000 Iraqi soldiers are engaged in the
assaults that began July 30 to dislodge the Kurds from their
mountain strongholds.
   Iran, at war with Iraq for nearly eight years, has supported the
Kurdish rebels in Iraq. But Iran and Iraq agreed Monday to a
U.N.-mediated cease-fire that is to go into effect Aug. 20.
   Massoud Barzani, leader of the insurgent Kurdish Democratic
Party,, issued a statement Tuesday saying Iraqi troops using
chemical weapons and with air and artillery support advanced into
``liberated territory'' controlled by the rebels.
   The statement, received in Nicosia from the Kurdish Democratic
Party office in Greece, appealed to the United Nations to stop the
Iraqis ``particularly now that the Kurdish people are the target of
gas attacks and face planned extermination.''
   It said 63 civilians were seriously hurt in poison gas attacks
on three Kudish villages near the Turkish border. The statement
also claimed 1,000 Iraqi soldiers were killed, wounded or captured
in the offensive.
   A report by Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said Kurdish refugees were fleeing into Turkey and Iran.
It called on the Turkish and Iranian Red Crescent societies and the
International Red Cross to help them.
   The cease-fire accord calls for Iranian and Iraqi forces to
return to internationally recognized borders. The Kurdish rebels
said Iraq launched the new operations to drive Kurds out of the
border areas before U.N. peackeepers arrive to oversee the truce.
   Some 20 million Kurds live in sections of Turkey, Iran, Iraq,
the Soviet Union and Syria. There are an estimated 3.5 million
Iraqi Kurds, and the rebels have been fighting for autonomy for
more than 50 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
