<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 12,0778</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Aug. 12, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Graham Sees More Spiritual Notes In Political Conventions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   God usually gets some polite nods at American
political conventions, but an old-timer of the candidate-crowning
powwows says he detects a stronger religious element this time
around.
   ``There was more of a spiritual tone at the Democratic
Convention and I think we'll also see it at the Republical
Convention,'' says evangelist Billy Graham, a convention regular
since midcentury.
   As he has done at every Democratic and Republican national
convention over the last 36 years, Graham will be offering prayers
at next week's Republican affair as he did for the Democrats in
July.
   ``I never go to one without the other,'' he said in telephone
interview from Buffalo, N.Y., where he wound up a heavily attended
crusade last Sunday in that mostly Roman Catholic city.
   ``I always stay neutral politically, and I'm going to be neutral
this time,'' he said. I won't tell who I'm voting for, and I'm not
endorsing anybody. That's the reason I go to both conventions.''
   Graham, 69, a personal friend and unofficial chaplain to the
country's seven presidents since 1952, attributed the increased
spiritual note at the Democratic Convention to the influence of
black delegates.
   ``The black people made a great impression on white delegates as
dignified, highly educated and they love the Lord,'' he said.
``They came out of the churches. These black people made a
spiritual impact.''
   He said that unlike some past conventions, when delegates would
``walk around and talk'' during prayers, the crowd this time would
all stand ``and it would be so quiet you could hear a pin drop.''
   At one point, he said he watched a network television reporter
trying to question the Rev. Jesse Jackson on the floor during the
benediction, but Jackson deflected the reporter's questions,
saying, ``We're praying now.''
   Jackson bowed his head while African Methodist Episcopal Bishop
Frederick C. James led the benediction, refusing to continue the
interview until the prayer was finished, Graham said.
   While Jackson, the second-running Democratic candidate, gave a
rousing address in Gospel-preaching style to the Democrats, another
also-ran minister, Pat Robertson, was to address the Republicans.
   ``I'm happily surprised for clergymen to be addressing both
conventions,'' Graham said. ``It's healthy for there to be more
recognition of spiritual life whenever people gather.''
   At the Republican Convention, Graham is to lead a prayer Monday
night when President Reagan finishes his address, and will sit with
the George Bush family on the closing night when he gives his
acceptance speech.
   ``They're both long-time friends,'' Graham said, noting that he
had spent a dozen nights at the White House in Reagan's presidency,
and regularly spent part of his vacation in Maine with Bush.
   Besides leading prayers, Graham said he'd also be going to
various receptions at the convention, just as he did at the
Democratic Convention, including a luncheon for governors where he
sat with Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis.
   ``He was very warm and friendly,'' Graham said.
   At one reception given by veteran Democratic party leader Robert
Strauss, Graham said that as he was leaving Strauss followed him
into the hall and said, ``When you get ready to go to heaven, let
me know. I want to go with you.''
   Graham said that while avoiding partisan politics, he tries to
do as much for one party as the other, and he urges Christians to
become involved in the political process regardless of which
candidate or party they support.
   Of his just ended crusade in Buffalo, 70 percent Roman
Catholics, Graham said he had received ``wonderful support'' from
Catholics, as well as mainline Protestant bodies and black churches.
   ``People really came out in numbers,'' he said. ``More came
forward to receive Christ per capita than I've seen anywhere in
America.''
   He said the Buffalo crusade was part of a New York regional
drive, with campaigns over the next six months in Rochester,
Hamilton, Ontario; Syracuse, Long Island and Albany.
   Before his Buffalo crusade, Graham had been abroad for 16 weeks,
first with his wife, Ruth, in China where she was born, daughter of
a missionary doctor, and then in the Soviet Union for celebrations
of the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity in Russia.
   ``To see television filled with religion for 10 days stunned the
Soviet people,'' he said. ``It was the first time many of them
realized their roots were in Christianity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 12.</NOTE>
