<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Aug. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dough Boys _ Inmate Bakers at State Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buried in the prison landscape of concrete cell
blocks, watch towers and barbed wire fences is a building warmed by
the smell of a staple of life _ freshly baked bread.
   Welcome to the bakery at the state's Richard J. Donovan
Correctional Facility, where 50 inmates produce 1,500 loaves a day
of white and wheat bread to help feed the 2,821 prisoners.
   ``Don't tell them (prison officials) this, but I'd work for
free, just to pass the time,'' said inmate Mike Warner, who is
making 25 cents an hour as a lead ``dough man.'' He helps oversee
the initial creative stage, the mixing of the dough to make the
bread.
   ``I wanted to come in here and benefit myself more,'' said John
Briseno of Bakersfield, who works as a dough mixer. ``I can learn
more about being a baker so I can look for a baker's job when I get
out.''
   Briseno, who has 2{ years left to serve on a robbery conviction,
said the money he makes as a prison baker allows him to buy
``toothpaste, shampoo and cards to send to my mother.''
   Warner, convicted of attempted murder eight years ago, is
counting on his bakery and supervisory experience to help him set
up a business when he gets out of prison.
   ``My mom and I are planning to open a restaurant when I get out
in 28 months,'' said Warner, who is from San Diego.
   George Ford II of Los Angeles, who has served three months of a
three-year sentence for armed robbery, worked in the prison's
canteen and laundry before switching to the bakery when it went
into operation May 2.
   Ford, who works around the bakery's 43-foot-long oven making
sure the bread cooks properly and workers abide by safety rules,
said Tony Angelini, the civilian baker overseeing the inmates'
work, ``has been an inspiration to me. He's teaching me how to be
the best oven man there is.''
   The blending of yeast and flour still intrigues Ford, who said
he ``never knew the inner workings of bread.''
   ``I'm used to going to the supermarket, and there it was,'' he
said.
   The bakery is an operation of the Department of Corrections'
Prison Industry Authority, which still oversees the manufacture of
license plates using inmate labor but increasingly exposes
prisoners to varied occupations that they can use upon release.
   ``We can offer these men the skills that will make them a viable
part of society when they get out,'' said Mario Luque, a production
manager for the authority at the San Diego prison.
   Still, each inmate must make an individual commitment. ``It's
like leading a horse to water,'' Luque said.
   Products made by the authority are, by law, sold only to
tax-supported agencies. ``We don't compete with the public,'' Luque
said.
   But state, county and local governments save millions of dollars
each year by purchasing authority goods, said Carlos Chavez, the
authority administrator at the San Diego prison.
   The prison bakery, for instance, sells the bread to the state
for 46.5 cents a loaf, well under the going rate on the open
market. Officials plan to add a second shift of 50 inmate-bakers
and to expand production to 20,000 loaves a day, along with
hamburger and hotdog buns and rolls. The expanded bakery will
supply breads to four other state prisons, said Chavez.
   The prison authority is developing other enterprises at the San
Diego prison, which opened about a year ago _ from an optical
laboratory producing prescription and safety glasses to a textile
mill making inmate clothing.
   The authority's jobs are the most desirable to inmates because
they pay by the hour, giving prisoners a chance to make a little
more money than they would if they worked for the state in a
kitchen, prison fire department or yard clean-up job at a flat
monthly rate.
   ``Plus for each day they work here, they get a day off their
sentence,'' Angelini said.
   The authority, which employs 42 percent of the inmates
statewide, starts its workers at 25 cents an hour for a month-long
probationary period. The inmates work a minimum 30-hour week and
their pay can escalate in 5-cent increments to a maximum of 90
cents an hour.
   ``The pay and conditions are so good as compared to other
(prison) jobs that nobody wants to mess it up,'' Warner said, when
asked how the prison bakers got along with one another on the job.
   Chavez added: ``The Prison Industry Authority is designed to
eliminate idleness among inmates, to keep them working. In the
prison environment, idleness is your No. 1 concern.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, Aug 16</NOTE>
