<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 12,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Jewish population rose slightly last year
to an estimated 5.9 million, representing 2.5 percent of the
population, reports the 1988 Jewish Yearbook.
   Biggest gains were reported in the Sunbelt and West Coast areas,
with a 50,000 increase in the San Francisco-Oakland-San Jose area,
and 30,000 increase in Florida.
   Of 15 states reporting a drop in Jewish population, New York,
whose 1,891,400 make it No. 1 in Jewish population, had the
greatest absolute loss, down 20,000.
   Biggest relative loss occurred in Mississippi, which fell from
3,005 to 2,400 Jews.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Bishop Norbert Gaughan has
prohibited use of church facilities in the diocese for partisan
political gathering, saying the church does not endorse any party
or candidate.
   His action came after pro-life groups complained that candidates
who support legalized abortion were speaking at parish facilities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of Jesus Chist of Latter-day
Saints (Mormon) has reiterated its policy of strict political
neutrality _ of not endorsing any candidates or parties and not
using church facilities for political purposes.
   The church's first presidency added that it does urge ``all
voters to involve themselves in the political process.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican bishops have reversed a
century-old ban on baptizing polygamists in cultures where polygamy
is socially established. The new policy upholds monogamy as the
ideal and forbids converted polygamists from taking any more wives.
   The change was approved at the Anglican global Lambeth
Conference, which ended last weekend. Kenyan Bishop David Gitari
said it has been inconsistent to extend pastoral care to divorcees,
despite Jesus's strictures against divorce, yet not to tolerate
African polygamy, about which Jesus was silent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of influential Greek Orthodox lay people
has set up an independent lay organization, the Orthodox Christian
Laity, seeking to restore and strengthen the role of the laity in
the church.
   Lay people have been ``neglected or relegated to mostly
fund-making roles'' of ``silent obedience'' apart from church
governance, the group said, adding that church history shows
``laity and clergy are equal partners.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLORIETA, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches are experiencing a worsening
shortage of organists, says a Southern Baptist music specialist.
   ``The problem is universal,'' Sharron Lyon told a meeting here.
``All denominations have the same problem.''
   She said few college students now major in organ. At a recent
meeting of the American Guild of Organists, she said, participants
questioned whether musicians would be considering careers as
organists by the end of the century.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, which
began its life last Jan. 1 with merger of three former Lutheran
bodies, had 5,272,984 members in 11,127 congregations at its
outset, reports the church secretary, the Rev. Lowell Almen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Catholic Rural Life
Conference has called on Christians across the country to join in
prayer on Monday, Aug. 15, for mutual community support and drought
relief.
   ``The drought of 1988 has reminded us of our dependence upon
water, as well as our dependence upon our creator who gives us that
water,'' said the national group's executive director, Joseph K.
Fitzgerald.
   ``In these difficult times, we remember that it is our reliance
upon God and one another than enables us to get through
difficulties.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs Aug. 12.</NOTE>
