<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Chan Adv17   08-10 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Chan, Adv 17,0857</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bruce Lee's Successor Refuses to Be Another Rambo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackie Chan, the successor to the legendary
chop and drop king Bruce Lee as Asia's top action film star, has
yet to crack the American market but insists he has more to offer
than Sylvester ``Rambo'' Stallone.
   ``I think I am far better than him _ I dare say it straight to
his face _ because I can do things he can, but he can't do things I
can,'' the baby-faced Chan boasted in a recent interview.
   Chan, 34, is famous throughout Asia for the death-defying stunts
liberally sprinkled throughout his movies, and he pooh-poohs the
``Rambo'' series because Stallone doesn't attempt such exploits.
   ``We see the cave explode and then there he is, appearing on top
of another hill. Really, Rambo,'' he said.
   ``I only do what I really can, something an ordinary man cannot
do but a trained man can. This is me,'' Chan said, proudly tapping
his chest.
   In the 1987 film ``Project A II,'' Chan jumped from a 50-foot
clock tower to the concrete ground through two flimsy canvases. It
was a typical example of his work.
   Such stunts, however, don't come without bruises. In July, he
knocked himself out during a scene in which he somersaulted on top
of a moving bus before smashing through a billboard.
   The combination of stunts and humor in Chan's movies have made
him a smash, so to speak, box-office success in Asia, with his last
10 movies earning more than $150 million in Japan, Hong Kong,
Taiwan, Singapore and Malaysia.
   When he appeared for a promotion in Tokyo in March, 800 fans
turned up, and he topped a list of idols in a survey of Taiwan
teen-agers released in February.
   In 1987, a Japanese woman named Reiko Mimura moved to Hong Kong
to serve him tea in his studio every day. Chan made her his floor
manager, a move that drove dozens more Japanese women to fly to the
British colony.
   The 24-year-old Mimura moved here from Tokyo in 1984 to be
closer to her idol. ``I just looked at him and felt very nervous.
He was nice and gave me his records with his autograph,'' she
recalled of a meeting two years ago.
   Chan, a muscular 5-foot-10, said he does not dare have a lover
or a wife for fear of driving his fans to despair. Two girls
reportedly tried to kill themselves over the actor.
   Despite his wild popularity in Asia, his efforts to impress U.S.
moviegoers have been disappointing. He has appeared in five
American movies, including ``Battle Creek Brawl'' and ``The
Cannonball Run.''
   Chan was not happy with the movies, and said he would like to do
a film with Steven Spielberg _ free of charge if necessary.
   ``I need an opportunity _ a great director who wants to make a
movie about Chinese people to hire me,'' Chan said. ``The audience
will want to see any film by that director, and when they happen to
see me in the movie they'll say, `Hey, this Jackie is cool.'''
   With no offers from Spielberg, however, Chan plans to star in a
self-directed movie in the United States next year. ``If the
Americans like it, OK. If not, forget it,'' he said.
   Chan was born in Hong Kong in 1954 to parents who emigrated to
Australia six years later. They enrolled Chan in the Chinese Opera
Research Institute to study acting, acrobatics and martial arts. He
appeared in a few films before leaving the institute to work as a
stuntman.
   After kung fu star Bruce Lee's death in 1974, director Lo Wei
picked Chan as a new talent. Chan's career was launched in the 1976
film ``New Fist of Fury'' in which he imitated Lee. More than 10
similar films quickly followed, but not until the 1978 ``Drunken
Monkey in a Tiger's Eye'' did Chan find his own style of
action-comedy.
   In 1985, Chan cracked his skull in Yugoslavia while shooting a
scene in which he was to leap from a castle onto a tree. Instead,
he fell 50 feet to the ground, fracturing his skull and driving a
splinter into his brain. Chan underwent brain surgery and hearing
in his right ear remains impaired.
   ``I never thought it would happen to me,'' he said. ``While I
was lying in the hospital I thought a lot and found there are many
things I have not done.'' The accident was a turning point in his
life. When he returned to Hong Kong, he set up a charity
foundation, participated in anti-drug campaigns and ran marathons
for charity.
   ``Now I think more positively,'' he said. ``If I want to do
something, I'll do it quickly. It's not that I'm afraid I may not
live through tomorrow, but I don't want to have any regrets.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Aug. 17</NOTE>
