<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 20-21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Olds Ciera Remains A Top-Selling Nameplate</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera, which made its
debut in 1982, has become the best seller at Oldsmobile and a
top-selling nameplate in the auto industry.
   After testing a 1988 Cutlass Ciera International Series coupe,
it's easy to see why.
   Nothing was surprising about the car. Inside and out, everything
was where you'd expect to find it, and the Ciera went about its
business with predictable ease.
   It didn't seem to matter what the business was. Oldsmobile
reports the Ciera has a higher percentage than normal of buyers who
have single-car households (52 percent).
   Thus, the Ciera is expected to do a lot of things _ get around
town, haul luggage, whatever, said Mary Munkacsy, product liaison
at Oldsmobile for the Cutlass Ciera. A majority of the primary
drivers of Cieras are women, although only 38 percent of the
purchasers are female, she added.
   The average buyer, according to 1987 sales data, has an average
age of 53 and annual income of $44,000. Thirty-five percent are
college graduates and 23 percent are single, Munkacsy said.
   Sales of the Ciera topped 264,800 in the 1987 model year, making
it the sixth best-selling nameplate in the industry that year. It
also became the best-selling Oldsmobile nameplate in 1985, topping
the Cutlass Supreme.
   Through June of this model year, Ciera sales were 165,800, down
about 14 percent from year-ago sales, largely due to increased
competition in the mid-size market.
   But the Ciera still has a respectable record _ it continues to
be the top seller at Oldsmobile. It also shares its body
underpinnings _ A-car design _ with other General Motors Corp. cars
and ranks second, after its sibling Chevrolet Celebrity A-car, in
A-car sales at the giant automaker, Munkacsy said.
   The Celebrity, by the way, was the fourth best-seller in the
industry in 1987.
   Ciera's prices put it about in the range of its competitors.
   At $15,957 out the door, the test car compared to the $16,350
for a 1988 Taurus with 3.8-liter V6 engine and other similar
features. Oldsmobile lists the Toyota Camry as another competitor.
A 1988 Camry with a 2.5-liter V6 engine and equipped like the Ciera
was $15,700. However, there are lower-priced Cieras, including a
bare one at around $11,000 without the V6 engine.
   The International Series coupe and sedan add a new name to the
Ciera line for 1988. Munkacsy said they are designed for younger
buyers who want an expressive and fun car.
   The test car was expressive all right. It had ribbed pieces of
fabric in the middle of the seats and there was more of the ribbed
look on the sides of the doors inside. If you sat in the back seat,
you looked at zippers smack down the middle back of the front seats
plus a number of seams. I could do without all that.
   Legroom in the rear also could be cramped if a front seat was
pushed back and reclined somewhat.
   The suspension was OK, not real firm and certainly not punishing
as in some sporty cars. The trunk was spacious, though items must
be lifted over the rear part of the body of the car.
   Consumer Reports said 1982-86 Cutlass Cieras with six-cylinder
engines rated worse than average or much worse than average in
their trouble index with owners. Many problems were listed as
engine mechanical.
   Munkacsy said there have been a number of engines in the Cieras
over the years and noted a new V6 will be standard in the
International Series in the upcoming 1989 model year and optional
in some other Cieras. She added that in GM surveys the Ciera and
other A-cars have looked very good in having low incidents per car.
   Nonetheless, the company this summer mailed incentive offers to
buyers of 1985-odel Cieras who had expressed displeasure with their
vehicles in surveys by Oldsmobile. Those who took the time to
respond and complain are being offered $1,500 off or an extended
warranty when they buy a new Ciera.
   GM noted that after about three years many owners begin to think
about a new car and the company did not want those buyers to go
elsewhere because of a bad experience with their Ciera.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
