<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-BushProfile Adv14-2Takes   08-10 1241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bush Profile, Adv 14-2 Takes,1262</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush's Epic Ride: The White House on Track 29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He has led a life of almost fictional
proportions, a character out of F. Scott Fitzgerald's reveries
about the Eastern, moneyed elite, a man of drive, ability and charm
who moves, methodically, from mountain to mountain simply because
they are there to climb.
   George Herbert Walker Bush, scion of the late Connecticut
senator and New York financier Prescott Bush _ yes, born to the
silvery privilege so ridiculed by the opposition in Atlanta last
month _ obediently learned to compete early in life and hasn't quit
yet.
   As a child, he played hard in the home on Grove Lane in
Greenwich, Conn. _ no numbered address, people just called it the
Bush house _ matching wit and muscle against family members at
golf, tennis, tiddlywinks, backgammon, bridge, anagrams, anything
that pitted one against another. Then to Yale and war, where he
fought valiantly on the playing fields of Old Blue and in the skies
of the Pacific.
   Next, bride Barbara at his side, he headed westward, in a shiny
1947 Studebaker, to plumb the Texas oil fields and a feverish
business career where he gambled old money to win new. And then
chucked it all _ he's worth a modest $2 million today _ for a
fitful political climb in which he still courts the North with the
noblesse oblige of the Connecticut gentry and serenades the South
with a country tune as rough and dusty as West Texas sagebrush.
   Just days before he trampled his Republican rivals on Super
Tuesday this year, George Bush, 64, sat by a crackling fire in his
vice presidential office and offered this prescription for winning
his ultimate political quest: ``Be what you are in life. Don't try
to be everythng just because you're running for president.''
   Simple and sound enough advice for Bush, who has sometimes
exhibited hesitance but always forged ahead, uprooting wife and
children 28 times in 40 years. A 29th house, the white one on
Pennsylvania Avenue, may be the crowning stop of the Bush odyssey,
but he already has settled on his proudest accomplishment: ``The
fact that our children still come home.''
   It has been a trek from president of his prep school class at
Andover, Mass., like Dad, to captain of the Yale baseball team,
like Dad, to member of the super-secret Skull and Bones society,
like Dad, to millionaire, like Dad, to member of Congress, like
Dad, to _ unlike Dad _ two ambassadorships, chairman of the
Republican Party, director of the Central Intelligence Agency, vice
president for two terms, and now his party's standard-bearer in a
new campaign for the White House.
   But therein lies a problem. For all that George Bush has been,
many people seem uncertain about what he is. As one television
wisecracker put it, ``There is no there there.''
   Who is the real George Bush? In many respects he is what Ronald
Reagan played in the movies.
   Bush was a star collegiate athlete and a daring fighter pilot in
the Pacific, roles that Reagan knew only on the back lots in
Hollywood. He has been married to the same woman for 42 years and
has five children who are devoted to him; Reagan has an ex-wife and
children he rarely sees. Bush regularly attends church, Reagan
seldom does.
   Bush built the Republican Party in Texas, helped save the
national GOP, as its chairman, from being torn apart by Watergate,
and has loyally answered every party call; Reagan began his
political career as a Democrat.
   Yet, it is Reagan whose name is synonymous with Republican
loyalty, with God, family and country, with competitive spirit.
Bush, for his trouble, has been reviled by critics right and left
as a wimp, a lap dog, a preppy, a whiny, waffling boot-licker, a
target of scorn by Carson and Letterman, an invisible Doonesbury
character whose political manhood has been placed in a blind trust.
   Bush bridles at this criticism. To offset it, he sometimes talks
tough, as in a speech in New York City where he blasted ``every
two-bit punk with a knife who mugs a cleaning lady.''
   Several of these efforts have been downright clumsy, as in his
assertion to New Jersey dockworkers four years ago that he had
``kicked a little ass'' in his debate with vice presidential
challenger Geraldine Ferraro.
   But then, to the dismay of his aides, he will talk off-handedly
about his people attending ``coming-out parties'' or preface a trip
to the parched Midwest with a chipper ``Off to the drought!''
   The preppy charge may bother him most, and he has gone to some
lengths to explain that he hasn't worn a button-down Oxford shirt
in 20 years and his suits aren't Brooks Brothers but Arthur Adler,
and no, those aren't Gucci shoes, and he actually jogs more than he
plays tennis.
   At a pre-convention rally for ethnic groups, Bush acknowledged
he is ``a nice WASP'' but said his values match their own. Bush's
critics don't question his innate decency within his own set of
values but challenge whether he ever can understand what it is like
to be poor and oppressed and desperate.
   In his autobiography, Bush says that when he was ambassador to
China, he spurned diplomatic formalities and bicycled around
Beijing to get to know and understand its people.
   Historian Barbara Tuchman tells a story with a different view.
She and Bush appeared at a forum sponsored by a church in
Connecticut, some months after Bush had returned from China.
According to Mrs. Tuchman, somebody asked Bush if he'd had a chance
to meet any ordinary Chinese, and Bush replied: ``Oh, yes. They
gave us a boy to play tennis with.''
   To combat the ``w'' word, Bush has talked up his war record,
when he logged 1,228 hours of flying time and 126 carrier landings,
crashed on takeoff once, got shot down another time, flew 58 combat
missions and won the Distingushed Flying Cross. And he has written
poignantly about the death of his daughter, Robin, at age 3 after a
tortuous bout with leukemia.
   But nobody has questioned Bush's physical courage, or even his
emotional trials or toughness, a point he seems to miss. The doubts
are over his intellectual independence.
   In 1980, candidate Bush favored the Equal Rights Amendment,
opposed an amendment to ban abortions, derided Reagan ``as far to
the right as you can get.'' But since the moment of Reagan's
midnight call in Detroit, he has toed the Reagan line and has
reached to sometimes bizarre lengths to court the right wing.
   Two years ago, he jangled conservative nerves when he joined
civil rights leaders for an emotional tribute to the slain Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. at Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta, and
sang ``We Shall Overcome'' with Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the South
African anti-apartheid leader.
   Three days later, he rallied with the New York State
Conservative Party and the day after that appeared before the
Liberty Federation to praise its founder, the Rev. Jerry Falwell, a
man who had branded Tutu a fraud.
   Bush perplexingly turned out, in December 1985, at a testimonial
for the late William Loeb, the staunchly right-wing New Hampshire
publisher who had called Bush ``an incompetent liberal ... a
hypocrite ... a spoon-fed little rich kid.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-BushProfile Adv14-1stAdd   08-10 1265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bush Profile, Adv 14-1st Add,1286</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: rich kid.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But changes of heart did not come to Bush solely in the Reagan
era. Going back to his early political days in Texas, he has often
seen the light of the times. He opposed civil rights legislation,
then favored it. He backed the Vietnam War, even called for the
``restricted use of nuclear weapons if militarily prudent,'' then
wanted Americans withdrawn from Southeast Asia.
   Hardly a weekend television interview show goes by without
somebody carping that Bush has yet to demonstrate his own ``vision
of America,'' that he should unveil his own ``positive'' campaign
rather than relying on the Reagan program to carry him to the White
House.
   ``He has spent a lifetime thinking in conventional terms, never
reaching beyond them, never even wanting to,'' said Thomas ``Lud''
Ashley, a former Democratic congressman from Ohio but one of Bush's
closest friends for 40 years.
   Other Bush associates agree. Eddie Mahe Jr., who was political
director of the Republican National Committee when Bush was its
chairman, puts it bluntly: ``He's not a deep person. ... He doesn't
have the courage of his convictions.''
   Bush has always favored team play; baseball was his best sport,
and even in his business ventures he took in partners. He does not
enjoy a good argument, and, by many accounts, has rarely spoken out
in Cabinet meetings or National Security Council sessions, although
Bush himself says he communicates his ideas to the president in
their private, weekly Mexican-food lunches.
   But if he has seriously taken issue with the Reagan White House,
it remains locked in his heart. ``There are just many examples in
my mind that I'm not gonna share with you, where I know I've shaped
what happens,'' he said earlier this year. ``You can't point to
three things, I take that on the chin, because it's offset by the
fact that I know I've been loyal.''
   Even after the re-election campaign in 1984, when Reagan was
into a lame-duck term and Bush might have been expected to step
into the foreground, he remained quiet at White House staff
meetings. In early 1985, he rejected David Stockman's pleas for
help in persuading the president to cut the deficit. A year later,
he spurned appeals from several leading Republicans to intervene
with the president to dismiss Donald T. Regan as chief of staff.
   But the most nagging of the ``Where was George?'' questions
relates to the Iran-Contra debacle, an issue the vice president has
yet to address in specific, consistent terms. He has variously
claimed that he was ``out of the loop'' of the decisions that led
to the scandal, that he was ``deliberately excluded'' from key
meetings, and that he was completely unaware of the diversion of
funds from the arms sale to Iran to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   In its 690-page report on the scandal, Congress mentioned Bush
only briefly, saying it found no evidence he knew of the fund
diversion. As for the arms sales themselves, the report said, ``The
vice president attended several meetings on the Iran initiative,
but none of the participants could recall his views.''
   Bush did miss one key meeting, on Dec. 7, 1985, at which
Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Defense Secretary Caspar W.
Weinberger vigorously opposed the arms sale. ``I was off at the
Army-Navy game,'' Bush said.
   Some see Bush's reluctance to step forward and speak out as part
and parcel of a political style geared more to getting along than
pulling along.
   Psychoanalyst Ray Walker, Bush's cousin, says, ``There is a
Christian innocence to George. His life has been without moral
ambiguity. He feels he has been granted goodness and that his
success proves the goodness was warranted.
   ``But this has all come to him without introspection, without
any grappling about right or wrong. George plays it safe. ... He
plays for the status quo.''
   With Bush, politics is personal, a contest to make friends, not
waves. He is a fanatic about writing personal notes to people along
the campaign trail. On the stump, he sometimes goes overboard to
buddy up to people. ``Hey, my main man!'' he says, with the
Connecticut roll of his vowels, to a high school student in Ames,
Iowa.
   And he tailors more than street cliches to his audiences. He
does, contrary to his self-advice, project different images to
different people, endearing himself, perhaps, to the local crowd
but exacerbating the ``wimp factor'' in the process.
   After Bob Dole drubbed him in Iowa, Bush ditched his imperial
style and surfaced in New Hampshire as one of the boys, offering to
help residents whose cars had stalled, shaking hands at factory
gates, tossing snowballs. ``I'm one of you,'' he said. ``I was born
in Massachusetts, grew up in Connecticut ... and have a home across
the way in Maine.''
   In Texas, his story is that his heart is there, too, since, as a
young man, he left the East and took a low-paying job with the
Ideco Corp. to learn the oil business and went on to ``strike out
on my own in the oil fields and build a business.''
   He doesn't dwell on the fact that the job was arranged by his
father, who was a friend of Ideco's chairman of the board, and that
his passage from the Skull and Bones club at Yale to the Petroleum
Club in Houston was helped with an $800,000 stake from relatives
and friends back East.
   Even while abroad, Bush's attempt to please the immediate
audience didn't play all that well elsewhere, like his own country.
After visiting Warsaw Pact forces in Eastern Europe last fall, he
effusively told his hosts that when the Russian tank mechanics
``run out of work in the Soviet Union, send them to Detroit,
because we could use that kind of ability.'' Auto workers were not
amused.
   Some see Bush's proclivity to make friends, to fit in, to be
``one of you,'' not as a flaw but rather as the heart of his
character. They see his empathy with people as the glue of his
success and point out that a major part of the art of being
president is compromise.
   Bush himself acknowledges, his Phi Beta Kappa key at Yale
notwithstanding, that ``I'm no intellectual.'' According to
Nicholas Brady, one of Bush's most trusted confidants, ``He's not
an ideologue in any sense. His philosophy centers around what's
fair and what's appropriate and a right sense of proportion.''
   There is some evidence to suggest that Bush can be effective
without stirring anybody's soul. He held the CIA together at a time
when it was under severe congressional attack for domestic privacy
violations in prior years. Others point out that he kept the GOP's
finances and organization together when Watergate threatened to
shatter the national party.
   Still, his cousin Walker says, ``He always placated his father,
then, later on, he placated his bosses. If you have a history of
deferring to somebody up the line, of saying `I'm not really free
to have my own moral position,' that's not going to change when you
become president.''
   Bush doesn't accept that a bit. ``I know who I am. I know
exactly where I want to go, how to take this country there,'' he
has said.
   But leadership ``isn't just making decisions and giving orders.
It's hearing all points of view before making the decision. That's
the way leadership works in a free society, by keeping open doors
and open minds.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
