<2ND_LINE>BC-GOP Delegate Profile, Adv14,0489</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Republican Confab: Overwhelmingly White and Male</HEAD>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When George Bush steps to the microphone to
accept the Republican presidential nomination this week, he will
gaze out over a convention floor populated overwhelmingly with
white, college-educated men.
   An Associated Press survey of 1,274 of the delegates to the
Republican National Convention found that 83 percent went to
college, 66 percent are men and 92 percent are white.
   By contrast, 52 percent of the delegates to last month's
Democratic National Convention were men and 68 percent were white.
   Republican delegates do show great diversity in their
occupations, ranging from an Amway distributor to the president of
that corporation. Other professions represented include lawyers, by
far the largest single group, teachers, scientists and sales
representatives.
   Three percent of the Republican delegates are members of labor
unions, compared with more than 20 percent of the Democratic
delegates.
   About 26 percent of the Republican delegates hold elected
offices, roughly the same as the percentage of professional
politicians among the delegates to the Democratic convention.
   The average age of a Republican delegate is 49, two years older
than the average age of a Democratic delegate, according to the AP
survey.
   The lack of ethnic diversity at the convention brought a mild
protest from Arizona Hispanics, who complained that none of them
were represented in the state's 32-member delegation.
   Overall, about 3 percent of the delegates to the Republican
National Convention are Hispanic, 3 percent are black, and 2
percent are American Indian, Asian or other minorities, according
to the AP survey.
   ``The polls said at this point that we're behind with women and
minorities, so let's try to do something to even that up,'' Joseph
A. Castillo, a former state senator and chairman of the Arizona
Republican Hispanic Committee, told party leaders.
   Castillo filed a challenge to the Arizona delegation so he could
tell the national party what he thought was wrong with the way
delegates were picked with respect to minorities.
   ``The Arizona delegation is sadly lacking in that respect,''
Castillo said.
   Castillo said he submitted the names of 11 people to the Bush
campaign in Arizona to be considered as candidates for delegates to
the national convention. One was picked as a delegate candidate _
Castillo himself _ but he was not elected.
   Arizona GOP Chairman Burton Kruglick said he supported bringing
minorities into the party, but he said they have to earn their
place by working to elect Republicans.
   ``I think the minority communities of our state have to do a
better job of involving their people,'' Kruglick told the party's
Committee on Contests last week. ``You can't just go out and
annoint somebody because they're a minority.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
