<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Flight255-Fraud Adv14   08-10 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Flight 255-Fraud, Adv 14,0521</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Father John Irish: Was He Making Money Out of Misery?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the early morning hours after Northwest Flight
255 crashed and exploded on a highway last summer, a gray-bearded
man with a clerical collar was there to comfort relatives of the
156 victims.
   One of those relatives had a brother who was a Roman Catholic
priest, and something seemed wrong. ``Father John Irish'' withdrew
when pressed about some of the church's sacraments.
   Others reacted when the priest distributed the name of a Florida
attorney he said could handle damage suits.
   The Wayne County Sheriff's Department, now searching for the
``priest,'' says his real motivation was making money out of misery.
   ``There are always those who see the darker side of things for
opportunity,'' said Sheriff Robert Ficano.
   The investigation of Irish is one of at least two instances of
fraud linked to the crash. In the other, a New York man, then a
flight attendant, sent the department burned personal documents,
allegedly evidence of a 157th victim.
   The information was quickly dismissed.
   ``We took it as a joke when it arrived,'' said investigator Tim
Rapp. ``We checked with his family, who said he was having trouble
with his girlfriend.''
   But the department, along with the FBI, is taking Irish
seriously.
   By the time officials suspected Irish of unethical or criminal
behavior, he had left Detroit. A warrant was issued for his arrest,
charging he defrauded Northwest out of money for a motel room and
other expenses while he ministered to the relatives.
   Witnesses and law enforcement officials said Irish also
distributed business cards for lawyer Ronald Brimmell of Deerfield
Beach, Fla., who is licensed to practice law in Michigan.
   Ficano said no charges had been filed against Brimmell, and
Michael Schwartz of the Attorney Grievance Commission in Detroit
refused to say whether the commission is investigating Brimmell.
Repeated calls seeking comment from Brimmell were not returned.
   Irish vanished after leaving Detroit.
   Then, hours after a Continental airliner flipped and crashed at
takeoff from Stapleton International Airport in Denver on Nov. 15,
killing 27 of the 82 people aboard, police received reports of a
man matching Irish's description talking to survivors at Denver
General Hospital. He allegedly posed as a reporter and a private
investigator who said he was seeking clients for an unidentified
lawyer.
   Ficano said Wayne County investigators went to Denver area,
searched a condominium and found evidence linking Irish to Flight
255. Ficano declined to describe the evidence.
   But Irish eluded authorities again.
   ``We've been following some leads,'' Ficano said. ``He may be in
Canada right now. His mother lives there.''
   The sheriff said Irish's alleged scam involving Brimmell may
have worked in the past and he may be living off the proceeds of
past schemes.
   ``He'll likely surface when the money runs out,'' Ficano said.
``He apparently has a bankroll from other incidents.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
