<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-10 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady against major currencies in
nervous morning trading today, but dealers expected a further rise
in the U.S. currency. Gold rose slightly.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar rose in the first half
hour of trading but then stopped and began fluctuating.
   Traders said they expected the dollar to resume its advance once
the U.S. market opened because the market was very bullish toward
the U.S. currency.
   ``The U.S. economy is so strong that it will continue to attract
funds,'' said a trader in Rome.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.6865, compared
with $1.6830 Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9210 West German marks, up from 1.9160; 1.6075
Swiss francs, up from 1.5960; 6.4785 French francs, up from 6.4325;
2.1707 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1570; 1,418.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,403.50; 1.2180 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2137.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 1.34 yen to a closing 134.92 yen following a
half-percentage point increase to 6.5 percent in the U.S. discount
rate on Tuesday. Later, in London, it was quoted lower at 134.77
yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $427.45 a troy ounce, up
from late Tuesday's $426. At mid-morning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $426.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $426.90, up from $426 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 48 cents to close at a bid
$430.13.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.62 a troy
ounce, up slightly from Tuesday's $6.60.
</TEXT>
