<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Farmers-Batus Bjt   08-10 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers-Batus, Bjt,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Raises Bid For Farmers To $72 A Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   B.A.T. Industries PLC, maneuvering to win
approval of its hostile takeover bid for Farmers Group Inc.,
increased its cash buyout offer to $72 a share, up from $63 a share.
   The beefed-up offer, announced Tuesday and apparently tendered
to promote a possible friendly settlement, boosted the British
conglomerate's total cash offer to more than $4.9 billion from its
last offer of $4.5 billion.
   Farmers, a Los Angeles-based insurance holding company, has
resisted overtures made by Batus Inc., B.A.T. Industries' U.S.
subsidiary, since an initial $60 a share offer in January, but said
Tuesday it would at least consider the latest offer.
   ``The board of directors will give this new offer careful
consideration,'' said Leo E. Denlea Jr., chairman and chief
executive of Farmers.
   In sweetening its offer for Farmers' 68.4 million common shares,
Batus set a condition requiring negotiations of a definitive merger
agreement by Aug. 19.
   Farmers stock rose 12{ cents Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange to $57.75 a share. The new Batus offer wasn't disclosed
until hours after the market closed.
   Farmers has about $11 billion in assets. It is the nation's
third-largest home and auto insurer and seventh-biggest property
and casualty insurer.
   Batus also has been attempting to secure regulatory approval of
its hostile takeover bid from insurance commissioners in nine
states where Farmers does business.
   Those efforts have met with mixed success.
   Arizona is the only state to approve the deal, with decisions
still pending in Texas, Illinois and Kansas.
   In Ohio, the superintendent of insurance has given conditional
approval.
   Three states _ Oregon, Idaho and Washington _ have rejected the
takeover because of issues unrelated to the price offered by Batus,
Farmers said.
   California's insurance commissioner rejected the proposal, but
that decision was recently overturned by a state court. Farmers,
which does 40 percent of its business in California, said it would
appeal.
   Batus, which is based in Louisville, Ky., includes among its
holdings the Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., which makes Kool
cigarettes, and several retailers, led by New York's Saks Fifth
Avenue.
   In the various state regulatory hearings, Farmers has repeatedly
suggested that if Batus took over, its tobacco holdings would
prompt the company to end Farmers non-smoker insurance discounts.
   Several members of Congress have opposed the Batus takeover on
similar grounds, prompting the company to assure governmental and
regulatory bodies it won't end non-smoker insurance breaks.
   The original California rejection of the proposed takeover was
based on a section of state law that forbids foreign ownership of
an insurer.
   About 10 percent of B.A.T. Industries stock is owned by various
government agencies, including town councils in Britain.
   Batus has acknowledged that the takeover bid initiated at the
beginning of 1988 easily could drag on into 1989 and cost the
company as much as $70 million in legal fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
