<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks     08-10 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday, Hit By Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Wednesday on
fears of further rises in interest rates following rate hikes in
both the United States and Britain.
   But the market wasn't rattled by sharp falls in Tokyo earlier
Wednesday and on Wall Street Tuesday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 9.6
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,853.0, at about 12:30 p.m., its lowest
level for the day.
   The index fell 13.4 points on Tuesday.
   Volume was a light 239.6 million shares at midday Wednesday,
compared with 222.1 million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   Dealers said the market was stunned by the interest rate moves,
both of which had been unexpected.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve on Tuesday lifted its discount rate by
half a point to 6.5 percent.
   On Monday, the Bank of England signaled a half-point increase in
the British commercial banks' base lending rate to 11 percent.
   The London market had rallied last week, taking the 100-share
index near its post-crash high, in part on expectations of a stable
interest rate environment in Britain in the near-term, after a
series of rate rises beginning in June. In addition, few analsyts
expected a discount rate hike in the United States ahead of
November's presidential election.
   The London market now is concerned that inflationary pressures
in the United States and Britain might have been underestimated,
and that further rate hikes might be necessary, dealers said.
</TEXT>
