<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DiamondStar     08-10 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diamond Star,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diamond-Star Cars Will Be Available in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No test drives of the new sporty coupes
rolling off the Diamond-Star Motors assembly line will be available
until January, even though full-scale production begins next month.
   Part of the reason for the delay is that the cars produced at
the $650 million Normal plant will be 1990 models. Federal law
prohibits automobile manufacturers from shipping cars to dealers
more than 12 months in advance of their model year.
   ``Besides that, we have such a slow launch curve on production
that we wouldn't have the volume of cars needed to supply the
dealers,'' said company spokeswoman Robin Skiles.
   ``We'll only make about 3,000 units the rest of this year.''
   The state-of-the-art auto plant, a joint venture of Chrysler
Corp. and Mitsubishi Motors of Japan, features high-technology
machinery, with robotics in the final assembly line.
   The first batch of cars produced by Diamond-Star will be divided
evenly between Chrysler and Mitsubishi for distribution to their
network of dealers nationwide. Chyrsler will market the cars as the
Plymouth Laser and Mitsubishi will sell them as the Eclipse.
   Ms. Skiles said Diamond-Star is not involved in sale or
distribution of the vehicles. In fact, Diamond-Star is not even
responsible for shipment of the cars to Chrysler or Mitsubishi.
   ``We manufacture them and the distributors handle everything
else, including hauling them from the plant,'' she said.
   Assembly of pilot cars started in June and Diamond-Star is
scheduled to begin full-scale production in the first week of
September.
   None of the more than 100 pilot cars will be sold. Ms. Skiles
said they will be used for promotion and testing in this country
and Japan.
   A prototype of the Laser will be on display Aug. 11-21 in
Springfield at the Illinois State Fair.
   Rebecca Caruso, a Plymouth spokeswoman in Highland Park, Mich.,
said each Plymouth dealer in the nation's top 100 markets will get
a new Laser for initial showroom display.
   Some smaller markets, including Peoria, will also get a car
because of high interest locally.
   ``The initial rollout is a small number of cars,'' she said.
``They will go to California first. Then Chicago might have a car
in a week or two. And then Peoria will get a car.''
   John Pashdag, Mitsubishi spokesman, said the Eclipse will be
distributed in similar fashion, although each dealer likely will
get more than one car because there are far fewer Mitsubishi
dealers around the country.
   Diamond-Star employs about 875 people and intends to have 1,300
people on board by the end of the year.
   A second shift will be added in 1989 to produce a four-door
compact sedan. Those vehicles will be marketed as the Mitsubishi
Mirage and the Plymouth Eagle Summit. Total employment at that time
is projected at 2,900.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
