<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CM&WBailout     08-10 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CM&W Bailout,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ailing Railroad Makes Final Pitch for $14 Million State Bailout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for the Chicago, Missouri & Western
Railway told a federal bankruptcy judge the company's finances are
improving and public interest demands that the carrier continue
operating.
   At immediate issue is $14 million in aid the state has offered
to keep the line rolling in the belief that the railroad is
important for the state's economic health.
   But the railroad's chief creditors, Citicorp North America and
Heller Financial Inc., oppose the bailout. They want to recover
more than $100 million in loans by liquidating the railroad's
assets.
   The two sides made their final pitch for the proposed $14
million on Tuesday before U.S. Bankruptcy Judge John Schwartz.
   The creditors' position has been that even under the best of
circumstances, the railroad's earnings won't come close to paying
even the interest on the loans in the coming years.
   ``Public interest ... dictates that the (state) loans be
granted,'' Donald Cassling, an attorney for CM&W trustee Daniel
Murray, told the judge.
   He noted that Gregory Baise, director of the state Department of
Transportation, and the Illinois Commerce Commission have testified
in favor of the loan.
   The CM&W filed for protection from its creditors in April,
listing debts of $131.8 million and assets of $103.5 million.
Cassling said its position has improved, although it still is
operating at a deficit.
   Gov. James R. Thompson, who offered the loans and grants, says
the railroad is crucial to 90 Illinois cities along its route, and
to the 300,000 people annually who use the Chicago-to-St. Louis
Amtrak service that runs over CM&W track.
   Schwartz allowed the railroad to accept $1 million of the
proposed bailout on July 29, to keep the CM&W rolling through the
completion of bankruptcy proceedings.
   The proposed loans ``really cost the lenders nothing but they do
add to the value of the lenders' collateral'' by allowing for
rehabilitation of deteriorating track and locomotive repair, which
will cut expenses, Cassling said Tuesday.
   ``The problem with that argument is that it's speculative,''
countered Schwartz.
   Liquidation would affect Illinois' ability to attract and retain
business, Cassling said.
   ``Passenger service to Springfield, the state capital, would
almost certainly cease,'' as would service to Bloomington, Joliet
and other cities, he said.
   Scores of jobs would be lost, not only at CM&W but at companies
that rely on the railroad, Cassling said.
   The railroad's 632-mile freight operation between Joliet and
Kansas City also would be affected, he said.
</TEXT>
