<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Sears-McKids     08-10 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sears-McKids,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Plans Free-Standing McKids Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., in another move into
specialty retailing, says it will open 20 to 40 free-standing
McKids children's stores over the next two years.
   The pilot program will help the nation's largest retailer expand
beyond its traditional image as the Big Store, a place that sells
everything under one roof.
   The McKids stores will feature brand-name children's products in
addition to McKids products, which Sears sells under an exclusive
licensing agreement with Oak Brook, Ill.-based McDonald's Corp.
   The first McKids store will open late this month in a shopping
center on Chicago's North Side, according to Michael Bozic,
chairman and chief executive officer of the Sears Merchandise Group.
   The mostly mall-based stores will sell national brands of
clothing, shoes, accessories, toys, games, books and novelties for
children, Bozic said in a statement.
   The merchandise sold in McKids stores will not be available in
any Sears store and is designed to supplement, not replace,
existing McKids products, he said.
   ``These new stores ... offer an opportunity to broaden our
customer base,'' Bozic said.
   Paul D. Schrage, chief marketing officer of McDonald's, said the
fast-food giant was ``delighted'' with the McKids plan.
   ``The store design is innovative and the quality of product and
service promises to be consistent with the high standards of
McDonald's and Sears,'' he said.
   Sears said the McKids stores were designed from a child's
perspective and, where possible, would feature child-size entrances
in addition to a adult-size doors.
   Sears' expansion into specialty retailing appears designed to
combat its loss of market share to specialty retailers in recent
years.
   In other such moves during the past year, Sears purchased the
Western Auto chain of tire and auto-parts stores; acquired
Pinstripe Petites, a chain of women's apparel stores; launched
in-store ``Brand Central'' superstores to sell brand-name
electronics and appliances alongside its own private-label goods;
and announced plans to open free-standing Brand Central stores.
</TEXT>
