<1ST_LINE>d f PM-ConsumerEquity     08-10 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Equity,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Group Attacks Home-Equity Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group claims California
financial institutions are ``encouraging homeowners to view equity
as an untapped gold mine.''
   San Francisco-based Consumer Action charged on Tuesday banks and
savings and loans are ``enticing homeowners into risking their
hard-earned home equity on frivolous purchases, vacations and
investments.''
   It called for a halt in the use of brochures that encourage
people to use home-equity loans for buying such items as wardrobes
and boats.
   ``I think it's irresponsible marketing,'' Consumer Action
Director Ken McEldowney said.
   ``They're trying to break that historical preference to
primarily use equity loans for home improvements,'' he said. ``It's
trying to create a need in the consumer's eyes.''
   The consumer group said its survey included 25 lines of credit
and 42 second-mortgage loan products at 28 California banks and
savings and loans.
   A home-equity loan is a line of credit given to a borrower based
on how much equity is built up in a home. As with credit cards,
consumers use only the amount they want and are billed only for the
amount they borrow. If consumers are unable to make their monthly
payments, they can be forced to sell their home.
</TEXT>
