<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Obit-Wolfe     08-10 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Wolfe,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CNW Chairman Dies at 58</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp. chairman and chief executive officer
James R. Wolfe, a specialist in railroad law, is dead at the age of
58.
   Wolfe died Monday of cancer, officials said.
   Wolfe served as CNW's chief executive for nearly 12 years, first
as president and CEO of the Chicago & North Western Transportation
Co., then as chairman, president and CEO of CNW Corp., a holding
company formed in March 1985.
   On July 11, Wolfe relinquished the presidency of CNW and its
railroad subsidiary to Robert W. Schmiege, the chief operating
officer of both Chicago-based businesses.
   Schmiege said in a prepared statement that Wolfe was ``the
primary architect of CNW's success and a true leader within our
industry.
   ``We have lost an articulate and forceful advocate for railroads
and their importance to the U.S. economy.''
   Wolfe was born in Hannibal, Mo., to a long-time railroading
family. His grandfather had been a locomotive engineer for the
Wabash Railroad and his father, James E. Wolfe, was vice president
of the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad.
   Wolfe, a graduate of DePaul University's law school, first
worked as a trial attorney for the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy
in 1953.
   He served in the Army and on several railroad commissions and
emergency boards, including a stint as general counsel of the
National Railway Labor Conference before joining the C&NW railroad
in 1968 as vice president in charge of labor relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers     08-10 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspapers Move Quickly To Implement Partial Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News and the Detroit Free Press moved
quickly to integrate operations following approval of their partial
merger, while readers bombarded the papers with questions ranging
from cost to crossword puzzles.
   The joint operating agreement, approved Monday by U.S. Attorney
General Edwin Meese, combines the newspapers' business, advertising
and circulation operations. Their editorial staffs remain separate.
   The Detroit Newspaper Agency, which will manage business
operations under the JOA, on Tuesday announced executive
appointments.
   Five Detroit News executives were named DNA executive vice
presidents: Publisher Louis A. Weil III; vice president for
marketing Richard J. McClennan; vice president for circulation
Robert J. Kurzawa; vice president for finance Gary L. Anderson, and
vice president for human resources Robert R. Taylor.
   Three Free Press managers named to executive vice president
posts with the DNA are Executive Vice President and General Manager
Robert J. Hall; Vice President for Production Robert F. Burns, and
Vice President for Labor Relations Timothy J. Kelleher.
   The first editions published under the JOA will appear Aug. 19.
   Meanwhile, the newspapers fielded questions from readers who
wanted to know more about the JOA. The Free Press set up a
toll-free hotline.
   ``Several callers asked about the Sunday New York Times puzzle
in The Detroit News,'' said Shannon Ross-Albers, a library clerk at
the paper who staffed the phone Tuesday.
   ``Others asked whose ink will be used,'' she said. ``Callers
said they don't like taking The News out in public because the ink
washes off.''
   Ross-Albers didn't know the answer to either question. Or what
would happen to Free Press sports columnist Mitch Albom's regular
Sunday column.
   Callers also asked about how much the newspaper will cost. The
Free Press currently goes for 20 cents and the News costs 15 cents
in Detroit and 20 cents outside the metropolitan area. The price
will go up but when and by how much has not been announced.
   Delivery was another concern. It will stay the same for the Free
Press. The News will switch to an afternoon paper. There will be
some morning delivery in outlying parts of the state, but where and
on what scale hasn't been announced.
   The newspapers, which rank among the 10 largest in the country,
said the Free Press was in danger of going out of business without
the JOA.
   Under the agreement, the papers will publish joint weekend
editions called The Detroit News and Free Press.
   The Free Press will cover news, sports and business on Saturday,
while The News will handle features. They'll switch roles on Sunday.
   Weekend editions will carry all the comics now published in both
papers.
   As many as 500 of the 4,500 employees at the two papers will be
notified within a few days that they be laid off, executives said.
No workers will be cut from the news departments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
