<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Trade,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Rises For First Time In 15 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 14 straight months of decline, Japan's
merchandise trade surplus reversed direction and increased 3.5
percent in July over its year-earlier level, the Finance Ministry
announced today.
   July's $7.18 billion surplus exceeded both the $6.94 billion
registered a year earlier and the $5.93 billion posted in June, the
ministry said.
   Japan's surplus with the United States shrank from a year
earlier to $4.49 billion from $4.79 billion in July 1987, but was
up sharply from $3.63 billion in June.
   Exports to the United States rose 4.0 percent from a year
earlier to $7.95 billion, while imports rose 21.4 percent to $3.46
billion.
   The overall increase in Japan's July trade surplus may partially
reflect the recent rebound of the dollar against the Japanese yen
on foreign exchange markets. The dollar, which began the year at
about 120 yen, was trading in Tokyo Wednesday at close to 135 yen.
   A lower yen tends to make Japanese products more competitive
overseas and foreign goods more costly in Japan.
   Ministry officials also attributed the widening of the gap
between Japan's exports and imports to increased sales of
semiconductors, chiefly to Southeast Asia, where many Japanese
companies have shifted assembly of electronic products as a way of
dealing with higher production costs at home.
   But ministry offi80.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 28.27 to
2,079.13.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 348 up, 1,206 down and 418 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 200.71 million shares, against 148.80 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
