<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-AsiaPopulation     08-10 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Asia Population,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asian Population Hits 3 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-seven minutes after the clock struck midnight
Wednesday, the population of Asia reached 3 billion, according to a
report released by a group of politicians representing 19 Asian
nations.
   The Asian Forum of Parliamentarians on Population and
Development report, based on data compiled by the United Nations,
said the population of Asia hit the 3 billion mark at 0047
Greenwhich Mean Time Wednesday.
   Asia, the world's most populous region, accounts for 60 percent
of the global total, which passed the 5 billion mark in July 1987.
Seven babies are born in Asia every second _ or 150,000 each day _
the report said.
   The forum, headed by Takashi Sato, Japan's Agriculture Minister,
issued the report at an international conference in Tokyo last
month heralding the Day of the Three Billion. The forum groups 19
Asian nations from Australia to Syria.
   ``The designation of a day marking the birth of the 3 billionth
baby in Asia is very symbolic,'' said Shigemi Kono, director
general of the National Institute of Population Problems. ``But I
personally think it is nonsense, because there is no way of
actually knowing when the 3 billionth baby was born.''
   Skepticism about calculations aside, however, Kono agrees there
are serious population problems in the region.
   ``Though we have come close to solving the fertility rate
problem in Japan and China, serious questions remain in India,
Bangladesh and Pakistan,'' he said.
   India, with a population of 818 million, has an annual growth
rate of 2.08 percent. Pakistan, with a population of 115 million,
has a 3.45-percent growth rate and Bangladesh, with 110 million
people, has 2.67 percent, according to United Nations estimates.
   By the year 2025, Asia will have 4.5 billion inhabitants, said
an official with the non-profit, Tokyo-based Asian Population and
Development Association. The estimated growth in Asia is roughly
equal to the increase in the total world population from 1950 to
1980, she added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Experts have predicted that rice production will have to
increase 50 percent by 2025 to feed the continent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
