<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Murdoch-Triangle     08-10 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Murdoch-Triangle,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch Outlines Financing Plans For Triangle Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. plans to raise money
to help finance its $3 billion takeover of Triangle Publications
Inc. by selling its stake in Reuters Holdings PLC as well as land
in Britain and Australia.
   Howard J. Rubenstein, a spokesman for Murdoch, said Wednesday
that the media magnate expects to raise about $200 million from the
sale of News Corp.'s 4 percent stake in Reuters, a London-based
news and financial information services agency.
   He also said Murdoch valued the undeveloped real estate holdings
at about $200 million.
   Murdoch's goal is to raise half the necessary funds by selling
assets and borrow the rest. While there are no formal commitments
yet from lenders, several banks have expressed interest in
participating in Murdoch's acquisition of Triangle, publisher of
Elle, Star, New York magazine and TV Guide, Rubenstin said.
   ``He is extremely confident of his ability to complete the
economic end of the deal,'' Rubenstein said, adding that Murdoch is
working with his financial advisers to determine which operations
will be sold to make up the balance of the $1.5 billion in asset
sales.
   According to Wednesday editions of The Wall Street Journal,
Murdoch has ruled out selling News Corp.'s 20.5 percent stake in
Pearson PLC, publisher of the Financial Times.
   Dismissing speculation that he would use TV Guide to promote his
Fox Broadcasting operation, Murdoch told the Journal that the
television magazine would strengthen News Corp.'s ability to
negotiate favorable positions at supermarket checkout counters for
his other magazines.
</TEXT>
