<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened narrowly mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in relatively light, cautious
trading ahead of an Agriculture Department crop report.
   The report is expected to indicate some drought-related
deterioration of crop conditions in July but traders weren't
willing to bet heavily on the USDA numbers.
   ``The pattern of trading ahead of a crop report is generally
quiet,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   On average, private analysts were expecting the USDA estimates
to show about a 38 percent decline in corn production and a 20
percent drop in soybean production from last year's levels.
   Widespread showers that brought badly needed rain to much of the
Corn Belt appeared to be tapering off today, and may support prices
in the grain markets, Spilka said.
   ``The weather is beginning to dry out a little now and I think
we'll see a warmer, drier pattern develop,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to 2} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.78{ a bushel; corn was
1\ cents lower to { cent higher with September at $2.99 a bushel;
oats were { cent to 1 cent higher with September at $2.69 a bushel;
and soybeans were 1 cent to 5\ cents lower with August at $8.53 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were sharply higher while pork futures were
moderately higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .55 cent to 1.43 cents higher with August at
69.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .63 cent to 1.15 cents
higher with August at 80.87 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to
.75 cent higher with August at 45.90 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .60 cent to .80 cent higher with August at 33.40 cents
a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
were lower.
</TEXT>
