<HEAD>Stok Prices Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with closing figures, comments.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices tumbled in nervous trading Wednesday
on the London Stock Exchange as the market was shaken by declines
in the stock markets in New York and Tokyo and worries about
interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 22.7
points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,839.9.
   Volume was a moderate 442.2 million shares, compared with
Tuesday's 424.9 million shares traded.
   Some analysts said Wednesday's setback was a retrenchment after
the market's recent advances.
   ``There's been no wholesale dumping of stock,'' said Andrew
Smith, economist at CL-Alexanders Laing Cruickshank Ltd. in London.
   Dealers said the markets have been unsettled by the unexpected
interest rate hikes earlier this week in both the United States and
Britain.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve Board on Tuesday lifted its discount
rate to 6.5 percent from 6 percent. That is its interest charge on
loans to member banks.
   On Monday, the Bank of England signaled a half-point gain to 11
percent in the British commercial banks' base lending rates.
   Market watchers were concerned with the Tokyo stock market's
performance Wednesday, as the Nikkei 225 Index plummeted 615.49
points, or 2.2 percent, to 27,554.87.
   London stock prices fell further when prices opened lower
Wednesday on Wall Street, dealers said. On the New York Stock
Exchange, the Dow Jones industrial average was off 27.38 points at
2,051.73 as trading in London wound up.
   In London, the Financial Times 30-share index was off 19.0
points at 1,482.1. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 11.85
points to 1,050.76.
</TEXT>
