<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   08-10 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Rises For First Time In 15 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's merchandise trade surplus rose in July from
a year earlier for the first time in 15 months, the government said
Wednesday.
   Economists said it was too soon to conclude the steady shrinkage
in Japan's surplus had come to an end, and they noted that the
surplus with the United States continued to shrink.
   But some noted that Japanese companies have been raising export
prices lately, something that tends to swell the surplus.
   Japan's worldwide surplus rose 3.5 percent to $7.18 billion from
$6.94 billion in July 1987, and was also up sharply from the $5.93
billion posted in June, the Finance Ministry said.
   Japan's surplus with the United States, its biggest trading
partner, shrank 6.3 percent to $4.49 billion from $4.79 billion in
July 1987. It was up from $3.63 billion in June of this year.
   Although the dollar has risen sharply against the Japanese yen
this year, helping make Japanese goods more competitively priced,
economists said that was probably a relatively small factor in the
rise in the surplus.
   It typically takes more than a year before changes in currency
rates begin to show up in changes in the volume of goods shipped
between nations, the economists said.
   ``I don't think you can read too much into one month's data,''
said Mitchell Held, an economist for Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co. in New York.
   Japanese export prices are rising partly because Japan's
domestic economy is growing so strongly that it has created
shortages of products for export, said Yoshihisa Kitai, economist
for the Long Term Credit Bank of Japan in New York.
   Moreover, Kitai said, Japanese exporters are beginning to push
through price increases after having held prices down to avoid
losing their share of foreign markets.
   Kyocera Corp., a maker of ceramic parts for electronics, raised
prices 18 percent earlier this year, said Thomas Chesser, a Smith
Barney analyst. He said Kyocera dominates its market so much that
it can afford to raise prices.
   Finance Ministry officials attributed the widening of the
surplus partly to increased sales of semiconductors, chiefly to
Southeast Asia, where many Japanese companies have shifted assembly
of electronic products as a way of dealing with higher production
costs at home.
   Exports of semiconductors during the month surged 51.3 percent
over the previous year's level to $1.11 billion, it said.
   In the long run, once foreign operations are well-stocked, the
movement of manufacturing off shore should begin to shrink the
surplus.
   Ministry officials said it was too early to tell if the July
trade figures signaled a long-term turnaround from more than a year
of shrinking Japanese trade surpluses.
   Overall, Japanese exports during the month rose 16.2 percent to
$23.13 billion from $19.9 billion, while imports grew 23.1 percent
to $15.9 billion from $13.0 billion, the ministry said.
   Exports to the United States rose 4.0 percent from a year
earlier to $7.95 billion, while imports rose 21.4 percent to $3.46
billion.
   Japan's surplus with the European Community grew from $1.53
billion in July 1987 to $1.97 billion in July this year. Exports to
the region rose 29.6 percent from a year earlier to $4.12 billion,
while imports grew 30.7 percent to $2.15 billion, the ministry said.
   Exports to Southeast Asia grew 23.2 percent to $5.77 billion,
while imports from the region rose 26.7 percent to $4.05 billion,
it said.
   When seasonally adjusted, Japan's trade surplus rose to $6.24
billion from $5.19 billion the previous month.
   Japan calculates its trade figures on a customs-clearance basis,
which includes transportation and insurance costs in imports but
not in exports. If the costs were added to both, Japan's trade
surplus would be higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
