<HEAD>Insilco Reports Receiving Several Unsolicited Buyout Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insilco Corp. disclosed Wednesday that it
received several unsolicited buyout offers since a management-led
group's $950 million bid for the high-technology and specialty
consumer products company last week.
   Insilco did not identify the parties involved in a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, but it said it had enterted
into confidentiality agreements with certain groups.
   Last Thursday, Insilco's board of directors approved a
$29-a-share management offer in what some analysts described as an
anti-takeover defense. At the time, analysts called the bid
reasonable and said they doubted a better offer would be
forthcoming.
   In recent years, Insilco, once known as the International Silver
Co., has restructured itself into an industrial holding company
with operating companies that make products for high-technology
industries and speciality consumer markets.
   Insilco makes Red Devil paints, Rolodex rotary files, metal
cartridges and other projectiles for the defense industry and
Dual-Lite emergency lighting equipment.
   Insilco earned $11.7 million, or 55 cents per share, in the
second quarter, compared with $11 million, or 52 cents a share,
last year. Revenue totaled $196.4 million, up from $154.3 million.
