<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Iacocca-Fortune     08-10 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iacocca-Fortune,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iacocca Says He, Ex-Boss Ford Were `Buddies'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca says he
holds no grudges against Henry Ford II for firing him a decade ago,
preferring to remember the good times they shared, like when they
hunted, went to parties or ``caroused Europe together.''
   ``My difficulty with Henry Ford was over long before he died
last year,'' the 63-year-old Iacocca wrote in the Aug. 29 edition
of Fortune magazine, which was made public on Wednesday.
   ``Most people were remembering the last years of his life, when
Henry was sick with a bad heart, realizing that he was mortal and
worrying about his health day and night,'' he said. ``I tried to
remember the years beginning in 1960, when we were buddies.''
   The grandson of Ford's founder died about a year ago after more
than 40 years at the helm of the nation's second-largest automaker.
   Iacocca, who rose to stardom in the auto industry after creating
the super-popular Mustang automobile, was fired after more than 20
years at Ford Motor Co. in 1978. He has been at Chrysler since then
and credited for putting the once-troubled company back on its feet
with the help of $1.2 billion in government-guaranteed loans.
   ``A lot of people told me Henry Ford II did me a favor 10 years
ago by firing me,'' Iacocca said in the five-page Fortune article
he wrote. ``They said that if I had stayed at Ford, I would have
been in a comfortable ivory tower. The company would have given me
a gold watch when I retired, and that would have been the end of my
life.
   ``...By getting canned in 1978 I got thrown into a situation
where I became a leader.''
   Iacocca had few kind words to say about Henry Ford II in his
first book, ``Iacocca: An Autobiography,'' but in the Fortune
article he recalled how he and Ford ``hunted together, we went to
parties together, we caroused Europe together.''
   ``I remember the 16 good years, and not the two bad ones in 1977
and 1978.''
</TEXT>
