<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in light trading marked by
nervousness about the Agriculture Department's upcoming crop
production report.
   Grain and soybean futures were led higher by the soybean meal
market, which posted strong gains on rumors that the Soviet Union
was shopping in Argentina for soybean meal pellets, analysts said.
   Some weather forecasts predicted a hot, dry weekend in the
Midwest, which added further support to the markets, said Joel
Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research Department Inc.
   But traders were unwilling to take large risks ahead of the USDA
crop report, which will be released after the grain and livestock
futures markets close on Thursday.
   The report is expected to indicate further deterioration of
drought-stressed crops during July.
   ``The pattern of trading ahead of a crop report is generally
quiet,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Private analysts' predictions of the USDA estimates averaged out
to a 38 percent decline in corn production and a 20 percent drop in
soybean production from last year's levels.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 6} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.83{ a bushel; corn was \
cent to 2{ cents higher with September at $3.01 a bushel; oats were
2 cents to 5 cents higher with September at $2.71{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 9\ cents higher with August at $8.65
a bushel.
</TEXT>
