   Stock prices fell sharply today, extending
Tuesday's decline amid continuing interest-rate worries.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 28.27 points
Tuesday, dropped 35.92 to 2,043.21 by 3 p.m. today on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 236 up, 1,291
down and 408 unchanged.
   The Federal Reserve's move Tuesday to raise its discount rate
from 6 percent to 6.5 percent remained the dominant topic on Wall
Street.
   Many analysts had been expecting the Fed to tighten credit
further. But the timing of the increase caught many traders by
surprise.
   ``Or perhaps it was the memory that the previous hike last
September was followed by you-know-what in October,'' said Newton
Zinder at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   In one sense, analysts said, the Fed's action could turn out to
be a plus for the stock and bond markets if it achieves its stated
purpose of restraining inflation.
   But at the same time, it created problems for the stock market
by intensifying recession fears and adding to the allure of short
term interest-bearing investments, which compete with stocks and
bonds for investors' favor.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone & Telegraph
dropped \ to 26; Exxon [ to 45}; International Business Machines 1|
to 120, and General Electric } to 40[.
   Farmers Group climbed 5~ to 63| as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company, which had rejected a
$63-a-share takeover bid by B.A.T. Industries of Britain, said it
would consider a sweetened offer of $72 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
1.99 to 148.67. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 3.81 at 297.31.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 165.65 million shares with an
hour to go.
