<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sterling-CEO     08-10 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sterling-CEO,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pietruski Resigns As Chairman Of Sterling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and chief executive officer of
Sterling Drug Inc. resigned Wednesday, six months after the company
was acquired by Eastman Kodak Co., because of what one official
called a decline in his authority.
   John M. Pietruski, 55, is the fifth officer of Sterling Drug,
maker of such products as Bayer aspirin and Phillips Milk of
Magnesia, to resign since June, Sterling spokesman John H. Wood
said.
   Wood said that none of the resignations were prompted by Eastman
Kodak, which acquired the company in March for $5.1 billion. Kodak,
based in Rochester, N.Y., said at the time of the purchase that it
would leave Sterling's organization intact.
   The resignation is effective Aug. 31.
   ``When a publicly owned corporation loses its independence it is
not unusual for there to be significant changes in the duties of
the acquired company's chief executive officer,'' Pietruski said in
a letter to Sterling employees Wednesday. ``Now that Sterling is no
longer an independent company, I have experienced a similar change
in my position.''
   Wood said that after Sterling's acquisition by Kodak in March,
Pietruski was named executive vice president of Kodak reporting to
Kodak President Kay R. Whitmore
   ``Effectively Mr. Pietruski's reporting relationship dropped and
I think that's what that refers to,'' Wood said. ``There honestly
was no awkward relationship (with Whitmore), just a diminished
responsibility, frankly, and authority.''
   Wood said Pietruski's replacement would be announced on
Thursday. Among the likely successors are Leo ``Jack'' Thomas,
currently vice chairman at Sterling and formerly senior vice
president at Kodak.
   Pietruski, who was elected chairman of Sterling Drug in May
1985, did not say what he plans to do after he leaves.
   ``He has several options which he is considering, but he hasn't
decided yet,'' Wood said.
</TEXT>
