<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Aeromexico Bjt   08-10 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aeromexico, Bjt,0963</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temporary Aeromexico Operation Extended While Pilots Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the state-owned Aeromexico plunged into
bankruptcy last April, the government charted a course: create a
new, pared-down major airline and let a covey of fledgling carriers
grow.
   But negotiations on the new airline have been slower and more
complicated than anticipated, prolonging uncertainty and, say hotel
operators, losses in the crucial travel industry.
   The negotiations are being held up by disagreements over the
extent of the pilots' share in the new airline and their future
role in its management.
   The 54-year-old Aeromexico was one of two airlines that carried
the bulk of air passengers over Mexico's rugged, mountainous
terrain.
   In mid-April, its 43 planes were grounded overnight by a strike
of ground and technical workers protesting management plans for
cutbacks. Travelers were stranded, and cities served exclusively by
Aeromexico were left without service.
   Then, less than three weeks later, some of its jets were back in
the air under a limited, 90-day operation run by the bankruptcy
trustee, a government bank, to ease the crisis.
   With the new airline delayed, the temporary operation has been
extended.
   Flights to Aeromexico's foreign destinations _ including New
York; Miami; Houston; Tucson, Ariz.; and Madrid, Spain _ may not be
resumed until next year, an aviation source said.
   Crucial to forming the new airline are the 765 pilots who flew
for Aeromexico. When the company collapsed, flight attendants and
the 7,250 ground workers were fired and given severance pay.
   The pilots, however, still have their contract, although they
are flying only a few hours each with the temporary operation.
   Their union, which also includes pilots of the other major
airline, Mexicana, has a tentative commitment from the government
for about 35 percent ownership in the new airline. It's to be
called Aerolineas Mexicanas SA, possibly AMSA for short.
   As part of the government's shedding of its array of
non-strategic and unprofitable companies, the other 65 percent is
to be sold to private interests.
   Pilots and the government are negotiating both a new contract
and terms for the pilots' ownership in the still-to-be-formed
company that will hire them.
   The government blamed fat union contracts, along with chronic
losses, poor service and the four-day strike for Aeromexico's
financial failure.
   ``The situation of Aeromexico was totally unsustainable. It no
longer operated,'' said one industry source who spoke on condition
he not be identified.
   While the government wants to create a more efficient company
with fewer personnel that would be attractive to private investors,
some businessmen are reported to be wary of an alliance with a
union representing company employees.
   Alejandro Luna, an Aeromexico pilot and outgoing head of the
Aviation Pilots' Union, counters that employee interest in the
company's profitability should make it more attractive.
   ``It's a guarantee for anyone who's going to invest that its
labor problems will be at a minimum,'' he said in an interview.
   He said the two sides have set a mid-August deadline for
agreement.
   Any deal made on Aeromexico also could affect the value of the
government's majority ownership of the better-run Mexicana. The
government's shares in Mexicana are expected to be sold once the
new airline is formed.
   Officials at the Communications and Transportation Department,
the bankruptcy trustee and the temporary operation either declined
or did not respond to interview requests.
   A department plan published in late May calls for two trunk
airlines; two or three regional airlines for the Pacific and
Caribbean-Gulf of Mexico areas; and feeder airlines for five
sectors.
   Smaller, privately-owned airlines, notably Aerocalifornia and
Aeromar in the Northwest of Mexico, already are flying some new
routes and have begun buying new planes.
   Aeromexico, which carried 5.8 million passengers in 1987, is
flying one-fourth to one-fifth of the 250 or so flights a day it
operated before.
   Created as a private airline, Aeromexico absorbed 23
unprofitable airlines between 1940 and 1960. Nationalized in 1959,
it survived on government subsidies for years, something considered
acceptable in Mexico until reforms forced by the 6-year-old
economic crisis.
   But contract restrictions on work scheduling, ample benefits,
the high employee-to-plane ratio and other conditions made
cost-cutting difficult, the industry source said.
   ``Say a flight was delayed because of mechanical trouble. When
the plane was ready, just one hour of the work day was left,'' he
said. ``Crews decided they wouldn't make the flight. Or they would
be paid another full day or the flight would be canceled, and many
details like this.''
   Four percent of flights were canceled last year, 35 percent were
delayed and the aging fleet was constantly in need of maintenance,
the government said.
   Ironically, late last year efficiency measures had improved the
company's situation.
   The flight attendants union blames the losses on frequent
management changes, including four directors in six years, capital
flight due to corruption and a surplus of non-union employees,
among other reasons.
   The disruption ``definitely has had an impact'' on business,
Guillermo Rocha, president of the Mexican Hotel and Motel
Association, said.
   ``What worries us is that the start of the new airline has been
postponed,'' he said.
   In Mexico City, hotel occupancy has been running about 60
percent instead of its usual 85 percent for July and August, said
Marcos Romano, president of the city's hotel association.
   ``There aren't enough flights, both in the interior as well as
from the United States to Mexico,'' he said.
   Occupancy in Acapulco, the biggest Pacific beach resort, is
about 60 percent now, when it should be booked solid with Mexican
vacationers, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
