<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Sun-Fujitsu     08-10 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sun-Fujitsu,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Micro and Fujitsu Sign Marketing Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's largest computer supplier,
Fujitsu Ltd., has signed a $280 million agreement to market Sun
Microsystem's workstations and servers.
   Sun Microsystems, the world's leading supplier of network-based
distributed computing systems, has experienced rapid expansion in
the last year, with 1988 revenues topping $1 billion, almost
doubling its 1987 revenues.
   The Mountain View-based company estimates that about 15,000 ``S
Family'' workstations and servers will be sold during the next
three years.
   The worldwide agreement will initially focus on the Japanese
market, where Sun currently sells more products _ directly and
through original equipment manufacturer agreements _ than any other
vendor.
   Fujitsu expects the Sun workstatons to complement its existing
workstation line, ``offering a more attractive total solution to
customers because of the availablility of of 1,500 software and
hardware products that run on Sun workstations,'' said Yasuchika
Koike, Fujitsu board director.
   ``Sun has always participated in strategic partnerships as a way
of expanding our markets,'' said Bernard Lacroute, executive vice
president of Sun. ``We have had a very good relationship with
Fujitsu in the past and this new agreement offers important
benefits to both companies.''
   Scott McNealy, president and chief executive officer of Sun,
said the company expects to show significant year-over-year
earnings increases per share in the next several quarters.
   ``The overall business environment, both here and abroad, bodes
well for additional increases in market share in the next few
quarters,'' he said.
</TEXT>
