<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Diamond-Star     08-10 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diamond-Star,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi May Join `Reverse Importers' with Diamond-Star Model</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A front-wheel-drive sports coupe being
manufactured at the Diamond-Star Motors plant may be distributed in
Japan as Mitsubishi Motors Corp. considers joining the ``reverse
importers.''
   Japanese auto manufacturers Honda, Nissan and Mazda already are
shipping U.S.-made vehicles back to Japan. And Mitsubishi is
thinking of shipping its Eclipse model, to be made here, because it
will not compete with any autos now on the market in Japan.
   Richard Recchia, executive vice president of Mitsubishi Motor
Sales of America, said Tuesday the ``reverse import'' plan is being
considered.
   ``Imported cars are beginning to get strong in Japan,'' Recchia
told The Bloomington Pantagraph.
   The Diamond-Star plant is a joint venture between Chrysler Corp.
and Mitsubishi Motors of Japan. The sports coupes produced in
Normal will be 1990 models available at Plymouth and Mitsubishi
dealers in January.
   A decision on exporting the Eclipse would be made within six
months and will depends on whether ``the domestic dealer network
over there wants it,'' Recchia told the newspaper.
   If the Eclipse is shipped overseas, he said it will involve
small numbers and will occur later next year or in early 1990.
   Toyoo Tate, president of Mitsubishi, recently told the Los
Angelese Times his company ``was thinking of importing from the
United States.''
   He said the Eclipse was a perfect candidate because it is
different from anything on the market in Japan.
   ``We will be making a completely different kind of sporty car in
the United States than we make in Japan,'' Tate said.
   Recchia said production of a convertible also is being studied
at the Diamond-Star plant with a decision expected by next spring.
   ``The biggest problem is the passive-restraint (seat-belt) laws.
Convertibles are difficult to put those in. If we can solve the
problem in an economic way, we could produce a convertible,'' he
said.
   Full-scale production begins in September at the $650 million
Diamond-Star plant. About 875 employees already are at work,
producing pilot cars and gearing up for the offical start of the
assembly line.
</TEXT>
