<DOCNO> AP880810-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Stocks-Markets     08-10 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Stocks-Markets,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds Plummet On Continued Interest-Rate Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest-rate worries overwhelmed the financial
markets again Wednesday and sent the Dow Jones industrial average
plummeting 50 points before a protective collar on program trading
was triggered.
   With less than an hour left in the trading session and the Dow
down 50.50 points, the New York Stock Exchange said it banned
member firms from using computer trading systems for index
arbitrage, the most prevalent form of program trading.
   The Dow closed down 44.99 at 2,034.14, for its fifth consecutive
loss. The downward trend in stocks intensified Tuesday when the
Federal Reserve announced an increase in a key lending rate.
   The Fed surprised traders by boosting its discount rate, the
rate it charges on short-term loans to member banks, by half a
percentage point to 6.5 percent to keep a lid on inflation.
   Fallout from the rate increase was felt in financial markets
around the world, as investors voiced worries that the Fed's move
is just the first of a series of hikes in global lending rates.
   Stock prices in Japan and Britain were hit hard. In Tokyo, the
already volatile Nikkei Index of 225 selected issues posted its
biggest lost since November, plummeting 615.49 points, or 2.2
percent, to close at 27,554.87.
   And in London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index fell 22.7 points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,839.9.
   In the credit markets, the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond
slipped more than $13 per $1,000 in face value, while its yield
soared above 9.3 percent in late afternoon trading.
   ``The market's slashing its wrists again,'' said Ward McCarthy,
chief financial economist at Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The Dow was lifted from its lows when the NYSE put into effect
its controversial collar, which bans the use of the exchange's
computer system for index arbitrage on days when the Dow average
rises or falls 50 points from the previous close.
   This marks the sixth time the collar has been put into effect
since it was approved as a temporary measure in April. The
Securities and Exchange Commission is reviewing reforms that
include coordinated trading halts when the Dow falls 250 points.
</TEXT>
