<HEAD>Posts $62.9 Million Loss in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytech Corp., a manufacturer of
automotive friction material, said Wednesday it lost $62.9 million
in the second quarter, primarily due to the divestiture of its
wholly owned subsidiary, Raymark Corp.
   The loss contrasted with earnings of $2.6 million, or 82 cents
per share, for the same period last year.
   Sales increased 9 percent in the second quarter, from $34
million last year to $37.2 million this year. The most substantial
gains were made within the domestic wet clutch and brake business.
   Raytech shareholders approved and ratified the divestiture of
Raymark common stock during the annual meeting in May.
   ``The divestiture of Raymark Corporation will allow Raytech's
management to allocate resources previously involved with Raymark's
problems to Raytech's future growth,'' Raytech president and CEO
Craig R. Smith said.
   For the first six months of the year, Raytech lost $66.4 million
in contrast to a profit of $4.6 million, or $1.46 a share, a year
earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose to $75.5 million from $67.5 million a
year earlierr.
