<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0547</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply to a 2{-month low
Wednesday as the jolt of Tuesday's increase in a key Federal
Reserve interest rate kept reverberating through the market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 44.99 to 2,034.14,
bringing its loss over the past five sessions to 99.93 points. The
average last closed lower at 2,031.12 on May 31.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
201 up, 1,401 down and 378 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 200.95 million
shares, against 200.71 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 231.09 million shares.
   The Federal Reserve's move Tuesday to raise its discount rate
from 6 percent to 6.5 percent remained the dominant concern on Wall
Street.
   Many analysts had been expecting the Fed to tighten credit
further. But the timing of the increase caught many traders by
surprise.
   ``Or perhaps it was the memory that the previous hike last
September was followed by you-know-what in October,'' said Newton
Zinder at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   In one sense, analysts said, the Fed's action could turn out to
be a plus for the stock and bond markets if it achieves its stated
purpose of restraining inflation.
   But at the same time, it created problems for the markets by
intensifying recession fears and adding to the allure of short term
interest-bearing investments, which compete with stocks and bonds
for investors' favor.
   With about 40 minutes left in the session, the NYSE activated
the ``collar'' that bars member firms from using exchange computer
facilities for so-called index arbitrage program trading whenever
the Dow rises or falls 50 points in a session.
   The exchange plans to discontinue this procedure if the
Securities and Exchange Commission approves alternative measures it
has proposed to deal with market volatility.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone & Telegraph
dropped ] to 25~; Exxon ] to 45{; International Business Machines
2} to 118~; Dow Chemical 1} to 84}, and General Electric } to 40[.
   Procter & Gamble, which reported a quarterly earnings increase
that came in toward the low side of analysts' estimates, fell 1[ to
72{.
   Farmers Group climbed 5} to 63{ as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company, which had rejected a
$63-a-share takeover bid by B.A.T. Industries of Britain, said it
would consider a sweetened offer of $72 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $42.12 billion, or 1.58
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 2.43 to 148.25.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 5.67 to 301.19, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 4.59 at 261.90.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
tumbled 5.72 to 378.51. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 296.57, down 4.55.
</TEXT>
