<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls in New York, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in domestic trading after
closing higher overseas Wednesday as a variety of factors fueled
trader anxiety about the currency's near-term direction.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $428.80 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from
$426.90 late Tuesday.
   Profit-taking, which followed the dollar's surge on Tuesday, set
in Wednesday morning after the U.S. currency was unable to climb
past 1.9250 West German marks, said James T. McGroarty, a vice
president at Discount Corp.
   The dollar was also hurt by concerns about U.S. trade deficit
figures scheduled to be released next week and by rumors of a
possible meeting of the Group of Seven industrial nations,
McGroarty said.
   No meeting of the G-7 has been announced, but traders were
concerned a session might be called to discuss ways of ending the
dollar's recent advance, McGroarty said.
   The dollar was also buffeted by worries about declines Tuesday
and Wednesday on the stock and bond markets, he said.
   ``It's enough to keep the market a little nervous,'' McGroarty
said.
   However, the dollar's fall was broken by prospects of higher
interest rates. The dollar rose Tuesday after the Federal Reserve
announced it had increased its discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6
percent.
   The dollar began its day in Tokyo, rising 1.34 Japanese yen to a
closing 134.92 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted lower at 134.46
yen, and it slipped further to 133.675 yen in New York from late
Tuesday's 135.15 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6910 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6830 late Tuesday,
and in New York, the pound rose to $1.69715 from late Tuesday's
$1.6840.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's quotes, included: 1.90685 West German marks, down from
1.9204; 1.5955 Swiss francs, down from 1.6065; 6.4505 French
francs, down from 6.4710; 1,409.50 Italian lire, down from
1,413.475; and 1.22735 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2160.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.9155 West German marks, up from 1.9125; 1.5995
Swiss francs, up from 1.5960; 6.4780 French francs, up from 6.4325;
2.1655 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1570; 1,414.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,403.50; and 1.2273 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2137.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $428.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $426 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, the metal closed at a bid $427 an ounce compared with
$426 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 48 cents to close at a bid
$430.13 an ounce.
   In New York, gold closed at $429.20 a troy ounce on the
Commodity Exchange, up from $427.40 late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid of $6.67 a
troy ounce, up from $6.60 bid late Tuesday.
   Silver also rose on the New York Comex, closing at $6.677 a troy
ounce, compared with late Tuesday's $6.630.
</TEXT>
