<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Inflation     08-10 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Inflation,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Prices Up 1.7 Percent in July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 1.7 percent in July, the
smallest monthly increase in seven years, the central Bank of
Mexico announced.
   Inflation for the first seven months of the year reached 43.3
percent, the bank said, while the annual inflation rate from July
of 1987 was 122.3 percent.
   The government started an Economic Solidarity Pact with business
and labor last December to control inflation, which soared by a
record 159.2 percent for 1987.
   The central bank's report said the latest figures showed the
pact ``continues being successful in bringing down the inflationary
process.''
   Consumer prices had risen 2 percent in June, 1.9 percent in May,
3.1 percent in April, 5.1 percent in March, 8.3 percent in February
and a record 15.5 percent in January.
   The biggest contributors to the increase in the latest report,
issued Tuesday night, were an 11.6 percent increase in fresh meat
prices and 7.4 percent in rents.
   The bank's report noted decreases in 82 of the 302 categories
tracked for the consumer price index, among them a 1 percent
decline in health and personal care. Shoes and clothing fell 0.5
percent and transportation fell 0.2 percent.
   A key component of the inflation-fighting program is a freeze on
the minimum wage, prices of government-regulated goods and services
and the exchange rate of the peso currency.
   Critics of the solidarity pact say it was intended to
artifically control inflation to ease unrest before July general
elections, without correcting any of the problems that are the
basic causes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
