<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Reagan-BallBearings     08-10 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Ball Bearings,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Puts Off Ruling on Import Protection Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said Wednesday it
has postponed action until the end of the year on a request by U.S.
ball bearing manufacturers for protection from imports.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity said President Reagan
directed the Commerce and Defense departments to assess recent
efforts to improve the competitiveness of the ball bearing industry
before a decision is made on import restrictions.
   In July 1987, the Anti-Friction Bearing Manufacturers
Association filed a petition seeking protection under a 1962 law
designed to protect industries vital to national defense.
   ``The petition alleged that high levels of imports are seriously
weakening the domestic bearing industry's defense production
capabilities,'' Verity said in a statement.
   ``The administration ... is currently taking a number of steps
to better enable the domestic bearing industry to improve its
production capabilities,'' he said.
   Among the steps are new regulations requiring defense
contractors to use only U.S.-manufactured ball bearings and a
program to encourage the industry to modernize.
   ``Because the administration's actions are expected to improve
the bearing industry's ability to meet national security
requirements, the president is withholding a final decision ... at
this time,'' Verity said.
</TEXT>
