<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RateFallout Bjt   08-10 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rate Fallout, Bjt,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Move Causes Tremors In World Financial Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jolt applied to interest rates by the
Federal Reserve singed financial markets again Wednesday, as
traders from Tokyo to Wall Street sweated over the prospects for a
global interest-rate spiral.
   The day started with a violent reaction in Japan, where the
already volatile Nikkei Index of 225 selected issues posted its
biggest loss since November. The index plummeted 615.49 points, or
2.2 percent, to close at 27,554.87.
   When trading shifted to London, the Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100-share index echoed those rumblings by shedding 22.7
points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,839.9.
   And in New York, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell
44.99 points to close at 2,034.14 after a loss of more than 28
points the previous day.
   The Dow had been off slightly more than 50 points with an hour
of trading to go Wednesday, but that descent was stalled when the
New York Stock Exchange triggered its post-crash collar on program
trading.
   The markets began reeling in the United States on Tuesday after
the Federal Reserve unexpectedly announced it was raising a key
lending rate. The 0.5 percent increase in the discount rate to 6.5
percent put the fee the Fed charges member banks for short-term
loans at its highest level in more than two years.
   Interest-rate worries then swept overseas to Tokyo, hitting a
market that some experts said was poised for a selloff.
   Noboru Terashima, head of research at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Asia, Inc. in Tokyo, said the Fed's decision hastened the
inevitable for the Japanese market, which had lately shown signs of
instability.
   Many observers said markets overseas were caught by surprise and
may have overreacted. Many investors around the world had assumed
the Fed would refrain from taking any interest-rate action until
after November's presidential election.
   But with the Fed's decisive, anti-inflation move, ``there's
worry on worldwide basis that everybody is competing, with interest
rates as their weapon,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president
at First Albany Corp.
   Japan, Britain and West Germany all have taken action recently
to push up short-term interest rates, and more hikes are expected.
   ``That makes markets fairly nervous even though cooperation
among the major Western trading nations hasn't broken down,'' said
Johnson.
   If interest rates become a drawing card for U.S. securities,
some of the money siphoned out of Japan's stock market could find
its way into American markets.
   ``There's no doubt that Japanese portfolio managers have an
ongoing appetite for U.S.-dollar assets, and this increased rate
differential makes them attractive,'' said Ronald Solberg, a vice
president and senior international economist at Security Pacific
National Bank in Los Angeles.
   The Japanese government's long-term bond is carrying a yield of
about 5.4 percent, compared with a return well over 9 percent on
the U.S. Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue.
   Indeed, in the long run, rate hikes can help stabilize the
financial markets by calming inflation worries.
   But in the immediate aftermath of the Fed's action, fear appears
to be overwhelming investors.
   With the Dow down 50.50 points late in the trading session
Wednesday, the New York Stock Exchange said it banned member firms
from using computer trading systems for index arbitrage, the most
prevalent form of program trading.
   The so-called collar, used for the sixth time since it was
approved as a temporary measure in April, bans the use of the
exchange's computer system for index arbitrage on days when the Dow
average rises or falls 50 points from the previous close.
   In the credit markets, bond prices tumbled as their yields
soared. The Treasury's 30-year bond plunged $17.50 per $1,000 in
face value. Its yield surged to 9.36 percent _ a level not seen
since last December _ from 9.19 percent late Tuesday.
   The dollar, which initially rallied on the interest rate news,
pulled back amid some profit-taking. However, dealers said the
dollar's fall was broken by the prospect for higher interest rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880810-0330 </DOCNO>
