<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     08-10 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Cool to Sweetened Offer from Batus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc. responded cooly Wednesday
to a sweetened $5 billion friendly takeover bid from Batus Inc.,
and Batus pledged to continue a hostile bid for the insurer if
management refuses to negotiate.
   Batus, which is based in Louisville, boosted its cash offer on
Tuesday for a negotiated merger from $63 a share to $72 a share and
gave management until Aug. 19 to respond.
   Farmers announced it would study the offer with an eye to the
best interests of shareholders, but Treasurer Jerry Faulwell hinted
the higher price was unlikely to overcome management opposition to
the bid from the tobacco and retailing company.
   Among management concerns are that Farmers could end up helping
pay off the loans needed to finance the buyout, and oft-voiced
worries that the insurer might end up sharing costs of tobacco
liability suits against Batus.
   ``I don't know of any reason why our position with regard to
having certain non-economic misgivings about this offer have
changed,'' Faulwell said.
   The $72-a-share offer for a management-sanctioned buyout is
distinct from Batus' $63-a-share tender offer to the owners of
Farmers' stock, submitted in January and scheduled to expire
Thursday.
   Farmers has 68.4 million shares outstanding and employees have
options to buy an additional 1.5 million shares, putting the
potential cost to Batus at $5 billion.
   On Wednesday, Batus, a subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC of
Britain, hinted the tender offer to shareholders would be extended
beyond its Thursday expiration deadline. But the company said it
didn't intend to boost the price in the tender offer beyond $63 a
share.
   As of July 15, holders of 31 percent of Farmers' shares had
offered to sell to Batus, the company said.
   Farmers, with $11 billion in assets, is the nation's
third-largest home and auto insurer and seventh-biggest property
and casualty insurer.
   Batus has retailing operations led by Saks Fifth Avenue stores
and its Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. makes Kool, Viceroy and
other cigarette brands.
   Farmers has been battling Batus in hearings before insurance
regulators in nine states where a takeover needs government
approval.
   Arizona regulators approved a merger and Ohio gave conditional
approval. Oregon, Idaho and Washington have rejected Batus and
California regulators rejected it only to have the decision
overturned by a state judge.
   Decisions or hearings are pending in Texas, Illinois and Kansas,
and the decisions already made in other states are in various
stages of appeal by both companies.
</TEXT>
