<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-10 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0864</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cattle Futures Soar As Cash Market Hits 2-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle futures soared their permitted daily limits Wednesday on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as a surge in meat-packer demand
pushed cash prices for fattened steers to their highest level in
nearly two months.
   On other commodity markets, stock-index futures plunged;
precious metals advanced; grains and soybeans were higher; and
energy futures were mixed.
   Meat-packers in western Kansas and Texas paid up to 69 cents a
pound for fed cattle, apparently to build up their inventories for
an expected upswing in retail beef demand before the Labor Day
weekend.
   It was the highest price paid for cattle since June 17, when
packers bid 70 cents a pound, said Thomas Morgan, president of
Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the price for August
delivery of live cattle settled 1.17 cents higher at 69.42 cents a
pound and the October contract gained 1.50 cents, the maximum
movement allowed by the exchange.
   ``What pushed the (futures) market up was the speculation _ and
speculation is the key word here _ that the (cash) market might go
to 69.50 or 70,'' Morgan said.
   But market bears believe packers now have enough cattle on hand
to satisfy the Labor Day demand and will become less aggressive in
their bidding, he said.
   The live-cattle rally spread to the neighboring feeder cattle
pit, where limit gains also were recorded, and the pork pits. Most
frozen pork belly contracts gained 2 cents a pound, the limit in
that market.
   Pork bellies also were supported by a Chicago Mercantile
Exchange report indicating an upturn in demand for pork bellies,
from which bacon is made.
   Live cattle settled .90 cent to 1.50 cents higher with August at
69.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .85 cent to 1.50 cents
higher with August at 81.22 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent to
1.37 cents higher with August at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .18 cent to 2 cents higher with August at 34.80 cents
a pound.
   Tuesday's boost in the discount rate, the rate the Federal
Reserve charges on short-term loans to member banks, reverberated
through financial futures markets on Wednesday. The Fed raised the
rate half a percentage point to 6.5 percent.
   Treasury bonds for September delivery tumbled 1\ points to 84
31-32 on the Chicago Board of Trade, and the contract for September
delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index plunged 5.35
points to 262.05 on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Those declines, combined with a weaker dollar and the rise in
agricultural commodity prices, spurred buying of precious metals
futures, analysts said. Precious metals are considered relatively
safe investments in a turbulent economy.
   Silver got an additional boost from ideas that a resolution was
near in the 3-week-old miners' strike in Peru, said Bette
Raptopoulos, precious metals analyst in New York with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A scheduled vote Thursday in the House of Representatives on a
proposal for stronger trade sanctions against South Africa gave
platinum futures prices an extra upward shove, Raptopoulos said.
   Platinum for October delivery settled $13.50 higher at $535.80 a
troy ounce on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold was $1.70 to $1.80 higher
with August at $429.20 a troy ounce; silver was 8.2 cents to 8.7
cents higher with September at $6.71 a troy ounce.
   Most crop futures moved higher on the Chicago Board of Trade in
light trading amid nervousness about the Agriculture Department's
upcoming crop production report.
   Grain and soybean futures were led higher by the soybean meal
market, which posted strong gains on rumors that the Soviet Union
was shopping in Argentina for soybean meal pellets, analysts said.
   But traders were unwilling to take large risks ahead of the USDA
crop report, which will be released Thursday after the grain
markets close.
   The report is expected to indicate further deterioration of
drought-stressed crops during July.
   Private analysts' predictions of the USDA crop estimates
averaged out to a 38 percent decline in corn production and a 20
percent drop in soybean production from last year's levels.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 6} cents higher with September at
$3.83\ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents higher with September
at $3.00} a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 5 cents higher with
September at $2.71{ a bushel; soybeans were 8{ cents lower to 9
cents higher with August at $8.64{ a bushel.
   Oil futures prices settled mixed, with prices for future
delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline skidding lower and crude
and heating oil mixed in generally quiet trading.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents lower to 3
cents higher with September at $15.71 a barrel; heating oil was .05
cent to .10 cent higher with September at 44.15 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .58 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
September at 45.57 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
