<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1814EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     08-10 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Tumble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices tumbled Wednesday in active trading,
still reeling from the shock of Tuesday's increase in the discount
rate and catapulting interest rates to their highest levels this
year.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond dropped about 1}
points, or a hefty $17.50 for every $1,000 in face value. Its
yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator
of interest rate trends, surged to 9.36 percent from 9.19 percent
late Tuesday.
   The yield on the key 30-year issue hasn't been that high since
Dec. 10, 1987, when it reached 9.40 percent.
   Short-term Treasury bills were mixed.
   Analysts said bond prices continued to be weakened by the
half-point rise, to 6.5 percent, in the interest rate the Federal
Reserve charges on loans to member U.S. financial institutions.
   ``The market's slashing its wrists again,'' said Ward McCarthy,
chief financial economist at Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Many bond traders are fearful that Tuesday's move could be the
first of a series of hikes in the discount rate, analysts say.
   The Fed said it raised the discount rate to reduce inflationary
pressures on the economy.
   Credit markets are concerned that increased inflation could
erode the value of fixed-income securities such as bonds. A rise in
interest rates, however, tends to send bond prices lower.
   Analysts said bonds were also dragged down by market
expectations that a government auction of $11 billion in 10-year
Treasury notes late Wednesday wouldn't be well received by
investors. On Tuesday, the government's companion auction of
three-year notes had been disappointing.
   The negative expectations for Wednesday's note sale were
confirmed late in the trading session when the results were
announced by the Treasury.
   Yields on the 10-year notes rose to the highest level in nearly
three years. The average yield was 9.27 percent, up from 9.06
percent at the last comparable auction on May 11.
   ``They were pretty dismal,'' said Elizabeth Reiners, a vice
president at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``The demand that everybody
thought was out there pretty much dried up at the auction.''
   On Thursday, in the third and final leg of the quarterly
refunding, the Treasury plans to auction $7 billion in 248-day cash
management bills.
   In the secondary market for Treasury issues Wednesday,
short-term government securities fell by between [ point and 13-32
point, intermediate maturities lost { point to nearly a full point,
and 20-year bonds dropped about 1] points, according to figures
provided by Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, slumped 7.58 to 1,125.97.
   Corporate bonds were slightly lower. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, slipped
0.06 to 281.33.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, declined to
7.20 percent as the discount fell 6 basis points to 6.99 percent.
Yields on six-month bills slipped to 7.77 percent as the discount
was unchanged at 7.39 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to
8.16 percent as the discount advanced 4 basis points to 7.60
percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 8 percent, up from 7 11-16
percent late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
