<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Argentina Pharmaceuticals,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Companies Ask Action Against Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Association
asked the government on Wednesday to take action against Argentine
trade, saying Argentina fails to protect its patents.
   The association says its members have lost $526 million since
1980 because Argentine law denies patent protection to medical
compounds.
   President Reagan announced on July 22 he would restrict imports
worth $200 million from Brazil because of a similar petition.
   Gerald J. Mossinghoff, president of the Pharmaceutical
Manufacturers Association, said: ``Our industry's initiatives on
intellectual property have led to improved protection in (South)
Korea and Taiwan, to constructive negotiations with Chile, and to
ongoing discussions between the United States and Thailand and
Indonesia.
   ``Our goal is not trade retaliation but the recognition and
granting of our intellectual property rights.''
   Worldwide divergences over how to protect ``intellectual
property'' _ patents and copyrights _ have led the administration
to give priority to the issue in current trade negotiations
involving about 100 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
