<DOCNO> AP880810-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Unisys-Convergent     08-10 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unisys-Convergent,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Agrees to Buy Convergent for $350 Million In Cash and Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. has agreed to buy the
computer firm Convergent Inc. for an estimated $350 million in cash
and Unisys stock, company officials said Wednesday.
   The agreement calls for Unisys to pay $7 a share for the 50
million outstanding shares of Convergent in a transaction is
expected to be 45 percent cash and 55 percent stock.
   Unisys spokesman J. Peter Hynes said the company reserved the
right to change the deal to all cash.
   Unisys stock fell 50 cents to $33.37{ a share Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange. Convergent fell 0.063 cent to $3.438 a
share in national over-the-counter trading. The buyout agreement
was announced after the markets closed.
   Under the agreement, which is subject to approval by
stockholders and both company boards of directors, Convergent will
merge with a Unisys subsidiary involved in similar engineering and
manufacturing of networked computer systems.
   Hynes said the acquisition would bring talented computer
engineers and designers into Unisys, significantly strengthening
the company's manufacturing capabilities.
   ``We don't want to be beholden 100 percent to outside
suppliers,'' Hynes said.
   Since Convergent's creation in 1979, Unysis has been one of its
biggest customers, accounting for about 20 percent of the company's
revenue, Convergent Chairman Paul C. Ely said.
   Under the agreement, Ely will join the Unisys management board
reporting to Unisys Chairman and Chief Executive Officer W. Michael
Blumenthal and will oversee the company's networked computer
business.
   Cyril J. Yansouni, Convergent's president, will assume overall
responsibility for the merged Convergent. Both men will remain at
Convergent's current headquarters in San Jose, Calif.
   Convergent had total revenue of $385 million in 1987. Unisys has
projected revenue of more than $10 billion for 1988, making it the
nation's third-largest computer maker after International Business
Machines Corp.
   Unisys projects that its networked computers business will
generate $1.7 billion in revenue in 1988. The combined networked
computer businesses are expected to produce annual revenue of more
than $2 billion.
</TEXT>
