<HEAD>Penske, GE Capital Merge Truck Leasing Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>READING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penske Corp. and GE Capital announced
Wednesday they had completed a previous agreement to form a joint
venture combining the two companies' truck leasing businesses.
   Penske's Reading-based Hertz Truck Leasing will be combined with
GE Capital's Gelco truck leasing business in a joint venture called
Penske Truck Leasing Co. L.P.
   Penske Truck Leasing is the nation's second largest full-service
truck leasing and rental company with more than 54,000 vehicles and
365 service and maintenance facilities.
   The new entity will be owned jointly by the two companies but
will be managed by Penske. It will have combined assets of $1.5
billion and revenue of approximately $750 million, officials said.
The new venture will employ about 5,300 people.
   Roger S. Penske, chairman of Penske Corp., will be chairman and
chief executive officer of the new company.
   Penske Corp. has annual revenue of more than $2 billion.
   GE Capital, with net earning assets in excess of $36 billion, is
one of the nation's largest diversified financial services
companies. Among its activities, GE Capital provides financing for
commercial equipment, real estate, leveraged buyouts, retailers and
the automotive industry.
