<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Auction,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on Three-Year Notes at Three-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on three-year Treasury notes rose in
the government's latest auction to the highest level in three years.
   The average yield was 8.77 percent on Tuesday, up from 8.23
percent at the last auction on May 10.
   It was the highest rate since three-year notes averaged 9.53
percent on Aug. 6, 1985. The notes will carry a coupon interest
rate of 8} percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for
$9,994.80.
   Some $11.1 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling $32.8
billion.
   Tuesday's auction was part of the Treasury's quarterly
refunding. On Wednesday, the government plans to auction $11
billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of $1,000. On
Thursday, it is scheduled to sell $7 billion in 248-day cash
management bills in minimum denominations of $10,000.
